39064|"PREFACE."|FALSE
39064|"I here offer a translation of the third or last part of Hegel’s"|FALSE
39064|"encyclopaedic sketch of philosophy,—the _Philosophy of Mind_. The volume,"|FALSE
39064|"like its subject, stands complete in itself. But it may also be regarded"|FALSE
39064|"as a supplement or continuation of the work begun in my version of his"|FALSE
39064|"_Logic_. I have not ventured upon the _Philosophy of Nature_ which lies"|FALSE
39064|"between these two. That is a province, to penetrate into which would"|FALSE
39064|"require an equipment of learning I make no claim to,—a province, also, of"|FALSE
39064|"which the present-day interest would be largely historical, or at least"|FALSE
39064|"bound up with historical circumstances."|FALSE
39064|"The translation is made from the German text given in the Second Part of"|FALSE
39064|"the Seventh Volume of Hegel’s Collected Works, occasionally corrected by"|FALSE
39064|"comparison with that found in the second and third editions (of 1827 and"|FALSE
39064|"1830) published by the author. I have reproduced only Hegel’s own"|FALSE
39064|"paragraphs, and entirely omitted the _Zusätze_ of the editors. These"|FALSE
39064|"addenda—which are in origin lecture-notes—to the paragraphs are, in the"|FALSE
39064|"text of the Collected Works, given for the first section only. The"|FALSE
39064|"psychological part which they accompany has been barely treated elsewhere"|FALSE
39064|"by Hegel: but a good popular exposition of it will be found in Erdmann’s"|FALSE
39064|"_Psychologische Briefe_. The second section was dealt with at greater"|FALSE
39064|"length by Hegel himself in his _Philosophy of Law_ (1820). The topics of"|FALSE
39064|"the third section are largely covered by his lectures on Art, Religion,"|FALSE
39064|"and History of Philosophy."|FALSE
39064|"I do not conceal from myself that the text offers a hard nut to crack. Yet"|FALSE
39064|"here and there, even through the medium of the translation, I think some"|FALSE
39064|"light cannot fail to come to an earnest student. Occasionally, too, as,"|FALSE
39064|"for instance, in §§ 406, 459, 549, and still more in §§ 552, 573, at the"|FALSE
39064|"close of which might stand the words _Liberavi animam meam_, the writer"|FALSE
39064|"really “lets himself go,” and gives his mind freely on questions where"|FALSE
39064|"speculation comes closely in touch with life."|FALSE
39064|"In the _Five Introductory Essays_ I have tried sometimes to put together,"|FALSE
39064|"and sometimes to provide with collateral elucidation, some points in the"|FALSE
39064|"Mental Philosophy. I shall not attempt to justify the selection of"|FALSE
39064|"subjects for special treatment further than to hope that they form a more"|FALSE
39064|"or less connected group, and to refer for a study of some general"|FALSE
39064|"questions of system and method to my _Prolegomena to the Study of Hegel’s"|FALSE
39064|"Philosophy_ which appear almost simultaneously with this volume."|FALSE
39064|"OXFORD,"|FALSE
