39064|"FIVE INTRODUCTORY ESSAYS IN PSYCHOLOGY AND ETHICS."|FALSE
39064|"Essay I. On The Scope Of A Philosophy Of Mind."|FALSE
39064|"The art of finding titles, and of striking out headings which catch the"|FALSE
39064|"eye or ear, and lead the mind by easy paths of association to the subject"|FALSE
39064|"under exposition, was not one of Hegel’s gifts. A stirring phrase, a vivid"|FALSE
39064|"or picturesque turn of words, he often has. But his lists of contents,"|FALSE
39064|"when they cease to be commonplace, are apt to run into the bizarre and the"|FALSE
39064|"grotesque. Generally, indeed, his rubrics are the old and (as we may be"|FALSE
39064|"tempted to call them) insignificant terms of the text-books. But, in"|FALSE
39064|"Hegel’s use of them, these conventional designations are charged with a"|FALSE
39064|"highly individualised meaning. They may mean more—they may mean less—than"|FALSE
39064|"they habitually pass for: but they unquestionably specify their meaning"|FALSE
39064|"with a unique and almost personal flavour. And this can hardly fail to"|FALSE
39064|"create and to disappoint undue expectations."|FALSE
39064|"(i.) Philosophy and its Parts."|FALSE
39064|"Even the main divisions of his system show this conservatism in"|FALSE
39064|"terminology. The names of the three parts of the Encyclopaedia are, we may"|FALSE
39064|"say, non-significant of their peculiar contents. And that for a good"|FALSE
39064|"reason. What Hegel proposes to give is no novel or special doctrine, but"|FALSE
39064|"the universal philosophy which has passed on from age to age, here"|FALSE
39064|"narrowed and there widened, but still essentially the same. It is"|FALSE
39064|"conscious of its continuity and proud of its identity with the teachings"|FALSE
39064|"of Plato and Aristotle."|FALSE
39064|"The earliest attempts of the Greek philosophers to present philosophy in a"|FALSE
39064|"complete and articulated order—attempts generally attributed to the"|FALSE
39064|"Stoics, the schoolmen of antiquity—made it a tripartite whole. These three"|FALSE
39064|"parts were Logic, Physics, and Ethics. In their entirety they were meant"|FALSE
39064|"to form a cycle of unified knowledge, satisfying the needs of theory as"|FALSE
39064|"well as practice. As time went on, however, the situation changed: and if"|FALSE
39064|"the old names remained, their scope and value suffered many changes. New"|FALSE
39064|"interests and curiosities, due to altered circumstances, brought other"|FALSE
39064|"departments of reality under the focus of investigation besides those"|FALSE
39064|"which had been primarily discussed under the old names. Inquiries became"|FALSE
39064|"more specialised, and each tended to segregate itself from the rest as an"|FALSE
39064|"independent field of science. The result was that in modern times the"|FALSE
39064|"territory still marked by the ancient titles had shrunk to a mere phantom"|FALSE
39064|"of its former bulk. Almost indeed things had come to such a pass that the"|FALSE
39064|"time-honoured figures had sunk into the misery of _rois fainéants_; while"|FALSE
39064|"the real business of knowledge was discharged by the younger and less"|FALSE
39064|"conventional lines of research which the needs and fashions of the time"|FALSE
39064|"had called up. Thus Logic, in the narrow formal sense, was turned into an"|FALSE
39064|"“art” of argumentation and a system of technical rules for the analysis"|FALSE
39064|"and synthesis of academical discussion. Physics or Natural Philosophy"|FALSE
39064|"restricted itself to the elaboration of some metaphysical postulates or"|FALSE
39064|"hypotheses regarding the general modes of physical operation. And Ethics"|FALSE
39064|"came to be a very unpractical discussion of subtleties regarding moral"|FALSE
39064|"faculty and moral standard. Meanwhile a theory of scientific method and of"|FALSE
39064|"the laws governing the growth of intelligence and formation of ideas grew"|FALSE
39064|"up, and left the older logic to perish of formality and inanition. The"|FALSE
39064|"successive departments of physical science, each in turn asserting its"|FALSE
39064|"independence, finally left Natural Philosophy no alternative between"|FALSE
39064|"clinging to its outworn hypotheses and abstract generalities, or"|FALSE
39064|"identifying itself (as Newton in his great book put it) with the"|FALSE
39064|"_Principia Mathematica_ of the physical sciences. Ethics, in its turn, saw"|FALSE
39064|"itself, on one hand, replaced by psychological inquiries into the"|FALSE
39064|"relations between the feelings and the will and the intelligence; while,"|FALSE
39064|"on the other hand, a host of social, historical, economical, and other"|FALSE
39064|"researches cut it off from the real facts of human life, and left it no"|FALSE
39064|"more than the endless debates on the logical and metaphysical issues"|FALSE
39064|"involved in free-will and conscience, duty and merit."|FALSE
39064|"It has sometimes been said that Kant settled this controversy between the"|FALSE
39064|"old departments of philosophy and the new branches of science. And the"|FALSE
39064|"settlement, it is implied, consisted in assigning to the philosopher a"|FALSE
39064|"sort of police and patrol duty in the commonwealth of science. He was to"|FALSE
39064|"see that boundaries were duly respected, and that each science kept"|FALSE
39064|"strictly to its own business. For this purpose each branch of philosophy"|FALSE
39064|"was bound to convert itself into a department of criticism—an examination"|FALSE
39064|"of first principles in the several provinces of reality or experience—with"|FALSE
39064|"a view to get a distinct conception of what they were, and thus define"|FALSE
39064|"exactly the lines on which the structures of more detailed science could"|FALSE
39064|"be put up solidly and safely. This plan offered tempting lines to"|FALSE
39064|"research, and sounded well. But on further reflection there emerge one or"|FALSE
39064|"two difficulties, hard to get over. Paradoxical though it may seem, one"|FALSE
39064|"cannot rightly estimate the capacity and range of foundations, before one"|FALSE
39064|"has had some familiarity with the buildings erected upon them. Thus you"|FALSE
39064|"are involved in a circle: a circle which is probably inevitable, but which"|FALSE
39064|"for that reason it is well to recognise at once. Then—what is only another"|FALSE
39064|"way of saying the same thing—it is impossible to draw an inflexible line"|FALSE
39064|"between premises of principle and conclusions of detail. There is no spot"|FALSE
39064|"at which criticism can stop, and, having done its business well, hand on"|FALSE
39064|"the remaining task to dogmatic system. It was an instinctive feeling of"|FALSE
39064|"this implication of system in what professed only to be criticism which"|FALSE
39064|"led the aged Kant to ignore his own previous professions that he offered"|FALSE
39064|"as yet no system, and when Fichte maintained himself to be erecting the"|FALSE
39064|"fabric for which Kant had prepared the ground, to reply by the"|FALSE
39064|"counter-declaration that the criticism was the system—that “the curtain"|FALSE
39064|"was the picture.”"|FALSE
39064|"The Hegelian philosophy is an attempt to combine criticism with system,"|FALSE
39064|"and thus realise what Kant had at least foretold. It is a system which is"|FALSE
39064|"self-critical, and systematic only through the absoluteness of its"|FALSE
39064|"criticism. In Hegel’s own phrase, it is an immanent and an incessant"|FALSE
39064|"dialectic, which from first to last allows finality to no dogmatic rest,"|FALSE
39064|"but carries out Kant’s description of an Age of Criticism, in which"|FALSE
39064|"nothing, however majestic and sacred its authority, can plead for"|FALSE
39064|"exception from the all-testing _Elenchus_. Then, on the other hand, Hegel"|FALSE
39064|"refuses to restrict philosophy and its branches to anything short of the"|FALSE
39064|"totality. He takes in its full sense that often-used phrase—the Unity of"|FALSE
39064|"Knowledge. Logic becomes the all-embracing research of “first"|FALSE
39064|"principles,”—the principles which regulate physics and ethics. The old"|FALSE
39064|"divisions between logic and metaphysic, between induction and deduction,"|FALSE
39064|"between theory of reasoning and theory of knowledge,—divisions which those"|FALSE
39064|"who most employed them were never able to show the reason and purpose"|FALSE
39064|"of—because indeed they had grown up at various times and by “natural"|FALSE
39064|"selection” through a vast mass of incidents: these are superseded and"|FALSE
39064|"merged in one continuous theory of real knowledge considered under its"|FALSE
39064|"abstract or formal aspect,—of organised and known reality in its"|FALSE
39064|"underlying thought-system. But these first principles were only an"|FALSE
39064|"abstraction from complete reality—the reality which nature has when"|FALSE
39064|"unified by mind—and they presuppose the total from which they are derived."|FALSE
39064|"The realm of pure thought is only the ghost of the Idea—of the unity and"|FALSE
39064|"reality of knowledge, and it must be reindued with its flesh and blood."|FALSE
39064|"The logical world is (in Kantian phrase) only the _possibility_ of Nature"|FALSE
39064|"and Mind. It comes first—because it is a system of First Principles: but"|FALSE
39064|"these first principles could only be elicited by a philosophy which has"|FALSE
39064|"realised the meaning of a mental experience, gathered by interpreting the"|FALSE
39064|"facts of Nature."|FALSE
39064|"Natural Philosophy is no longer—according to Hegel’s view of it—merely a"|FALSE
39064|"scheme of mathematical ground-work. That may be its first step. But its"|FALSE
39064|"scope is a complete unity (which is not a mere aggregate) of the branches"|FALSE
39064|"of natural knowledge, exploring both the inorganic and the organic world."|FALSE
39064|"In dealing with this endless problem, philosophy seems to be baulked by an"|FALSE
39064|"impregnable obstacle to its progress. Every day the advance of"|FALSE
39064|"specialisation renders any comprehensive or synoptic view of the totality"|FALSE
39064|"of science more and more impossible. No doubt we talk readily enough of"|FALSE
39064|"Science. But here, if anywhere, we may say there is no Science, but only"|FALSE
39064|"sciences. The generality of science is a proud fiction or a gorgeous"|FALSE
39064|"dream, variously told and interpreted according to the varying interest"|FALSE
39064|"and proclivity of the scientist. The sciences, or those who specially"|FALSE
39064|"expound them, know of no unity, no philosophy of science. They are content"|FALSE
39064|"to remark that in these days the thing is impossible, and to pick out the"|FALSE
39064|"faults in any attempts in that direction that are made outside their pale."|FALSE
39064|"Unfortunately for this contention, the thing is done by us all, and,"|FALSE
39064|"indeed, has to be done. If not as men of science, yet as men—as human"|FALSE
39064|"beings—we have to put together things and form some total estimate of the"|FALSE
39064|"drift of development, of the unity of nature. To get a notion, not merely"|FALSE
39064|"of the general methods and principles of the sciences, but of their"|FALSE
39064|"results and teachings, and to get this not as a mere lot of fragments, but"|FALSE
39064|"with a systematic unity, is indispensable in some degree for all rational"|FALSE
39064|"life. The life not founded on science is not the life of man. But he will"|FALSE
39064|"not find what he wants in the text-books of the specialist, who is obliged"|FALSE
39064|"to treat his subject, as Plato says, “under the pressure of necessity,”"|FALSE
39064|"and who dare not look on it in its quality “to draw the soul towards"|FALSE
39064|"truth, and to form the philosophic intellect so as to uplift what we now"|FALSE
39064|"unduly keep down(1).” If the philosopher in this province does his work"|FALSE
39064|"but badly, he may plead the novelty of the task to which he comes as a"|FALSE
39064|"pioneer or even an architect. He finds little that he can directly"|FALSE
39064|"utilise. The materials have been gathered and prepared for very special"|FALSE
39064|"aims; and the great aim of science—that human life may be made a higher,"|FALSE
39064|"an ampler, and happier thing,—has hardly been kept in view at all, except"|FALSE
39064|"in its more materialistic aspects. To the philosopher the supreme interest"|FALSE
39064|"of the physical sciences is that man also belongs to the physical"|FALSE
39064|"universe, or that Mind and Matter as we know them are (in Mr. Spencer’s"|FALSE
39064|"language) “at once antithetical and inseparable.” He wants to find the"|FALSE
39064|"place of Man,—but of Man as Mind—in Nature."|FALSE
39064|"If the scope of Natural Philosophy be thus expanded to make it the unity"|FALSE
39064|"and more than the synthetic aggregate of the several physical sciences—to"|FALSE
39064|"make it the whole which surpasses the addition of all their fragments, the"|FALSE
39064|"purpose of Ethics has not less to be deepened and widened. Ethics, under"|FALSE
39064|"that title, Hegel knows not. And for those who cannot recognise anything"|FALSE
39064|"unless it be clearly labelled, it comes natural to record their censure of"|FALSE
39064|"Hegelianism for ignoring or disparaging ethical studies. But if we take"|FALSE
39064|"the word in that wide sense which common usage rather justifies than"|FALSE
39064|"adopts, we may say that the whole philosophy of Mind is a moral"|FALSE
39064|"philosophy. Its subject is the moral as opposed to the physical aspect of"|FALSE
39064|"reality: the inner and ideal life as opposed to the merely external and"|FALSE
39064|"real materials of it: the world of intelligence and of humanity. It"|FALSE
39064|"displays Man in the several stages of that process by which he expresses"|FALSE
39064|"the full meaning of nature, or discharges the burden of that task which is"|FALSE
39064|"implicit in him from the first. It traces the steps of that growth by"|FALSE
39064|"which what was no better than a fragment of nature—an intelligence located"|FALSE
39064|"(as it seemed) in one piece of matter—comes to realise the truth of it and"|FALSE
39064|"of himself. That truth is his ideal and his obligation: but it is"|FALSE
39064|"also—such is the mystery of his birthright—his idea and possession."|FALSE
39064|"He—like the natural universe—is (as the _Logic_ has shown) a principle of"|FALSE
39064|"unification, organisation, idealisation: and his history (in its ideal"|FALSE
39064|"completeness) is the history of the process by which he, the typical man,"|FALSE
39064|"works the fragments of reality (and such mere reality must be always a"|FALSE
39064|"collection of fragments) into the perfect unity of a many-sided character."|FALSE
39064|"Thus the philosophy of mind, beginning with man as a sentient organism,"|FALSE
39064|"the focus in which the universe gets its first dim confused expression"|FALSE
39064|"through mere feeling, shows how he “erects himself above himself” and"|FALSE
39064|"realises what ancient thinkers called his kindred with the divine."|FALSE
39064|"In that total process of the mind’s liberation and self-realisation the"|FALSE
39064|"portion specially called Morals is but one, though a necessary, stage."|FALSE
39064|"There are, said Porphyry and the later Platonists, four degrees in the"|FALSE
39064|"path of perfection and self-accomplishment. And first, there is the career"|FALSE
39064|"of honesty and worldly prudence, which makes the duty of the citizen."|FALSE
39064|"Secondly, there is the progress in purity which casts earthly things"|FALSE
39064|"behind, and reaches the angelic height of passionless serenity. And the"|FALSE
39064|"third step is the divine life which by intellectual energy is turned to"|FALSE
39064|"behold the truth of things. Lastly, in the fourth grade, the mind, free"|FALSE
39064|"and sublime in self-sustaining wisdom, makes itself an “exemplar” of"|FALSE
39064|"virtue, and is even a “father of Gods.” Even so, it may be said, the human"|FALSE
39064|"mind is the subject of a complicated Teleology,—the field ruled by a"|FALSE
39064|"multifarious Ought, psychological, aesthetical, social and religious. To"|FALSE
39064|"adjust their several claims cannot be the object of any science, if"|FALSE
39064|"adjustment means to supply a guide in practice. But it is the purpose of"|FALSE
39064|"such a teleology to show that social requirements and moral duty as"|FALSE
39064|"ordinarily conceived do not exhaust the range of obligation,—of the"|FALSE
39064|"supreme ethical Ought. How that can best be done is however a question of"|FALSE
39064|"some difficulty. For the ends under examination do not fall completely"|FALSE
39064|"into a serial order, nor does one involve others in such a way as to"|FALSE
39064|"destroy their independence. You cannot absolve psychology as if it stood"|FALSE
39064|"independent of ethics or religion, nor can aesthetic considerations merely"|FALSE
39064|"supervene on moral. Still, it may be said, the order followed by Hegel"|FALSE
39064|"seems on the whole liable to fewer objections than others."|FALSE
39064|"Mr. Herbert Spencer, the only English philosopher who has even attempted a"|FALSE
39064|"_System_ of Philosophy, may in this point be compared with Hegel. He also"|FALSE
39064|"begins with a _First Principles_,—a work which, like Hegel’s _Logic_,"|FALSE
39064|"starts by presenting Philosophy as the supreme arbiter between the"|FALSE
39064|"subordinate principles of Religion and Science, which are in it “necessary"|FALSE
39064|"correlatives.” The positive task of philosophy is (with some inconsistency"|FALSE
39064|"or vagueness) presented, in the next place, as a “unification of"|FALSE
39064|"knowledge.” Such a unification has to make explicit the implicit unity of"|FALSE
39064|"known reality: because “every thought involves a whole system of"|FALSE
39064|"thoughts.” And such a programme might again suggest the Logic. But"|FALSE
39064|"unfortunately Mr. Spencer does not (and he has Francis Bacon to justify"|FALSE
39064|"him here) think it worth his while to toil up the weary, but necessary,"|FALSE
39064|"mount of Purgatory which is known to us as Logic. With a naïve realism, he"|FALSE
39064|"builds on Cause and Power, and above all on Force, that “Ultimate of"|FALSE
39064|"Ultimates,” which seems to be, however marvellously, a denizen both of the"|FALSE
39064|"Known and the Unknowable world. In the known world this Ultimate appears"|FALSE
39064|"under two forms, matter and motion, and the problem of science and"|FALSE
39064|"philosophy is to lay down in detail and in general the law of their"|FALSE
39064|"continuous redistribution, of the segregation of motion from matter, and"|FALSE
39064|"the inclusion of motion into matter."|FALSE
39064|"Of this process, which has no beginning and no end,—the rhythm of"|FALSE
39064|"generation and corruption, attraction and repulsion, it may be said that"|FALSE
39064|"it is properly not a first principle of all knowledge, but the general or"|FALSE
39064|"fundamental portion of Natural Philosophy to which Mr. Spencer next"|FALSE
39064|"proceeds. Such a philosophy, however, he gives only in part: viz. as a"|FALSE
39064|"Biology, dealing with organic (and at a further stage and under other"|FALSE
39064|"names, with supra-organic) life. And that the Philosophy of Nature should"|FALSE
39064|"take this form, and carry both the First Principles and the later portions"|FALSE
39064|"of the system with it, as parts of a philosophy of evolution, is what we"|FALSE
39064|"should have expected from the contemporaneous interests of science(2)."|FALSE
39064|"Even a one-sided attempt to give speculative unity to those researches,"|FALSE
39064|"which get—for reasons the scientific specialist seldom asks—the title of"|FALSE
39064|"biological, is however worth noting as a recognition of the necessity of a"|FALSE
39064|"_Natur-philosophie_,—a speculative science of Nature."|FALSE
39064|"The third part of the Hegelian System corresponds to what in the"|FALSE
39064|"_Synthetic Philosophy_ is known as Psychology, Ethics, and Sociology. And"|FALSE
39064|"here Mr. Spencer recognises that something new has turned up. Psychology"|FALSE
39064|"is “unique” as a science: it is a “double science,” and as a whole quite"|FALSE
39064|"_sui generis_. Whether perhaps all these epithets would not, _mutatis"|FALSE
39064|"mutandis_, have to be applied also to Ethics and Sociology, if these are"|FALSE
39064|"to do their full work, he does not say. In what this doubleness consists"|FALSE
39064|"he even finds it somewhat difficult to show. For, as his fundamental"|FALSE
39064|"philosophy does not on this point go beyond noting some pairs of verbal"|FALSE
39064|"antitheses, and has no sense of unity except in the imperfect shape of a"|FALSE
39064|"“relation(3)” between two things which are “antithetical and inseparable,”"|FALSE
39064|"he is perplexed by phrases such as “in” and “out of” consciousness, and"|FALSE
39064|"stumbles over the equivocal use of “inner” to denote both mental (or"|FALSE
39064|"non-spatial) in general, and locally sub-cuticular in special. Still, he"|FALSE
39064|"gets so far as to see that the law of consciousness is that in it neither"|FALSE
39064|"feelings nor relations have independent subsistence, and that the unit of"|FALSE
39064|"mind does not begin till what he calls two feelings are made one. The"|FALSE
39064|"phraseology may be faulty, but it shows an inkling of the _a priori_."|FALSE
39064|"Unfortunately it is apparently forgotten; and the language too often"|FALSE
39064|"reverts into the habit of what he calls the “objective,” i.e. purely"|FALSE
39064|"physical, sciences."|FALSE
39064|"Mr. Spencer’s conception of Psychology restricts it to the more general"|FALSE
39064|"physics of the mind. For its more concrete life he refers us to Sociology."|FALSE
39064|"But his Sociology is yet unfinished: and from the plan of its inception,"|FALSE
39064|"and the imperfect conception of the ends and means of its investigation,"|FALSE
39064|"hardly admits of completion in any systematic sense. To that incipiency is"|FALSE
39064|"no doubt due its excess in historical or anecdotal detail—detail, however,"|FALSE
39064|"too much segregated from its social context, and in general its tendency"|FALSE
39064|"to neglect normal and central theory for incidental and peripheral facts."|FALSE
39064|"Here, too, there is a weakness in First Principles and a love of"|FALSE
39064|"catchwords, which goes along with the fallacy that illustration is proof."|FALSE
39064|"Above all, it is evident that the great fact of religion overhangs Mr."|FALSE
39064|"Spencer with the attraction of an unsolved and unacceptable problem. He"|FALSE
39064|"cannot get the religious ideas of men into co-ordination with their"|FALSE
39064|"scientific, aesthetic, and moral doctrines; and only betrays his sense of"|FALSE
39064|"the high importance of the former by placing them in the forefront of"|FALSE
39064|"inquiry, as due to the inexperience and limitations of the so-called"|FALSE
39064|"primitive man. That is hardly adequate recognition of the religious"|FALSE
39064|"principle: and the defect will make itself seriously felt, should he ever"|FALSE
39064|"come to carry out the further stage of his prospectus dealing with “the"|FALSE
39064|"growth and correlation of language, knowledge, morals, and aesthetics.”"|FALSE
39064|"(ii.) Mind and Morals."|FALSE
39064|"A Mental Philosophy—if we so put what might also be rendered a Spiritual"|FALSE
39064|"Philosophy, or Philosophy of Spirit—may to an English reader suggest"|FALSE
39064|"something much narrower than it actually contains. A Philosophy of the"|FALSE
39064|"Human Mind—if we consult English specimens—would not imply much more than"|FALSE
39064|"a psychology, and probably what is called an inductive psychology. But as"|FALSE
39064|"Hegel understands it, it covers an unexpectedly wide range of topics, the"|FALSE
39064|"whole range from Nature to Spirit. Besides Subjective Mind, which would"|FALSE
39064|"seem on first thoughts to exhaust the topics of psychology, it goes on to"|FALSE
39064|"Mind as Objective, and finally to Absolute mind. And such combinations of"|FALSE
39064|"words may sound either self-contradictory or meaningless."|FALSE
39064|"The first Section deals with the range of what is usually termed"|FALSE
39064|"Psychology. That term indeed is employed by Hegel, in a restricted sense,"|FALSE
39064|"to denote the last of the three sub-sections in the discussion of"|FALSE
39064|"Subjective Mind. The Mind, which is the topic of psychology proper, cannot"|FALSE
39064|"be assumed as a ready-made object, or datum. A Self, a self-consciousness,"|FALSE
39064|"an intelligent and volitional agent, if it be the birthright of man, is a"|FALSE
39064|"birthright which he has to realise for himself, to earn and to make his"|FALSE
39064|"own. To trace the steps by which mind in its stricter acceptation, as will"|FALSE
39064|"and intelligence, emerges from the general animal sensibility which is the"|FALSE
39064|"crowning phase of organic life, and the final problem of biology, is the"|FALSE
39064|"work of two preliminary sub-sections—the first entitled _Anthropology_,"|FALSE
39064|"the second the _Phenomenology of Mind_."|FALSE
39064|"The subject of Anthropology, as Hegel understands it, is the Soul—the raw"|FALSE
39064|"material of consciousness, the basis of all higher mental life. This is a"|FALSE
39064|"borderland, where the ground is still debateable between Nature and Mind:"|FALSE
39064|"it is the region of feeling, where the sensibility has not yet been"|FALSE
39064|"differentiated to intelligence. Soul and body are here, as the phrase"|FALSE
39064|"goes, in communion: the inward life is still imperfectly disengaged from"|FALSE
39064|"its natural co-physical setting. Still one with nature, it submits to"|FALSE
39064|"natural influences and natural vicissitudes: is not as yet master of"|FALSE
39064|"itself, but the half-passive receptacle of a foreign life, of a general"|FALSE
39064|"vitality, of a common soul not yet fully differentiated into"|FALSE
39064|"individuality. But it is awaking to self-activity: it is emerging to"|FALSE
39064|"Consciousness,—to distinguish itself, as aware and conscious, from the"|FALSE
39064|"facts of life and sentiency of which it is aware."|FALSE
39064|"From this region of psychical physiology or physiological psychology,"|FALSE
39064|"Hegel in the second sub-section of his first part takes us to the"|FALSE
39064|"“Phenomenology of Mind,”—to Consciousness. The sentient soul is also"|FALSE
39064|"conscious—but in a looser sense of that word(4): it has feelings, but can"|FALSE
39064|"scarcely be said _itself_ to know that it has them. As consciousness, the"|FALSE
39064|"Soul has come to separate what it is from what it feels. The distinction"|FALSE
39064|"emerges of a subject which is conscious, and an object _of_ which it is"|FALSE
39064|"conscious. And the main thing is obviously the relationship between the"|FALSE
39064|"two, or the Consciousness itself, as tending to distinguish itself alike"|FALSE
39064|"from its subject and its object. Hence, perhaps, may be gathered why it is"|FALSE
39064|"called Phenomenology of Mind. Mind as yet is not yet more than emergent or"|FALSE
39064|"apparent: nor yet self-possessed and self-certified. No longer, however,"|FALSE
39064|"one with the circumambient nature which it feels, it sees itself set"|FALSE
39064|"against it, but only as a passive recipient of it, a _tabula rasa_ on"|FALSE
39064|"which external nature is reflected, or to which phenomena are presented."|FALSE
39064|"No longer, on the other hand, a mere passive instrument of suggestion from"|FALSE
39064|"without, its instinct of life, its _nisus_ of self-assertion is developed,"|FALSE
39064|"through antagonism to a like _nisus_, into the consciousness of self-hood,"|FALSE
39064|"of a Me and Mine as set against a Thee and Thine. But just in proportion"|FALSE
39064|"as it is so developed in opposition to and recognition of other equally"|FALSE
39064|"self-centred selves, it has passed beyond the narrower characteristic of"|FALSE
39064|"Consciousness proper. It is no longer mere intelligent perception or"|FALSE
39064|"reproduction of a world, but it is life, with perception (or apperception)"|FALSE
39064|"of that life. It has returned in a way to its original unity with nature,"|FALSE
39064|"but it is now the sense of its self-hood—the consciousness of itself as"|FALSE
39064|"the focus in which subjective and objective are at one. Or, to put it in"|FALSE
39064|"the language of the great champion of Realism(5), the standpoint of Reason"|FALSE
39064|"or full-grown Mind is this: “The world which appears to us is our percept,"|FALSE
39064|"therefore in us. The real world, out of which we explain the phenomenon,"|FALSE
39064|"is our thought: therefore in us.”"|FALSE
39064|"The third sub-section of the theory of Subjective Mind—the Psychology"|FALSE
39064|"proper—deals with Mind. This is the real, independent Psyché—hence the"|FALSE
39064|"special appropriation of the term Psychology. “The Soul,” says Herbart,"|FALSE
39064|"“no doubt dwells in a body: there are, moreover, corresponding states of"|FALSE
39064|"the one and the other: but nothing corporeal occurs in the Soul, nothing"|FALSE
39064|"purely mental, which we could reckon to our Ego, occurs in the body: the"|FALSE
39064|"affections of the body are no representations of the Ego, and our pleasant"|FALSE
39064|"and unpleasant feelings do not immediately lie in the organic life they"|FALSE
39064|"favour or hinder.” Such a Soul, so conceived, is an intelligent and"|FALSE
39064|"volitional self, a being of intellectual and “active” powers or phenomena:"|FALSE
39064|"it is a Mind. And “Mind,” adds Hegel(6), “is just this elevation above"|FALSE
39064|"Nature and physical modes and above the complication with an external"|FALSE
39064|"object.” Nothing is _external_ to it: it is rather the internalising of"|FALSE
39064|"all externality. In this psychology proper, we are out of any immediate"|FALSE
39064|"connexion with physiology. “Psychology as such,” remarks Herbart, “has its"|FALSE
39064|"questions common to it with Idealism”—with the doctrine that all reality"|FALSE
39064|"is mental reality. It traces, in Hegel’s exposition of it, the steps of"|FALSE
39064|"the way by which mind realises that independence which is its"|FALSE
39064|"characteristic stand-point. On the intellectual side that independence is"|FALSE
39064|"assured in language,—the system of signs by which the intelligence stamps"|FALSE
39064|"external objects as its own, made part of its inner world. A science, some"|FALSE
39064|"one has said, is after all only _une langue bien faite_. So, reversing the"|FALSE
39064|"saying, we may note that a language is an inwardised and mind-appropriated"|FALSE
39064|"world. On the active side, the independence of mind is seen in"|FALSE
39064|"self-enjoyment, in happiness, or self-content, where impulse and volition"|FALSE
39064|"have attained satisfaction in equilibrium, and the soul possesses itself"|FALSE
39064|"in fullness. Such a mind(7), which has made the world its certified"|FALSE
39064|"possession in language, and which enjoys itself in self-possession of"|FALSE
39064|"soul, called happiness, is a free Mind. And that is the highest which"|FALSE
39064|"Subjective Mind can reach."|FALSE
39064|"At this point, perhaps, having rounded off by a liberal sweep the scope of"|FALSE
39064|"psychology, the ordinary mental philosophy would stop. Hegel, instead of"|FALSE
39064|"finishing, now goes on to the field of what he calls Objective Mind. For"|FALSE
39064|"as yet it has been only the story of a preparation, an inward adorning and"|FALSE
39064|"equipment, and we have yet to see what is to come of it in actuality. Or"|FALSE
39064|"rather, we have yet to consider the social forms on which this preparation"|FALSE
39064|"rests. The mind, self-possessed and sure of itself or free, is so only"|FALSE
39064|"through the objective shape which its main development runs parallel with."|FALSE
39064|"An intelligent Will, or a practical reason, was the last word of the"|FALSE
39064|"psychological development. But a reason which is practical, or a volition"|FALSE
39064|"which is intelligent, is realised by action which takes regular shapes,"|FALSE
39064|"and by practice which transforms the world. The theory of Objective Mind"|FALSE
39064|"delineates the new form which nature assumes under the sway of"|FALSE
39064|"intelligence and will. That intellectual world realises itself by"|FALSE
39064|"transforming the physical into a social and political world, the given"|FALSE
39064|"natural conditions of existence into a freely-instituted system of life,"|FALSE
39064|"the primitive struggle of kinds for subsistence into the ordinances of the"|FALSE
39064|"social state. Given man as a being possessed of will and intelligence,"|FALSE
39064|"this inward faculty, whatever be its degree, will try to impress itself on"|FALSE
39064|"nature and to reproduce itself in a legal, a moral, and social world. The"|FALSE
39064|"kingdom of deed replaces, or rises on the foundation of, the kingdom of"|FALSE
39064|"word: and instead of the equilibrium of a well-adjusted soul comes the"|FALSE
39064|"harmonious life of a social organism. We are, in short, in the sphere of"|FALSE
39064|"Ethics and Politics, of Jurisprudence and Morals, of Law and Conscience."|FALSE
39064|"Here,—as always in Hegel’s system—there is a triad of steps. First the"|FALSE
39064|"province of Law or Right. But if we call it Law, we must keep out of sight"|FALSE
39064|"the idea of a special law-giver, of a conscious imposition of laws, above"|FALSE
39064|"all by a political superior. And if we call it Right, we must remember"|FALSE
39064|"that it is neutral, inhuman, abstract right: the right whose principle is"|FALSE
39064|"impartial and impassive uniformity, equality, order;—not moral right, or"|FALSE
39064|"the equity which takes cognisance of circumstances, of personal claims,"|FALSE
39064|"and provides against its own hardness. The intelligent will of Man,"|FALSE
39064|"throwing itself upon the mere gifts of nature as their appointed master,"|FALSE
39064|"creates the world of Property—of things instrumental, and regarded as"|FALSE
39064|"adjectival, to the human personality. But the autonomy of Reason (which is"|FALSE
39064|"latent in the will) carries with it certain consequences. As it acts, it"|FALSE
39064|"also, by its inherent quality of uniformity or universality, enacts for"|FALSE
39064|"itself a law and laws, and creates the realm of formal equality or"|FALSE
39064|"order-giving law. But this is a _mere_ equality: which is not inconsistent"|FALSE
39064|"with what in other respects may be excess of inequality. What one does, if"|FALSE
39064|"it is really to be treated as done, others may or even must do: each act"|FALSE
39064|"creates an expectation of continuance and uniformity of behaviour. The"|FALSE
39064|"doer is bound by it, and others are entitled to do the like. The material"|FALSE
39064|"which the person appropriates creates a system of obligation. Thus is"|FALSE
39064|"constituted—in the natural give and take of rational Wills—in the"|FALSE
39064|"inevitable course of human action and reaction,—a system of rights and"|FALSE
39064|"duties. This law of equality—the basis of justice, and the seed of"|FALSE
39064|"benevolence—is the scaffolding or perhaps rather the rudimentary framework"|FALSE
39064|"of society and moral life. Or it is the bare skeleton which is to be"|FALSE
39064|"clothed upon by the softer and fuller outlines of the social tissues and"|FALSE
39064|"the ethical organs."|FALSE
39064|"And thus the first range of Objective Mind postulates the second, which"|FALSE
39064|"Hegel calls “Morality.” The word is to be taken in its strict sense as a"|FALSE
39064|"protest against the quasi-physical order of law. It is the morality of"|FALSE
39064|"conscience and of the good will, of the inner rectitude of soul and"|FALSE
39064|"purpose, as all-sufficient and supreme. Here is brought out the"|FALSE
39064|"complementary factor in social life: the element of liberty, spontaneity,"|FALSE
39064|"self-consciousness. The motto of mere inward morality (as opposed to the"|FALSE
39064|"spirit of legality) is (in Kant’s words): “There is nothing without"|FALSE
39064|"qualification good, in heaven or earth, but only a good will.” The"|FALSE
39064|"essential condition of goodness is that the action be done with purpose"|FALSE
39064|"and intelligence, and in full persuasion of its goodness by the conscience"|FALSE
39064|"of the agent. The characteristic of Morality thus described is its"|FALSE
39064|"essential inwardness, and the sovereignty of the conscience over all"|FALSE
39064|"heteronomy. Its justification is that it protests against the authority of"|FALSE
39064|"a mere external or objective order, subsisting and ruling in separation"|FALSE
39064|"from the subjectivity. Its defect is the turn it gives to this assertion"|FALSE
39064|"of the rights of subjective conscience: briefly in the circumstance that"|FALSE
39064|"it tends to set up a mere individualism against a mere universalism,"|FALSE
39064|"instead of realising the unity and essential interdependence of the two."|FALSE
39064|"The third sub-section of the theory of Objective Mind describes a state of"|FALSE
39064|"affairs in which this antithesis is explicitly overcome. This is the moral"|FALSE
39064|"life in a social community. Here law and usage prevail and provide the"|FALSE
39064|"fixed permanent scheme of life: but the law and the usage are, in their"|FALSE
39064|"true or ideal conception, only the unforced expression of the mind and"|FALSE
39064|"will of those who live under them. And, on the other hand, the mind and"|FALSE
39064|"will of the individual members of such a community are pervaded and"|FALSE
39064|"animated by its universal spirit. In such a community, and so constituting"|FALSE
39064|"it, the individual is at once free and equal, and that because of the"|FALSE
39064|"spirit of fraternity, which forms its spiritual link. In the world"|FALSE
39064|"supposed to be governed by mere legality the idea of right is exclusively"|FALSE
39064|"prominent; and when that is the case, it may often happen that _summum jus"|FALSE
39064|"summa injuria_. In mere morality, the stress falls exclusively on the idea"|FALSE
39064|"of inward freedom, or the necessity of the harmony of the judgment and the"|FALSE
39064|"will, or the dependence of conduct upon conscience. In the union of the"|FALSE
39064|"two, in the moral community as normally constituted, the mere idea of"|FALSE
39064|"right is replaced, or controlled and modified, by the idea of equity—a"|FALSE
39064|"balance as it were between the two preceding, inasmuch as motive and"|FALSE
39064|"purpose are employed to modify and interpret strict right. But this"|FALSE
39064|"effect—this harmonisation—is brought about by the predominance of a new"|FALSE
39064|"idea—the principle of benevolence,—a principle however which is itself"|FALSE
39064|"modified by the fundamental idea of right or law(8) into a wise or"|FALSE
39064|"regulated kindliness."|FALSE
39064|"But what Hegel chiefly deals with under this head is the interdependence"|FALSE
39064|"of form and content, of social order and personal progress. In the picture"|FALSE
39064|"of an ethical organisation or harmoniously-alive moral community he shows"|FALSE
39064|"us partly the underlying idea which gave room for the antithesis between"|FALSE
39064|"law and conscience, and partly the outlines of the ideal in which that"|FALSE
39064|"conflict becomes only the instrument of progress. This organisation has"|FALSE
39064|"three grades or three typical aspects. These are the Family, Civil"|FALSE
39064|"Society, and the State. The first of these, the Family, must be taken to"|FALSE
39064|"include those primary unities of human life where the natural affinity of"|FALSE
39064|"sex and the natural ties of parentage are the preponderant influence in"|FALSE
39064|"forming and maintaining the social group. This, as it were, is the"|FALSE
39064|"soul-nucleus of social organisation: where the principle of unity is an"|FALSE
39064|"instinct, a feeling, an absorbing solidarity. Next comes what Hegel has"|FALSE
39064|"called Civil Society,—meaning however by civil the antithesis to"|FALSE
39064|"political, the society of those who may be styled _bourgeois_, not"|FALSE
39064|"_citoyens_:—and meaning by society the antithesis to community. There are"|FALSE
39064|"other natural influences binding men together besides those which form the"|FALSE
39064|"close unities of the family, gens, tribe, or clan. Economical needs"|FALSE
39064|"associate human beings within a much larger radius—in ways capable of"|FALSE
39064|"almost indefinite expansion—but also in a way much less intense and deep."|FALSE
39064|"Civil Society is the more or less loosely organised aggregate of such"|FALSE
39064|"associations, which, if, on one hand, they keep human life from stagnating"|FALSE
39064|"in the mere family, on another, accentuate more sharply the tendency to"|FALSE
39064|"competition and the struggle for life. Lastly, in the Political State"|FALSE
39064|"comes the synthesis of family and society. Of the family; in so far as the"|FALSE
39064|"State tends to develope itself on the nature-given unit of the Nation (an"|FALSE
39064|"extended family, supplementing as need arises real descent by fictitious"|FALSE
39064|"incorporations), and has apparently never permanently maintained itself"|FALSE
39064|"except on the basis of a predominant common nationality. Of society; in so"|FALSE
39064|"far as the extension and dispersion of family ties have left free room for"|FALSE
39064|"the differentiation of many other sides of human interest and action, and"|FALSE
39064|"given ground for the full development of individuality. In consequence of"|FALSE
39064|"this, the State (and such a state as Hegel describes is essentially the"|FALSE
39064|"idea or ideal of the modern State)(9) has a certain artificial air about"|FALSE
39064|"it. It can only be maintained by the free action of intelligence: it must"|FALSE
39064|"make its laws public: it must bring to consciousness the principles of its"|FALSE
39064|"constitution, and create agencies for keeping up unity of organisation"|FALSE
39064|"through the several separate provinces or contending social interests,"|FALSE
39064|"each of which is inclined to insist on the right of home mis-rule."|FALSE
39064|"The State—which in its actuality must always be a quasi-national state—is"|FALSE
39064|"thus the supreme unity of Nature and Mind. Its natural basis in land,"|FALSE
39064|"language, blood, and the many ties which spring therefrom, has to be"|FALSE
39064|"constantly raised into an intelligent unity through universal interests."|FALSE
39064|"But the elements of race and of culture have no essential connexion, and"|FALSE
39064|"they perpetually incline to wrench themselves asunder. Blood and judgment"|FALSE
39064|"are for ever at war in the state as in the individual(10): the"|FALSE
39064|"cosmopolitan interest, to which the maxim is _Ubi bene, ibi patria_,"|FALSE
39064|"resists the national, which adopts the patriotic watchword of Hector(11)."|FALSE
39064|"The State however has another source of danger in the very principle that"|FALSE
39064|"gave it birth. It arose through antagonism: it was baptised on the"|FALSE
39064|"battlefield, and it only lives as it is able to assert itself against a"|FALSE
39064|"foreign foe. And this circumstance tends to intensify and even pervert its"|FALSE
39064|"natural basis of nationality:—tends to give the very conception of the"|FALSE
39064|"political a negative and superficial look. But, notwithstanding all these"|FALSE
39064|"drawbacks, the State in its Idea is entitled to the name Hobbes gave"|FALSE
39064|"it,—the Mortal God. Here in a way culminates the obviously objective,—we"|FALSE
39064|"may almost say, visible and tangible—development of Man and Mind. Here it"|FALSE
39064|"attains a certain completeness—a union of reality and of ideality: a"|FALSE
39064|"quasi-immortality, a quasi-universality. What the individual person could"|FALSE
39064|"not do unaided, he can do in the strength of his commonwealth. Much that"|FALSE
39064|"in the solitary was but implicit or potential, is in the State actualised."|FALSE
39064|"But the God of the State is a mortal God. It is but a national and a"|FALSE
39064|"limited mind. To be actual, one must at least begin by restricting"|FALSE
39064|"oneself. Or, rather actuality is rational, but always with a conditioned"|FALSE
39064|"and a relative rationality(12): it is in the realm of action and"|FALSE
39064|"re-action,—in the realm of change and nature. It has warring forces"|FALSE
39064|"outside it,—warring forces inside it. Its unity is never perfect: because"|FALSE
39064|"it never produces a true identity of interests within, or maintains an"|FALSE
39064|"absolute independence without. Thus the true and real State—the State in"|FALSE
39064|"its Idea—the realisation of concrete humanity,—of Mind as the fullness and"|FALSE
39064|"unity of nature—is not reached in any single or historical State: but"|FALSE
39064|"floats away, when we try to seize it, into the endless progress of"|FALSE
39064|"history. Always indeed the State, the historical and objective, points"|FALSE
39064|"beyond itself. It does so first in the succession of times. _Die"|FALSE
39064|"Weltgeschichte ist das Weltgericht._(13) And in that doom of the world the"|FALSE
39064|"eternal blast sweeps along the successive generations of the temporal, one"|FALSE
39064|"expelling another from the stage of time—each because it is inadequate to"|FALSE
39064|"the Idea which it tried to express, and has succumbed to an enemy from"|FALSE
39064|"without because it was not a real and true unity within."|FALSE
39064|"But if temporal flees away before another temporal, it abides in so far as"|FALSE
39064|"it has, however inadequately, given expression and visible reality—as it"|FALSE
39064|"points inward and upward—to the eternal. The earthly state is also the"|FALSE
39064|"city of God; and if the republic of Plato seems to find scant admission"|FALSE
39064|"into the reality of flesh and blood, it stands eternal as a witness in the"|FALSE
39064|"heaven of idea. Behind the fleeting succession of consulates and"|FALSE
39064|"dictatures, of aristocracy and empire, feuds of plebeian with patrician,"|FALSE
39064|"in that apparent anarchy of powers which the so-called Roman constitution"|FALSE
39064|"is to the superficial observer, there is the eternal Rome, one, strong,"|FALSE
39064|"victorious, _semper eadem_: the Rome of Virgil and Justinian, the ghost"|FALSE
39064|"whereof still haunts with memories the seven-hilled city, but which with"|FALSE
39064|"full spiritual presence lives in the law, the literature, the manners of"|FALSE
39064|"the modern world. To find fitter expression for this Absolute Mind than it"|FALSE
39064|"has in the Ethical community—to reach that reality of which the moral"|FALSE
39064|"world is but one-sidedly representative—is the work of Art, Religion, and"|FALSE
39064|"Philosophy. And to deal with these efforts to find the truth and the unity"|FALSE
39064|"of Mind and Nature is the subject of Hegel’s third Section."|FALSE
39064|"(iii.) Religion and Philosophy."|FALSE
39064|"It may be well at this point to guard against a misconception of this"|FALSE
39064|"serial order of exposition(14). As stage is seen to follow stage, the"|FALSE
39064|"historical imagination, which governs our ordinary current of ideas, turns"|FALSE
39064|"the logical dependence into a time-sequence. But it is of course not meant"|FALSE
39064|"that the later stage follows the earlier in history. The later is the more"|FALSE
39064|"real, and therefore the more fundamental. But we can only understand by"|FALSE
39064|"abstracting and then transcending our abstractions, or rather by showing"|FALSE
39064|"how the abstraction implies relations which force us to go further and"|FALSE
39064|"beyond our arbitrary arrest. Each stage therefore either stands to that"|FALSE
39064|"preceding it as an antithesis, which inevitably dogs its steps as an"|FALSE
39064|"accusing spirit, or it is the conjunction of the original thesis with the"|FALSE
39064|"antithesis, in a union which should not be called synthesis because it is"|FALSE
39064|"a closer fusion and true marriage of minds. A truth and reality, though"|FALSE
39064|"fundamental, is only appreciated at its true value and seen in all its"|FALSE
39064|"force where it appears as the reconciliation and reunion of partial and"|FALSE
39064|"opposing points of view. Thus, e.g., the full significance of the State"|FALSE
39064|"does not emerge so long as we view it in isolation as a supposed single"|FALSE
39064|"state, but only as it is seen in the conflict of history, in its actual"|FALSE
39064|"“energy” as a world-power among powers, always pointing beyond itself to a"|FALSE
39064|"something universal which it fain would be, and yet cannot be. Or, again,"|FALSE
39064|"there never was a civil or economic society which existed save under the"|FALSE
39064|"wing of a state, or in one-sided assumption of state powers to itself: and"|FALSE
39064|"a family is no isolated and independent unit belonging to a supposed"|FALSE
39064|"patriarchal age, but was always mixed up with, and in manifold dependence"|FALSE
39064|"upon, political and civil combinations. The true family, indeed, far from"|FALSE
39064|"preceding the state in time, presupposes the political power to give it"|FALSE
39064|"its precise sphere and its social stability: as is well illustrated by"|FALSE
39064|"that typical form of it presented in the Roman state."|FALSE
39064|"So, again, religion does not supervene upon an already existing political"|FALSE
39064|"and moral system and invest it with an additional sanction. The true order"|FALSE
39064|"would be better described as the reverse. The real basis of social life,"|FALSE
39064|"and even of intelligence, is religion. As some thinkers quaintly put it,"|FALSE
39064|"the known rests and lives on the bosom of the Unknowable. But when we say"|FALSE
39064|"that, we must at once guard against a misconception. There are religions"|FALSE
39064|"of all sorts; and some of them which are most heard of in the modern world"|FALSE
39064|"only exist or survive in the shape of a traditional name and venerated"|FALSE
39064|"creed which has lost its power. Nor is a religion necessarily committed to"|FALSE
39064|"a definite conception of a supernatural—of a personal power outside the"|FALSE
39064|"order of Nature. But in all cases, religion is a faith and a theory which"|FALSE
39064|"gives unity to the facts of life, and gives it, not because the unity is"|FALSE
39064|"in detail proved or detected, but because life and experience in their"|FALSE
39064|"deepest reality inexorably demand and evince such a unity to the heart."|FALSE
39064|"The religion of a time is not its nominal creed, but its dominant"|FALSE
39064|"conviction of the meaning of reality, the principle which animates all its"|FALSE
39064|"being and all its striving, the faith it has in the laws of nature and the"|FALSE
39064|"purpose of life. Dimly or clearly felt and perceived, religion has for its"|FALSE
39064|"principle (one cannot well say, its object) not the unknowable, but the"|FALSE
39064|"inner unity of life and knowledge, of act and consciousness, a unity which"|FALSE
39064|"is certified in its every knowledge, but is never fully demonstrable by"|FALSE
39064|"the summation of all its ascertained items. As such a felt and believed"|FALSE
39064|"synthesis of the world and life, religion is the unity which gives"|FALSE
39064|"stability and harmony to the social sphere; just as morality in its turn"|FALSE
39064|"gives a partial and practical realisation to the ideal of religion. But"|FALSE
39064|"religion does not merely establish and sanction morality; it also frees it"|FALSE
39064|"from a certain narrowness it always has, as of the earth. Or, otherwise"|FALSE
39064|"put, morality has to the keener inspection something in it which is more"|FALSE
39064|"than the mere moral injunction at first indicates. Beyond the moral, in"|FALSE
39064|"its stricter sense, as the obligatory duty and the obedience to law, rises"|FALSE
39064|"and expands the beautiful and the good: a beautiful which is"|FALSE
39064|"disinterestedly loved, and a goodness which has thrown off all utilitarian"|FALSE
39064|"relativity, and become a free self-enhancing joy. The true spirit of"|FALSE
39064|"religion sees in the divine judgment not a mere final sanction to human"|FALSE
39064|"morality which has failed of its earthly close, not the re-adjustment of"|FALSE
39064|"social and political judgments in accordance with our more conscientious"|FALSE
