39064|"Essay II. Aims And Methods Of Psychology."|FALSE
39064|"It is not going too far to say that in common estimation psychology has as"|FALSE
39064|"yet hardly reached what Kant has called the steady walk of science—_der"|FALSE
39064|"sichere Gang der Wissenschaft_. To assert this is not, of course, to throw"|FALSE
39064|"any doubts on the importance of the problems, or on the intrinsic value of"|FALSE
39064|"the results, in the studies which have been prosecuted under that name. It"|FALSE
39064|"is only to note the obvious fact that a number of inquiries of somewhat"|FALSE
39064|"discrepant tone, method, and tendency have all at different times covered"|FALSE
39064|"themselves under the common title of psychological, and that the work of"|FALSE
39064|"orientation is as yet incomplete. Such a destiny seems inevitable, when a"|FALSE
39064|"name is coined rather as the title of an unexplored territory, than fixed"|FALSE
39064|"on to describe an accomplished fact."|FALSE
39064|"(i.) Psychology as a Science and as a Part of Philosophy."|FALSE
39064|"The _De Anima_ of Aristotle, gathering up into one the work of Plato and"|FALSE
39064|"his predecessors, may be said to lay the foundation of psychology. But"|FALSE
39064|"even in it, we can already see that there are two elements or aspects"|FALSE
39064|"struggling for mastery: two elements not unrelated or independent, but"|FALSE
39064|"hard to keep fairly and fully in unity. On one hand there is the"|FALSE
39064|"conception of Soul as a part of Nature, as a grade of existence in the"|FALSE
39064|"physical or natural universe,—in the universe of things which suffer"|FALSE
39064|"growth and change, which are never entirely “without matter,” and are"|FALSE
39064|"always attached to or present in body. From this point of view Aristotle"|FALSE
39064|"urged that a sound and realistic psychology must, e.g. in its definition"|FALSE
39064|"of a passion, give the prominent place to its physical (or material)"|FALSE
39064|"expression, and not to its mental form or significance. It must remember,"|FALSE
39064|"he said, that the phenomena or “accidents” are what really throw light on"|FALSE
39064|"the nature or the “substance” of the Soul. On the other hand, there are"|FALSE
39064|"two points to be considered. There is, first of all, the counterpoising"|FALSE
39064|"remark that the conception of Soul as such, as a unity and common"|FALSE
39064|"characteristic, will be determinative of the phenomena or"|FALSE
39064|"“accidents,”—will settle, as it were, what we are to observe and look for,"|FALSE
39064|"and how we are to describe our observations. And by the _conception_ of"|FALSE
39064|"Soul, is meant not _a_ soul, as a thing or agent (subject) which has"|FALSE
39064|"properties attaching to it; but soul, as the generic feature, the"|FALSE
39064|"universal, which is set as a stamp on everything that claims to be"|FALSE
39064|"psychical. In other words, Soul is one, not as a single thing contrasted"|FALSE
39064|"with its attributes, activities, or exercises of force (such single thing"|FALSE
39064|"will be shown by logic to be a metaphysical fiction); but as the unity of"|FALSE
39064|"form and character, the comprehensive and identical feature, which is"|FALSE
39064|"present in all its manifestations and exercises. But there is a second"|FALSE
39064|"consideration. The question is asked by Aristotle whether it is completely"|FALSE
39064|"and strictly accurate to put Soul under the category of natural objects."|FALSE
39064|"There is in it, or of it, perhaps, something, and something essential to"|FALSE
39064|"it, which belongs to the order of the eternal and self-active: something"|FALSE
39064|"which is “form” and “energy” quite unaffected by and separate from"|FALSE
39064|"“matter.” How this is related to the realm of the perishable and"|FALSE
39064|"changeable is a problem on which Aristotle has been often (and with some"|FALSE
39064|"reason) believed to be obscure, if not even inconsistent(21)."|FALSE
39064|"In these divergent elements which come to the fore in Aristotle’s"|FALSE
39064|"treatment we have the appearance of a radical difference of conception and"|FALSE
39064|"purpose as to psychology. He himself does a good deal to keep them both in"|FALSE
39064|"view. But it is evident that here already we have the contrast between a"|FALSE
39064|"purely physical or (in the narrower sense) “scientific” psychology,"|FALSE
39064|"empirical and realistic in treatment, and a more philosophical—what in"|FALSE
39064|"certain quarters would be called a speculative or metaphysical—conception"|FALSE
39064|"of the problem. There is also in Aristotle the antithesis of a popular or"|FALSE
39064|"superficial, and an accurate or analytic, psychology. The former is of a"|FALSE
39064|"certain use in dealing, say, with questions of practical ethics and"|FALSE
39064|"education: the latter is of more strictly scientific interest. Both of"|FALSE
39064|"these distinctions—that between a speculative and an empirical, and that"|FALSE
39064|"between a scientific and a popular treatment—affect the subsequent history"|FALSE
39064|"of the study. Psychology is sometimes understood to mean the results of"|FALSE
39064|"casual observation of our own minds by what is termed introspection, and"|FALSE
39064|"by the interpretation of what we may observe in others. Such observations"|FALSE
39064|"are in the first place carried on under the guidance of distinctions or"|FALSE
39064|"points of view supplied by the names in common use. We interrogate our own"|FALSE
39064|"consciousness as to what facts or relations of facts correspond to the"|FALSE
39064|"terms of our national language. Or we attempt—what is really an"|FALSE
39064|"inexhaustible quest—to get definite divisions between them, and clear-cut"|FALSE
39064|"definitions. Inquiries like these which start from popular distinctions"|FALSE
39064|"fall a long way short of science: and the inquirer will find that"|FALSE
39064|"accidental and essential properties are given in the same handful of"|FALSE
39064|"conclusions. Yet there is always much value in these attempts to get our"|FALSE
39064|"minds cleared: and it is indispensable for all inquiries that all alleged"|FALSE
39064|"or reported facts of mind should be realised and reproduced in our own"|FALSE
39064|"mental experience. And this is especially the case in psychology, just"|FALSE
39064|"because here we cannot get the object outside us, we cannot get or make a"|FALSE
39064|"diagram, and unless we give it reality by re-constructing it,—by"|FALSE
39064|"re-interrogating our own experience, our knowledge of it will be but"|FALSE
39064|"wooden and mechanical. And the term introspection need not be too"|FALSE
39064|"seriously taken: it means much more than watching passively an internal"|FALSE
39064|"drama; and is quite as well describable as mental projection, setting out"|FALSE
39064|"what was within, and so as it were hidden and involved, before ourselves"|FALSE
39064|"in the field of mental vision. Here, as always, the essential point is to"|FALSE
39064|"get ourselves well out of the way of the object observed, and to stand,"|FALSE
39064|"figuratively speaking, quite on one side."|FALSE
39064|"But even at the best, such a popular or empirical psychology has no"|FALSE
39064|"special claim to be ranked as science. It may no doubt be said that at"|FALSE
39064|"least it collects, describes, or notes down facts. But even this is not so"|FALSE
39064|"certain as it seems. Its so-called facts are very largely fictions, or so"|FALSE
39064|"largely interpolated with error, that they cannot be safely used for"|FALSE
39064|"construction. If psychology is to accomplish anything valuable, it must go"|FALSE
39064|"more radically to work. It must—at least in a measure—discard from its"|FALSE
39064|"preliminary view the data of common and current distinctions, and try to"|FALSE
39064|"get at something more primary or ultimate as its starting-point. And this"|FALSE
39064|"it may do in two ways. It may, in the one case, follow the example of the"|FALSE
39064|"physical sciences. In these it is the universal practice to assume that"|FALSE
39064|"the explanation of complex and concrete facts is to be attained by (_a_)"|FALSE
39064|"postulating certain simple elements (which we may call atoms, molecules,"|FALSE
39064|"and perhaps units or monads), which are supposed to be clearly conceivable"|FALSE
39064|"and to justify themselves by intrinsic intelligibility, and by (_b_)"|FALSE
39064|"assuming that these elements are compounded and combined according to laws"|FALSE
39064|"which again are in the last resort self-evident, or such that they seem to"|FALSE
39064|"have an obvious and palpable lucidity. Further, such laws being always"|FALSE
39064|"axioms or plain postulates of mechanics (for these alone possess this"|FALSE
39064|"feature of self-evident intelligibility), they are subject to and invite"|FALSE
39064|"all the aids and refinements of the higher mathematical calculus. What the"|FALSE
39064|"primary and self-explicative bits of psychical reality may be, is a"|FALSE
39064|"further question on which there may be some dispute. They may be, so to"|FALSE
39064|"say, taken in a more physical or in a more metaphysical way: i.e. more as"|FALSE
39064|"units of nerve-function or more as elements of ideative-function. And"|FALSE
39064|"there may be differences as to how far and in what provinces the"|FALSE
39064|"mathematical calculus may be applicable. But, in any case, there will be a"|FALSE
39064|"strong tendency in psychology, worked on this plan, to follow, _mutatis"|FALSE
39064|"mutandis_, and at some distance perhaps, the analogy of material physics."|FALSE
39064|"In both the justification of the postulated units and laws will be their"|FALSE
39064|"ability to describe and systematise the observed phenomena in a uniform"|FALSE
39064|"and consistent way."|FALSE
39064|"The other way in which psychology gets a foundation and ulterior certainty"|FALSE
39064|"is different, and goes deeper. After all, the “scientific” method is only"|FALSE
39064|"a way in which the facts of a given sphere are presented in thoroughgoing"|FALSE
39064|"interconnexion, each reduced to an exact multiple or fraction of some"|FALSE
39064|"other, by an inimitably continued subtraction and addition of an assumed"|FALSE
39064|"homogeneous element, found or assumed to be perfectly imaginable"|FALSE
39064|"(conceivable). But we may also consider the province in relation to the"|FALSE
39064|"whole sphere of reality, may ask what is its place and meaning in the"|FALSE
39064|"whole, what reality is in the end driving at or coming to be, and how far"|FALSE
39064|"this special province contributes to that end. If we do this, we attach"|FALSE
39064|"psychology to philosophy, or, if we prefer so to call it, to metaphysics,"|FALSE
39064|"as in the former way we established it on the principles generally"|FALSE
39064|"received as governing the method of the physical sciences."|FALSE
39064|"This—the relation of psychology to fundamental philosophy—is a question"|FALSE
39064|"which also turns up in dealing with Ethics. There is on the part of those"|FALSE
39064|"engaged in either of these inquiries a certain impatience against the"|FALSE
39064|"intermeddling (which is held to be only muddling) of metaphysics with"|FALSE
39064|"them. It is clear that in a very decided way both psychology and ethics"|FALSE
39064|"can, up to some extent at least, be treated as what is called empirical"|FALSE
39064|"(or, to use the more English phrase, inductive) sciences. On many hands"|FALSE
39064|"they are actually so treated: and not without result. Considering the"|FALSE
39064|"tendency of metaphysical inquiries, it may be urged that it is well to"|FALSE
39064|"avoid preliminary criticism of the current conceptions and beliefs about"|FALSE
39064|"reality which these sciences imply. Yet such beliefs are undoubtedly"|FALSE
39064|"present and effective. Schopenhauer has popularised the principle that the"|FALSE
39064|"pure empiricist is a fiction, that man is a radically metaphysical animal,"|FALSE
39064|"and that he inevitably turns what he receives into a part of a dogmatic"|FALSE
39064|"creed—a conviction how things ought to be. Almost without effort there"|FALSE
39064|"grows up in him, or flows in upon him, a belief and a system of beliefs as"|FALSE
39064|"to the order and values of things. Every judgment, even in logic, rests on"|FALSE
39064|"such an order of truth. He need not be able to formulate his creed: it"|FALSE
39064|"will influence him none the less: nay, his faith will probably seem more a"|FALSE
39064|"part of the solid earth and common reality, the less it has been reduced"|FALSE
39064|"to a determinate creed or to a code of principles. For such formulation"|FALSE
39064|"presupposes doubt and scepticism, which it beats back by mere assertion."|FALSE
39064|"Each human being has such a background of convictions which govern his"|FALSE
39064|"actions and conceptions, and of which it so startles him to suggest the"|FALSE
39064|"possibility of a doubt, that he turns away in dogmatic horror. Such ruling"|FALSE
39064|"ideas vary, from man to man, and from man to woman—if we consider them in"|FALSE
39064|"all their minuteness. But above all they constitute themselves in a"|FALSE
39064|"differently organised system or aggregate according to the social and"|FALSE
39064|"educational stratum to which an individual belongs. Each group, engaged in"|FALSE
39064|"a common task, it may be in the study of a part of nature, is ideally"|FALSE
39064|"bound and obliged by a common language, and special standards of truth and"|FALSE
39064|"reality for its own. Such a group of ideas is what Bacon would have called"|FALSE
39064|"a scientific fetich or _idolum theatri_. A scientific _idolum_ is a"|FALSE
39064|"traditional belief or dogma as to principles, values, and methods, which"|FALSE
39064|"has so thoroughly pervaded the minds of those engaged in a branch of"|FALSE
39064|"inquiry, that they no longer recognise its hypothetical character,—its"|FALSE
39064|"relation of means to the main end of their function."|FALSE
39064|"Such a collected and united theory of reality (it is what Hegel has"|FALSE
39064|"designated the Idea) is what is understood by a natural metaphysic. It has"|FALSE
39064|"nothing necessarily to do with a supersensible or a supernatural, if these"|FALSE
39064|"words mean a ghostly, materialised, but super-finely-materialised nature,"|FALSE
39064|"above and beyond the present. But that there is a persistent tendency to"|FALSE
39064|"conceive the unity and coherence, the theoretic idea of reality, in this"|FALSE
39064|"pseudo-sensuous (i.e. super-sensuous) form, is of course a well-known"|FALSE
39064|"fact. For the present, however, this aberration—this idol of the tribe—may"|FALSE
39064|"be left out of sight. By a metaphysic or fundamental philosophy, is, in"|FALSE
39064|"the present instance, meant a system of first principles—a secular and"|FALSE
39064|"cosmic creed: a belief in ends and values, a belief in truth—again"|FALSE
39064|"premising that the system in question is, for most, a rudely organised and"|FALSE
39064|"almost inarticulate mass of belief and hope, conviction and impression. It"|FALSE
39064|"is, in short, a _natural_ metaphysic: a metaphysic, that is, which has but"|FALSE
39064|"an imperfect coherence, which imperfectly realises both its nature and its"|FALSE
39064|"limits."|FALSE
39064|"In certain parts, however, it is more and better than this crude"|FALSE
39064|"background of belief. Each science—or at least every group of sciences—has"|FALSE
39064|"a more definite system or aggregate of first principles, axioms, and"|FALSE
39064|"conceptions belonging to it. It has, that is,—and here in a much"|FALSE
39064|"distincter way—its special standard of reality, its peculiar forms of"|FALSE
39064|"conceiving things, its distinctions between the actual and the apparent,"|FALSE
39064|"&c. Here again it will probably be found that the scientific specialist is"|FALSE
39064|"hardly conscious that these are principles and concepts: on the contrary,"|FALSE
39064|"they will be supposed self-evident and ultimate facts, foundations of"|FALSE
39064|"being. Instead of being treated as modes of conception, more or less"|FALSE
39064|"justified by their use and their results, these categories will be"|FALSE
39064|"regarded as fundamental facts, essential conditions of all reality. Like"|FALSE
39064|"popular thought in its ingrained categories, the specialist cannot"|FALSE
39064|"understand the possibility of any limitation to his radical ideas of"|FALSE
39064|"reality. To him they are not hypotheses, but principles. The scientific"|FALSE
39064|"specialist may be as convinced of the universal application of his"|FALSE
39064|"peculiar categories, as the Chinese or the Eskimo that his standards are"|FALSE
39064|"natural and final."|FALSE
39064|"Under such metaphysical or extra-empirical presuppositions all"|FALSE
39064|"investigation, whether it be crudely empirical or (in the physical sense)"|FALSE
39064|"scientific, is carried on. And when so carried on, it is said to be"|FALSE
39064|"prosecuted apart from any interference from metaphysic. Such a naïve or"|FALSE
39064|"natural metaphysic, not raised to explicit consciousness, not followed as"|FALSE
39064|"an imposed rule, but governing with the strength of an immanent faith,"|FALSE
39064|"does not count for those who live under it as a metaphysic at all. M."|FALSE
39064|"Jourdain was amazed suddenly to learn he had been speaking prose for forty"|FALSE
39064|"years without knowing it. But in the present case there is something worse"|FALSE
39064|"than amazement sure to be excited by the news. For the critic who thus"|FALSE
39064|"reveals the secrets of the scientist’s heart is pretty sure to go on to"|FALSE
39064|"say that a good deal of this naïve unconscious metaphysic is incoherent,"|FALSE
39064|"contradictory, even bad: that it requires correction, revision, and"|FALSE
39064|"readjustment, and has by criticism to be made one and harmonious. That"|FALSE
39064|"readjustment or criticism which shall eliminate contradiction and produce"|FALSE
39064|"unity, is the aim of the _science_ of metaphysic—the science of the"|FALSE
39064|"meta-physical element in physical knowledge: what Hegel has chosen to call"|FALSE
39064|"the Science of Logic (in the wide sense of the term). This higher Logic,"|FALSE
39064|"this _science_ of metaphysic, is the process to revise and harmonise in"|FALSE
39064|"systematic completeness the imperfect or misleading and partial estimates"|FALSE
39064|"of reality which are to be found in popular and scientific thought."|FALSE
39064|"In the case of the run of physical sciences this revision is less"|FALSE
39064|"necessary; and for no very recondite reason. Every science by its very"|FALSE
39064|"nature deals with a special, a limited topic. It is confined to a part or"|FALSE
39064|"aspect of reality. Its propositions are not complete truths; they apply to"|FALSE
39064|"an artificial world, to a part expressly cut off from the concrete"|FALSE
39064|"reality. Its principles are generally cut according to their"|FALSE
39064|"cloth,—according to the range in which they apply. The only danger that"|FALSE
39064|"can well arise is if these categories are transplanted without due"|FALSE
39064|"reservations, and made of universal application, i.e. if the scientist"|FALSE
39064|"elects on his speciality to pronounce _de omnibus rebus_. But in the case"|FALSE
39064|"of psychology and ethics the harmlessness of natural metaphysics will be"|FALSE
39064|"less certain. Here a general human or universal interest is almost an"|FALSE
39064|"inevitable coefficient: especially if they really rise to the full sweep"|FALSE
39064|"of the subject. For as such they both seem to deal not with a part of"|FALSE
39064|"reality, but with the very centre and purpose of all reality. In them we"|FALSE
39064|"are not dealing with topics of secondary interest, but with the very heart"|FALSE
39064|"of the human problem. Here the questions of reality and ideals, of unity"|FALSE
39064|"and diversity, and of the evaluation of existence, come distinctly to the"|FALSE
39064|"fore. If psychology is to answer the question, What am I? and ethics the"|FALSE
39064|"question, What ought I to do? they can hardly work without some formulated"|FALSE
39064|"creed of metaphysical character, without some preliminary criticisms of"|FALSE
39064|"current first principles."|FALSE
39064|"(ii.) Herbart."|FALSE
39064|"The German thinker, who has given perhaps the most fruitful stimulus to"|FALSE
39064|"the scientific study of psychology in modern times—Johann Friedrich"|FALSE
39064|"Herbart—is after all essentially a philosopher, and not a mere scientist,"|FALSE
39064|"even in his psychology. His psychological inquiry, that is, stands in"|FALSE
39064|"intimate connexion with the last questions of all intelligence, with"|FALSE
39064|"metaphysics and ethics. The business of philosophy, says Herbart, is to"|FALSE
39064|"touch up and finish off conceptions (_Bearbeitung der Begriffe_)(22). It"|FALSE
39064|"finds, as it supervenes upon the unphilosophical world, that mere and pure"|FALSE
39064|"facts (if there ever are or were such purisms) have been enveloped in a"|FALSE
39064|"cloud of theory, have been construed into some form of unity, but have"|FALSE
39064|"been imperfectly, inadequately construed: and that the existing concepts"|FALSE
39064|"in current use need to be corrected, supplemented and readjusted. It has,"|FALSE
39064|"accordingly, for its work to “reconcile experience with itself(23),” and"|FALSE
39064|"to elicit “the hidden pre-suppositions without which the fact of"|FALSE
39064|"experience is unthinkable.” Psychology, then, as a branch of this"|FALSE
39064|"philosophic enterprise, has to readjust the facts discovered in inner"|FALSE
39064|"experience. For mere uncritical experience or merely empirical knowledge"|FALSE
39064|"only offers _problems_; it suggests gaps, which indeed further reflection"|FALSE
39064|"serves at first only to deepen into contradictions. Such a psychology is"|FALSE
39064|"“speculative”: i.e. it is not content to accept the mere given, but goes"|FALSE
39064|"forward and backward to find something that will make the fact"|FALSE
39064|"intelligible. It employs totally different methods from the"|FALSE
39064|"“classification, induction, analogy” familiar to the logic of the"|FALSE
39064|"empirical sciences. Its “principles,” therefore, are not given facts: but"|FALSE
39064|"facts which have been manipulated and adjusted so as to lose their"|FALSE
39064|"self-contradictory quality: they are facts “reduced,” by introducing the"|FALSE
39064|"omitted relationships which they postulate if they are to be true and"|FALSE
39064|"self-consistent(24). While it is far from rejecting or ignoring"|FALSE
39064|"experience, therefore, psychology cannot strictly be said to build upon it"|FALSE
39064|"alone. It uses experimental fact as an unfinished datum,—or it sees in"|FALSE
39064|"experience a torso which betrays its imperfection, and suggests"|FALSE
39064|"completing."|FALSE
39064|"The starting-point, it may be said, of Herbart’s psychology is a question"|FALSE
39064|"which to the ordinary psychologist (and to the so-called scientific"|FALSE
39064|"psychologist) has a secondary, if it have any interest. It was, he says,"|FALSE
39064|"the problem of Personality, the problem of the Self or Ego, which first"|FALSE
39064|"led to his characteristic conception of psychological method. “My first"|FALSE
39064|"discovery,” he tells us(25), “was that the Self was neither primitive nor"|FALSE
39064|"independent, but must be the most dependent and most conditioned thing one"|FALSE
39064|"can imagine. The second was that the elementary ideas of an intelligent"|FALSE
39064|"being, if they were ever to reach the pitch of self-consciousness, must be"|FALSE
39064|"either all, or at least in part, opposed to each other, and that they must"|FALSE
39064|"check or block one another in consequence of this opposition. Though held"|FALSE
39064|"in check, however, these ideas were not to be supposed lost: they subsist"|FALSE
39064|"as endeavours or tendencies to return into the position of actual idea, as"|FALSE
39064|"soon as the check became, for any reason, either in whole or in part"|FALSE
39064|"inoperative. This check could and must be calculated, and thus it was"|FALSE
39064|"clear that psychology required a mathematical as well as a metaphysical"|FALSE
39064|"foundation.”"|FALSE
39064|"The place of the conception of the Ego in Kant’s and Fichte’s theory of"|FALSE
39064|"knowledge is well known. Equally well known is Kant’s treatment of the"|FALSE
39064|"soul-reality or soul-substance in his examination of Rational Psychology."|FALSE
39064|"Whereas the (logical) unity of consciousness, or “synthetic unity of"|FALSE
39064|"apperception,” is assumed as a fundamental starting-point in explanation"|FALSE
39064|"of our objective judgments, or of our knowledge of objective existence,"|FALSE
39064|"its real (as opposed to its formal) foundation in a “substantial” soul is"|FALSE
39064|"set aside as an illegitimate interpretation of, or inference from, the"|FALSE
39064|"facts of inner experience. The belief in the separate unity and"|FALSE
39064|"persistence of the soul, said Kant, is not a scientifically-warranted"|FALSE
39064|"conclusion. Its true place is as an ineffaceable postulate of the faith"|FALSE
39064|"which inspires human life and action. Herbart did not rest content with"|FALSE
39064|"either of these—as he believed—dogmatic assumptions of his master. He did"|FALSE
39064|"not fall in cheerfully with the idealism which seemed ready to dispense"|FALSE
39064|"with a soul, or which justified its acceptance of empirical reality by"|FALSE
39064|"referring to the fundamental unity of the function of judgment. With a"|FALSE
39064|"strong bent towards fully-differentiated and individualised experience"|FALSE
39064|"Herbart conjoined a conviction of the need of logical analysis to prevent"|FALSE
39064|"us being carried away by the first-come and inadequate generalities. The"|FALSE
39064|"Ego which, in its extremest abstraction, he found defined as the unity of"|FALSE
39064|"subject and object, did not seem to him to offer the proper guarantees of"|FALSE
39064|"reality: it was itself a problem, full of contradictions, waiting for"|FALSE
39064|"solution. On the other hand, the real Ego, or self of concrete experience,"|FALSE
39064|"is very much more than this logical abstract, and differs widely from"|FALSE
39064|"individual to individual, and apparently from time to time even in the"|FALSE
39064|"same individual. Our self, of which we talk so fluently, as one and the"|FALSE
39064|"self-same—how far does it really possess the continuity and identity with"|FALSE
39064|"which we credit it? Does it not rather seem to be an ideal which we"|FALSE
39064|"gradually form and set before ourselves as the standard for measuring our"|FALSE
39064|"attainments of the moment,—the perfect fulfilment of that oneness of being"|FALSE
39064|"and purpose and knowledge which we never reach? Sometimes even it seems no"|FALSE
39064|"better than a name which we move along the varying phenomena of our inner"|FALSE
39064|"life, at one time identifying it with the power which has gained the"|FALSE
39064|"victory in a moral struggle, at another with that which has been"|FALSE
39064|"defeated(26), according as the attitude of the moment makes us throw now"|FALSE
39064|"one, now another, aspect of mental activity in the foreground."|FALSE
39064|"The other—or logical Ego—the mere identity of subject and object,—when"|FALSE
39064|"taken in its utter abstractness and simplicity, shrivels up to something"|FALSE
39064|"very small indeed—to a something which is little better than nothing. The"|FALSE
39064|"mere _I_ which is not contra-distinguished by a _Thou_ and a _He_—which is"|FALSE
39064|"without all definiteness of predication (the I=I of Fichte and"|FALSE
39064|"Schelling)—is only as it were a point of being cut off from all its"|FALSE
39064|"connexions in reality, and treated as if it were or could be entirely"|FALSE
39064|"independent. It is an identity in which subject and object have not yet"|FALSE
39064|"appeared: it is not a real I, though we may still retain the name. It"|FALSE
39064|"is—as Hegel’s _Logic_ will tell us—exactly definable as Being, which is as"|FALSE
39064|"yet Nothing: the impossible edge of abstraction on which we try—and in"|FALSE
39064|"vain—to steady ourselves at the initial point of thought. And to reach or"|FALSE
39064|"stand at that intangible, ungraspable point, which slips away as we"|FALSE
39064|"approach, and transmutes itself as we hold it, is not the natural"|FALSE
39064|"beginning, but the result of introspection and reflection on the concrete"|FALSE
39064|"self. But with this aspect of the question we are not now concerned."|FALSE
39064|"That the unity of the Self as an intelligent and moral being, that the Ego"|FALSE
39064|"of self-consciousness was an ideal and a product of development, was what"|FALSE
39064|"Herbart soon became convinced of. The unity of Self is even as given in"|FALSE
39064|"mature experience an imperfect fact. It is a fact, that is, which does not"|FALSE
39064|"come up to what it promised, and which requires to be supplemented, or"|FALSE
39064|"philosophically justified. Here and everywhere the custom of life carries"|FALSE
39064|"us over gaps which yawn deep to the eye of philosophic reflection: even"|FALSE
39064|"though accident and illness force them not unfrequently even upon the"|FALSE
39064|"blindest. To trace the process of unification towards this unity—to trace,"|FALSE
39064|"if you like, even the formation of the concept of such unity, as a"|FALSE
39064|"governing and guiding principle in life and conduct, comes to be the"|FALSE
39064|"problem of the psychologist, in the largest sense of that problem. From"|FALSE
39064|"Soul (_Seele_) to Mind or Spirit (_Geist_) is for Herbart, as for Hegel,"|FALSE
39064|"the course of psychology(27). The growth and development of mind, the"|FALSE
39064|"formation of a self, the realisation of a personality, is for both the"|FALSE
39064|"theme which psychology has to expound. And Herbart, not less than Hegel,"|FALSE
39064|"had to bear the censure that such a conception of mental reality as a"|FALSE
39064|"growth would destroy personality(28)."|FALSE
39064|"But with so much common in the general plan, the two thinkers differ"|FALSE
39064|"profoundly in their special mode of carrying out the task. Or, rather,"|FALSE
39064|"they turn their strength on different departments of the whole. Herbart’s"|FALSE
39064|"great practical interest had been the theory of education: “paedagogic” is"|FALSE
39064|"the subject of his first important writings. The inner history of"|FALSE
39064|"ideas—the processes which are based on the interaction of elements in the"|FALSE
39064|"individual soul—are what he specially traces. Hegel’s interests, on the"|FALSE
39064|"contrary, are more towards the greater process, the unities of historical"|FALSE
39064|"life, and the correlations of the powers of art, religion, and philosophy"|FALSE
39064|"that work therein. He turns to the macrocosm, almost as naturally as"|FALSE
39064|"Herbart does to the microcosm. Thus, even in Ethics, while Herbart gives a"|FALSE
39064|"delicate analysis of the distinct aspects or elements in the Ethical"|FALSE
39064|"idea,—the diverse headings under which the disinterested spectator within"|FALSE
39064|"the breast measures with purely aesthetic eye his approach to unity and"|FALSE
39064|"strength of purpose, Hegel seems to hurry away from the field of moral"|FALSE
39064|"sense or conscience to throw himself on the social and political"|FALSE
39064|"organisation of the moral life. The General Paedagogic of Herbart has its"|FALSE
39064|"pendant in Hegel’s Philosophy of Law and of History."|FALSE
39064|"At an early period Herbart had become impressed with the necessity of"|FALSE
39064|"applying mathematics to psychology(29). To the usual objection, that"|FALSE
39064|"psychical facts do not admit of measurement, he had a ready reply. We can"|FALSE
39064|"calculate even on hypothetical assumptions: indeed, could we measure, we"|FALSE
39064|"should scarcely take the trouble to calculate(30). To calculate (i.e. to"|FALSE
39064|"deduce mathematically) is to perform a general experiment, and to perform"|FALSE
39064|"it in the medium where there is least likelihood of error or disturbance."|FALSE
39064|"There may be anomalies enough apparent in the mental life: there may be"|FALSE
39064|"the great anomalies of Genius and of Freedom of Will; but the Newton and"|FALSE
39064|"the Kepler of psychology will show by calculation on assumed conditions of"|FALSE
39064|"psychic nature that these aberrations can be explained by mechanical laws."|FALSE
39064|"“The human Soul is no puppet-theatre: our wishes and resolutions are no"|FALSE
39064|"marionettes: no juggler stands behind; but our true and proper life lies"|FALSE
39064|"in our volition, and this life has its rule not outside, but in itself: it"|FALSE
39064|"has its own purely mental rule, by no means borrowed from the material"|FALSE
39064|"world. But this rule is in it sure and fixed; and on account of this its"|FALSE
39064|"fixed quality it has more similarity to (what is otherwise heterogeneous)"|FALSE
39064|"the laws of impact and pressure than to the marvels of an alleged"|FALSE
39064|"inexplicable freedom(31).”"|FALSE
39064|"Psychology then deals with a real, which exhibits phenomena analogous in"|FALSE
39064|"several respects to those discussed by statics and mechanics. Its"|FALSE
39064|"foundation is a statics and mechanics of the Soul,—as this real is called."|FALSE
39064|"We begin by presupposing as the ultimate reality, underlying the"|FALSE
39064|"factitious and generally imperfect unity of self-consciousness and mind,"|FALSE
39064|"an essential and primary unity—the unity of an absolutely simple or"|FALSE
39064|"individual point of being—a real point which amongst other points asserts"|FALSE
39064|"itself, maintains itself. It has a character of its own, but that"|FALSE
39064|"character it only shows in and through a development conditioned by"|FALSE
39064|"external influences. The specific nature of the soul-reality is to be"|FALSE
39064|"representative, to produce, or manifest itself in, ideas"|FALSE
39064|"(_Vorstellungen_). But the character only emerges into actuality in the"|FALSE
39064|"conflict of the soul-atom with other ultimate realities in the"|FALSE
39064|"congregation of things. A soul _per se_ or isolated is not possessed of"|FALSE
39064|"ideas. It is merely blank, undeveloped, formal unity, of which nothing can"|FALSE
39064|"be said. But like other realities it defines and characterises itself by"|FALSE
39064|"antithesis, by resistance: it shows what it is by its behaviour in the"|FALSE
39064|"struggle for existence. It acts in self-defence: and its peculiar style or"|FALSE
39064|"weapon of self-defence is an idea or representation. The way the Soul"|FALSE
39064|"maintains itself is by turning the assailant into an idea(32): and each"|FALSE
39064|"idea is therefore a _Selbsterhaltung_ of the Soul. The Soul is thus"|FALSE
39064|"enriched—to appearance or incidentally: and the assailant is annexed. In"|FALSE
39064|"this way the one Soul may develop or evolve or express an innumerable"|FALSE
39064|"variety of ideas: for in response to whatever it meets, the living and"|FALSE
39064|"active Soul ideates, or gives rise to a representation. Thus, while the"|FALSE
39064|"soul is one, its ideas or representations are many. Taken separately, they"|FALSE
39064|"each express the psychic self-conservation. But brought in relation with"|FALSE
39064|"each other, as so many acts or self-affirmations of the one soul, they"|FALSE
39064|"behave as forces, and tend to thwart or check each other. It is as forces,"|FALSE
39064|"as reciprocally arresting or fostering each other, that ideas are objects"|FALSE
39064|"of science. When a representation is thus held in check, it is reduced to"|FALSE
39064|"a mere endeavour or active tendency to represent. Thus there arises a"|FALSE
39064|"distinction between representations proper, and those imperfect states or"|FALSE
39064|"acts which are partly or wholly held in abeyance. But the latent phase of"|FALSE
39064|"an idea is as essential to a thorough understanding of it as what appears."|FALSE
39064|"It is the great blunder of empirical psychology to ignore what is sunk"|FALSE
39064|"below the surface of consciousness. And to Herbart consciousness is not"|FALSE
39064|"the condition but rather the product of ideas, which are primarily forces."|FALSE
39064|"But representations are not merely in opposition,—impinging and resisting."|FALSE
39064|"The same reason which makes them resist, viz. that they are or would fain"|FALSE
39064|"be acts of the one soul, but are more or less incompatible, leads them in"|FALSE
39064|"other circumstances to form combinations with each other. These"|FALSE
39064|"combinations are of two sorts. They are, first, complications, or"|FALSE
39064|"“complexions”: a number of ideas combine by quasi-addition and"|FALSE
39064|"juxtaposition to form a total. Second, there is fusion: ideas presenting"|FALSE
39064|"certain degrees of contrast enter into a union where the parts are no"|FALSE
39064|"longer separately perceptible. It is easy to see how the problems of"|FALSE
39064|"psychology now assume the form of a statics and mechanics of the mind."|FALSE
39064|"Quantitative data are to be sought in the strength of each separate single"|FALSE
39064|"idea, and the degree in which two or more ideas block each other: in the"|FALSE
39064|"degree of combination between ideas, and the number of ideas in a"|FALSE
39064|"combination: and in the terms of relation between the members of a series"|FALSE
39064|"of ideas. A statical theory has to show the conditions required for what"|FALSE
39064|"we may call the ideal state of equilibrium of the “idea-forces”: to"|FALSE
39064|"determine, that is, the ultimate degree of obscuration suffered by any two"|FALSE
39064|"ideas of different strength, and the conditions of their permanent"|FALSE
39064|"combination or fusion. A mechanics of the mind will, on the contrary, deal"|FALSE
39064|"with the rate at which these processes are brought about, the velocity"|FALSE
39064|"with which in the movement of mind ideas are obscured or reawakened, &c."|FALSE
39064|"It is fortunately unnecessary, here, to go further into details. What"|FALSE
39064|"Herbart proposes is not a method for the mathematical measurement of"|FALSE
39064|"psychic facts: it is a theory of mechanics and statics specially adapted"|FALSE
39064|"to the peculiarities of psychical phenomena, where the forces are given"|FALSE
39064|"with no sine or cosine, where instead of gravitation we have the constant"|FALSE
39064|"effort (as it were elasticity) of each idea to revert to its unchecked"|FALSE
39064|"state. He claims—in short—practically to be a Kepler and Newton of the"|FALSE
39064|"mind, and in so doing to justify the vague professions of more than one"|FALSE
39064|"writer on mind—above all, perhaps of David Hume, who goes beyond mere"|FALSE
39064|"professions—to make mental science follow the example of physics. And a"|FALSE
39064|"main argument in favour of his enterprise is the declaration of Kant that"|FALSE
39064|"no body of knowledge can claim to be a science except in such proportion"|FALSE
39064|"as it is mathematical. And the peculiarity of this enterprise is that"|FALSE
39064|"self-consciousness, the Ego, is not allowed to interfere with the free"|FALSE
39064|"play of psychic forces. The Ego is—psychologically—the result, the"|FALSE
39064|"product, and the varying product of that play. The play of forces is no"|FALSE
39064|"doubt a unity: but its unity lies not in the synthesis of consciousness,"|FALSE
39064|"but in the essential unity of Soul. And Soul is in its essence neither"|FALSE
39064|"consciousness, nor self-consciousness, nor mind: but something on the"|FALSE
39064|"basis of whose unity these are built up and developed(33). The mere"|FALSE
39064|"“representation” does not include the further supervenience of"|FALSE
39064|"consciousness: it represents, but it is not as yet necessary that we"|FALSE
39064|"should also be conscious that there is representation. It is, in the"|FALSE
39064|"phrase of Leibniz, perception: but not apperception. It is mere"|FALSE
39064|"straight-out, not as yet reflected, representation. Gradually there"|FALSE
39064|"emerges through the operation of mechanical psychics a nucleus, a floating"|FALSE
39064|"unity, a fixed or definite central aggregate."|FALSE
39064|"The suggestion of mathematical method has been taken up by subsequent"|FALSE
39064|"inquirers (as it was pursued even before Herbart’s time), but not in the"|FALSE
39064|"sense he meant. Experimentation has now taken a prominent place in"|FALSE
39064|"psychology. But in proportion as it has done so, psychology has lost its"|FALSE
39064|"native character, and thrown itself into the arms of physiology. What"|FALSE
39064|"Herbart calculated were actions and reactions of idea-forces: what the"|FALSE
39064|"modern experimental school proposes to measure are to a large extent the"|FALSE
39064|"velocities of certain physiological processes, the numerical specification"|FALSE
39064|"of certain facts. Such ascertainments are unquestionably useful; as"|FALSE
39064|"numerical precision is in other departments. But, taken in themselves,"|FALSE
39064|"they do not carry us one bit further on the way to science. As"|FALSE
39064|"experiments, further,—to note a point discussed elsewhere(34)—their value"|FALSE
39064|"depends on the point of view, on the theory which has led to them, on the"|FALSE
39064|"value of the general scheme for which they are intended to provide a"|FALSE
39064|"special new determination. In many cases they serve to give a vivid"|FALSE
39064|"reality to what was veiled under a general phrase. The truth looks so much"|FALSE
39064|"more real when it is put in figures: as the size of a huge tree when set"|FALSE
39064|"against a rock; or as when Milton bodies out his fallen angel by setting"|FALSE
39064|"forth the ratio between his spear and the tallest Norway pine. But until"|FALSE
39064|"the general relationship between soul and body is more clearly formulated,"|FALSE
39064|"such statistics will have but a value of curiosity."|FALSE
39064|"(iii.) The Faculty-Psychology and its Critics."|FALSE
39064|"What Herbart (as well as Hegel) finds perpetual ground for objecting to is"|FALSE
39064|"the talk about mental faculties. This objection is part of a general"|FALSE
39064|"characteristic of all the higher philosophy; and the recurrence of it"|FALSE
39064|"gives an illustration of how hard it is for any class of men to see"|FALSE
39064|"themselves as others see them. If there be anything the vulgar believe to"|FALSE
39064|"be true of philosophy, it is that it deals in distant and abstruse"|FALSE
39064|"generalities, that it neglects the shades of individuality and reality,"|FALSE
39064|"and launches out into unsubstantial general ideas. But it would be easy to"|FALSE
39064|"gather from the great thinkers an anthology of passages in which they hold"|FALSE
39064|"it forth as the great work of philosophy to rescue our conceptions from"|FALSE
39064|"the indefiniteness and generality of popular conception, and to give them"|FALSE
39064|"real, as opposed to a merely nominal, individuality."|FALSE
39064|"The Wolffian school, which Herbart (not less than Kant) found in"|FALSE
39064|"possession of the field, and which in Germany may be taken to represent"|FALSE
39064|"only a slight variant of the half-and-half attitude of vulgar thought, was"|FALSE
39064|"entrenched in the psychology of faculties. Empirical psychology, said"|FALSE
39064|"Wolff(35), tells the number and character of the soul’s faculties:"|FALSE
39064|"rational psychology will tell what they “properly” are, and how they"|FALSE
39064|"subsist in soul. It is assumed that there are general receptacles or"|FALSE
39064|"tendencies of mental operation which in course of time get filled or"|FALSE
39064|"qualified in a certain way: and that when this question is disposed of, it"|FALSE
39064|"still remains to fix on the metaphysical bases of these facts."|FALSE
39064|"That a doctrine of faculties should fix itself in psychology is not so"|FALSE
39064|"wonderful. In the non-psychical world objects are easily discriminated in"|FALSE
39064|"space, and the individual thing lasts through a time. But a phase of mind"|FALSE
39064|"is as such fleeting and indeterminate: its individual features which come"|FALSE
39064|"from its “object” tend soon to vanish in memory: all freshness of definite"|FALSE
39064|"characters wears off, and there is left behind only a vague “recept” of"|FALSE
39064|"the one and same in many, a sort of hypostatised representative, faint but"|FALSE
39064|"persistent, of what in experience was an ever-varying succession. We"|FALSE
39064|"generalise here as elsewhere: but elsewhere the many singulars remain to"|FALSE
39064|"confront us more effectually. But in Mind the immense variety of real"|FALSE
39064|"imagination, memory, judgment is forgotten, and the name in each case"|FALSE
39064|"reduced to a meagre abstract. Thus the identity in character and"|FALSE
39064|"operation, having been cut off from the changing elements in its real"|FALSE
39064|"action, is transmuted into a substantial somewhat, a subsistent faculty."|FALSE
39064|"The relationship of one to another of the powers thus by abstraction and"|FALSE
39064|"fancy created becomes a problem of considerable moment, their causal"|FALSE
39064|"relations in particular: till in the end they stand outside and"|FALSE
39064|"independent of each other, engaged, as Herbart says, in a veritable"|FALSE
39064|"_bellum omnium contra omnes_."|FALSE
39064|"But this hypostatising of faculties becomes a source of still further"|FALSE
39064|"difficulties when it is taken in connexion with the hypostasis of the Soul"|FALSE
39064|"or Self or Ego. To Aristotle the Soul in its general aspect is Energy or"|FALSE
39064|"Essence; and its individual phases are energies. But in the hands of the"|FALSE
39064|"untrained these conceptions came to be considerably displaced. Essence or"|FALSE
39064|"Substance came to be understood (as may be seen in Locke, and still more"|FALSE
39064|"in loose talk) as a something,—a substratum,—or peculiar nature—(of which"|FALSE
39064|"_in itself_ nothing further could be said(36) but which notwithstanding"|FALSE
39064|"was permanent and perhaps imperishable): this something subsistent"|FALSE
39064|"exhibited certain properties or activities. There thus arose, on one hand,"|FALSE
39064|"the Soul-thing,—a substance misunderstood and sensualised with a"|FALSE
39064|"supernatural sensuousness,—a denizen of the transcendental or even of the"|FALSE
39064|"transcendent world: and, on the other hand, stood the actual"|FALSE
39064|"manifestations, the several exhibitions of this force, the assignable and"|FALSE
39064|"describable psychic facts. We are accordingly brought before the problem"|FALSE
39064|"of how this one substance or essence stands to the several entities or"|FALSE
39064|"hypostases known as faculties. And we still have in the rear the further"|FALSE
39064|"problem of how these abstract entities stand to the real and concrete"|FALSE
39064|"single acts and states of soul and mind."|FALSE
39064|"This hypostatising of faculties, and this distinction of the “Substantial”"|FALSE
39064|"soul from its “accidentia” or phenomena, had grown—through the"|FALSE
39064|"materialistic proclivities of popular conception—from the indications"|FALSE
39064|"found in Aristotle. It attained its climax, perhaps in the Wolffian school"|FALSE
39064|"in Germany, but it has been the resort of superficial psychology in all"|FALSE
39064|"ages. For while it, on one hand, seemed to save the substantial Soul on"|FALSE
39064|"whose incorruptibility great issues were believed to hinge, it held out,"|FALSE
39064|"on the other, an open hand to the experimental inquirer, whom it bade"|FALSE
39064|"freely to search amongst the phenomena. But if it was the refuge of"|FALSE
39064|"pusillanimity, it was also the perpetual object of censure from all the"|FALSE
39064|"greater and bolder spirits. Thus, the psychology of Hobbes may be hasty"|FALSE
39064|"and crude, but it is at least animated by a belief that the mental life is"|FALSE
39064|"continuous, and not cut off by abrupt divisions severing the mental"|FALSE
39064|"faculties. The “image” (according to his materialistically coloured"|FALSE
39064|"psychology) which, when it is a strong motion, is called sense, passes, as"|FALSE
39064|"it becomes weaker or decays, into imagination, and gives rise, by its"|FALSE
39064|"various complications and associations with others, to reminiscence,"|FALSE
39064|"experience, expectation. Similarly, the voluntary motion which is an"|FALSE
39064|"effect or a phase of imagination, beginning at first in small"|FALSE
39064|"motions—called by themselves “endeavours,” and in relation to their cause"|FALSE
39064|"“appetites” or “desires(37)”—leads on cumulatively to Will, which is the"|FALSE
39064|"“last appetite in deliberating.” Spinoza, his contemporary, speaks in the"|FALSE
39064|"same strain(38). “Faculties of intellect, desire, love, &c., are either"|FALSE
39064|"utterly fictitious, or nothing but metaphysical entities, or universals"|FALSE
39064|"which we are in the habit of forming from particulars. Will and intellect"|FALSE
39064|"are thus supposed to stand to this or that idea, this or that volition, in"|FALSE
39064|"the same way as stoniness to this or that stone, or as man to Peter or"|FALSE
39064|"Paul.” They are supposed to be a general something which gets defined and"|FALSE
39064|"detached. But, in the mind, or in the cogitant soul, there are no such"|FALSE
39064|"things. There are only ideas: and by an “idea” we are to understand not an"|FALSE
39064|"image on the retina or in the brain, not a “dumb something, like a"|FALSE
39064|"painting on a panel(39),” but a mode of thinking, or even the act of"|FALSE
39064|"intellection itself. The ideas _are_ the mind: mind does not _have_ ideas."|FALSE
39064|"Further, every “idea,” as such, “involves affirmation or negation,”—is not"|FALSE
39064|"an image, but an act of judgment—contains, as we should say, an implicit"|FALSE
39064|"reference to actuality,—a reference which in volition is made explicit."|FALSE
39064|"Thus (concludes the corollary of Eth. ii. 49) “Will and Intellect are one"|FALSE
39064|"and the same.” But in any case the “faculties” as such are no better than"|FALSE
39064|"_entia rationis_ (i.e. auxiliary modes of representing facts)."|FALSE
39064|"Leibniz speaks no less distinctly and sanely in this direction. “True"|FALSE
39064|"powers are never mere possibilities: they are always tendency and action.”"|FALSE
39064|"The “Monad”—that is the quasi-intelligent unit of existence,—is"|FALSE
39064|"essentially activity, and its actions are perceptions and appetitions,"|FALSE
39064|"i.e. tendencies to pass from one perceptive state or act to another. It is"|FALSE
39064|"out of the variety, the complication, and relations of these miniature or"|FALSE
39064|"little perceptions and appetitions, that the conspicuous phenomena of"|FALSE
39064|"consciousness are to be explained, and not by supposing them due to one or"|FALSE
39064|"other faculty. The soul is a unity, a self-developing unity, a unity which"|FALSE
39064|"at each stage of its existence shows itself in a perception or idea,—each"|FALSE
39064|"such perception however being, to repeat the oft quoted phrase, _plein de"|FALSE
39064|"l’avenir et chargé du passé_:—each, in other words, is not stationary, but"|FALSE
39064|"active and urgent, a progressive force, as well as a representative"|FALSE
39064|"element. Above all, Leibniz has the view that the soul gives rise to all"|FALSE
39064|"its ideas from itself: that its life is its own production, not a mere"|FALSE
39064|"inheritance of ideas which it has from birth and nature, nor a mere"|FALSE
39064|"importation into an empty room from without, but a necessary result of its"|FALSE
39064|"own constitution acting in necessary (predetermined) reciprocity and"|FALSE
39064|"harmony with the rest of the universe."|FALSE
39064|"But Hobbes, Spinoza, and Leibniz, were most attentively heard in the"|FALSE
39064|"passages where they favoured or combatted the dominant social and"|FALSE
39064|"theological prepossessions. Their glimpses of truer insight and even their"|FALSE
39064|"palpable contributions in the line of a true psychology were ignored or"|FALSE
39064|"forgotten. More attention, perhaps, was attracted by an attempt of a very"|FALSE
39064|"different style. This was the system of Condillac, who, as Hegel says (p."|FALSE
39064|"61), made an unmistakable attempt to show the necessary interconnexion of"|FALSE
39064|"the several modes of mental activity. In his _Traité des Sensations_"|FALSE
39064|"(1754), following on his _Essai sur l’origine des connaissances humaines_"|FALSE
39064|"(1746), he tried to carry out systematically the deduction or derivation"|FALSE
39064|"of all our ideas from sense, or to trace the filiation of all our"|FALSE
39064|"faculties from sensation. Given a mind with no other power than"|FALSE
39064|"sensibility, the problem is to show how it acquires all its other"|FALSE
39064|"faculties. Let us then suppose a sentient animal to which is offered a"|FALSE
39064|"single sensation, or one sensation standing out above the others. In such"|FALSE
39064|"circumstances the sensation “becomes” (_devient_) attention: or a"|FALSE
39064|"sensation “is” (_est_) attention, either because it is alone, or because"|FALSE
39064|"it is more lively than all the rest. Again: before such a being, let us"|FALSE
39064|"set two sensations: to perceive or feel (_apercevoir ou sentir_) the two"|FALSE
39064|"sensations is the same thing (_c’est la même chose_). If one of the"|FALSE
39064|"sensations is not present, but a sensation made already, then to perceive"|FALSE
39064|"it is memory. Memory, then, is only “transformed sensation” (_sensation"|FALSE
39064|"transformée_). Further, suppose we attend to both ideas, this is “the same"|FALSE
39064|"thing” as to compare them. And to compare them we must see difference or"|FALSE
39064|"resemblance. This is judgment. “Thus sensation becomes successively"|FALSE
39064|"attention, comparison, judgment.” And—by further steps of the equating"|FALSE
39064|"process—it appears that sensation again “becomes” an act of reflection."|FALSE
39064|"And the same may be said of imagination and reasoning: all are transformed"|FALSE
39064|"sensations."|FALSE
39064|"If this is so with the intelligence, it is equally the case with the Will."|FALSE
39064|"To feel and not feel well or ill is impossible. Coupling then this feeling"|FALSE
39064|"of pleasure or pain with the sensation and its transformations, we get the"|FALSE
39064|"series of phases ranging from desire, to passion, hope, will. “Desire is"|FALSE
39064|"only the action of the same faculties as are attributed to the"|FALSE
39064|"understanding.” A lively desire is a passion: a desire, accompanied with a"|FALSE
39064|"belief that nothing stands in its way, is a volition. But combine these"|FALSE
39064|"affective with the intellectual processes already noticed, and you have"|FALSE
39064|"thinking (_penser_)(40). Thus thought in its entirety is, only and always,"|FALSE
39064|"transformed sensation."|FALSE
39064|"Something not unlike this, though scarcely so simply and directly"|FALSE
39064|"doctrinaire, is familiar to us in some English psychology, notably James"|FALSE
39064|"Mill’s(41). Taken in their literal baldness, these identifications may"|FALSE
39064|"sound strained,—or trifling. But if we look beyond the words, we can"|FALSE
39064|"detect a genuine instinct for maintaining and displaying the unity and"|FALSE
39064|"continuity of mental life through all its modifications,—coupled"|FALSE
39064|"unfortunately with a bias sometimes in favour of reducing higher or more"|FALSE
39064|"complex states of mind to a mere prolongation of lower and beggarly"|FALSE
39064|"rudiments. But otherwise such analyses are useful as aids against the"|FALSE
39064|"tendency of inert thought to take every name in this department as a"|FALSE
39064|"distinguishable reality: the tendency to part will from thought—ideas from"|FALSE
39064|"emotion—and even imagination from reason, as if either could be what it"|FALSE
39064|"professed without the other."|FALSE
39064|"(iv.) Methods and Problems of Psychology."|FALSE
39064|"The difficulties of modern psychology perhaps lie in other directions, but"|FALSE
39064|"they are not less worth guarding against. They proceed mainly from failure"|FALSE
39064|"or inability to grasp the central problem of psychology, and a disposition"|FALSE
39064|"to let the pen (if it be a book on the subject) wander freely through the"|FALSE
39064|"almost illimitable range of instance, illustration, and application."|FALSE
39064|"Though it is true that the proper study of mankind is man, it is hardly"|FALSE
39064|"possible to say what might not be brought under this head. _Homo sum,"|FALSE
39064|"nihil a me alienum puto_, it might be urged. Placed in a sort of middle"|FALSE
39064|"ground between physiology (summing up all the results of physical science)"|FALSE
39064|"and general history (including the contributions of all the branches of"|FALSE
39064|"sociology), the psychologist need not want for material. He can wander"|FALSE
39064|"into ethics, aesthetic, and logic, into epistemology and metaphysics. And"|FALSE
39064|"it cannot be said with any conviction that he is actually trespassing, so"|FALSE
39064|"long as the ground remains so ill-fenced and vaguely enclosed. A desultory"|FALSE
