39064|"In conclusion, there are one or two points which seem of cardinal"|FALSE
39064|"importance for the progress of psychology. (1) Its difference from the"|FALSE
39064|"physical sciences has to be set out: in other words, the peculiarity of"|FALSE
39064|"psychical fact. It will not do merely to say that experience marks out"|FALSE
39064|"these boundaries with sufficient clearness. On the contrary, the terms"|FALSE
39064|"consciousness, feeling, mind, &c., are evidently to many psychologists"|FALSE
39064|"mere names. In particular, the habits of physical research when introduced"|FALSE
39064|"into mental study lead to a good deal of what can only be called"|FALSE
39064|"mythology. (2) There should be a clearer recognition of the problem of the"|FALSE
39064|"relations of mental unity to mental elements. But to get that, a more"|FALSE
39064|"thorough logical and metaphysical preparation is needed than is usually"|FALSE
39064|"supposed necessary. The doctrine of identity and necessity, of universal"|FALSE
39064|"and individual, has to be faced, however tedious. (3) The distinction"|FALSE
39064|"between first-grade and second-grade elements and factors in the mental"|FALSE
39064|"life has to be realised. The mere idea as presentative or immediate has to"|FALSE
39064|"be kept clear of the more logico-reflective, or normative ideas, which"|FALSE
39064|"belong to judgment and reasoning. And the number of these grades in mental"|FALSE
39064|"development seems endless. (4) But, also, a separation is required—were it"|FALSE
39064|"but temporary—between what may be called principles, and what is detail."|FALSE
39064|"At present, in psychology, “principles” is a word almost without meaning."|FALSE
39064|"A complete all-explaining system is of course impossible at present and"|FALSE
39064|"may always be so. Yet if an effort of thought could be concentrated on"|FALSE
39064|"cardinal issues, and less padding of conventional and traditional detail"|FALSE
39064|"were foisted in, much might thereby be done to make detailed research"|FALSE
39064|"fruitful. (5) And finally, perhaps, if psychology be a philosophical"|FALSE
39064|"study, some hint as to its purpose and problem would be desirable. If it"|FALSE
39064|"is only an abstract branch of science, of course, no such hint is in"|FALSE
39064|"place."|FALSE
39064|"Essay III. On Some Psychological Aspects Of Ethics."|FALSE
39064|"Allusion has already been made to the question of the boundaries between"|FALSE
39064|"logic and psychology, between logic and ethics, ethics and psychology, and"|FALSE
39064|"psychology and epistemology. Each of these occasionally comes to cover"|FALSE
39064|"ground that seems more appropriate to the others. Logic is sometimes"|FALSE
39064|"restricted to denote the study of the conditions of derivative knowledge,"|FALSE
