39064|"Accordingly mesmerism and its allied manifestations were generally"|FALSE
39064|"abandoned to the bohemians of science, and to investigators with dogmatic"|FALSE
39064|"bias. It was still employed as a treatment for certain ailments: and"|FALSE
39064|"philosophers, as different as Fichte and Schopenhauer(86), watched its"|FALSE
39064|"fate with attention. But the herd of professional scientists fought shy of"|FALSE
39064|"it. The experiments of Braid at Manchester in 1841 gradually helped to"|FALSE
39064|"give research into the subject a new character. Under the name of"|FALSE
39064|"Hypnotism (or, rather at first Neuro-hypnotism) he described the phenomena"|FALSE
39064|"of the magnetic sleep (induced through prolonged staring at a bright"|FALSE
39064|"object), such as abnormal rigidity of body, perverted sensibility, and the"|FALSE
39064|"remarkable obedience of the subject to the command or suggestions of the"|FALSE
39064|"operator. Thirty years afterwards, the matter became an object of"|FALSE
39064|"considerable experimental and theoretic work in France, at the rival"|FALSE
39064|"schools of Paris and Nancy; and the question, mainly under the title of"|FALSE
39064|"hypnotism, though the older name is still occasionally heard, has been for"|FALSE
39064|"several years brought prominently under public notice."|FALSE
39064|"It cannot be said that the net results of these observations and"|FALSE
39064|"hypotheses are of a very definitive character. While a large amount of"|FALSE
39064|"controversy has been waged on the comparative importance of the several"|FALSE
39064|"methods and instruments by which the hypnotic or mesmeric trance may be"|FALSE
39064|"induced, and a scarcely less wide range of divergence prevails with regard"|FALSE
39064|"to the physiological and pathological conditions in connexion with which"|FALSE
39064|"it has been most conspicuously manifested, there has been less anxiety"|FALSE
39064|"shown to determine its precise psychical nature, or its significance in"|FALSE
39064|"mental development. And yet the better understanding of these aspects may"|FALSE
39064|"throw light on several points connected with primitive religion and the"|FALSE
39064|"history of early civilisation, indeed over the whole range of what is"|FALSE
39064|"called _Völkerpsychologie_. Indeed this is one of the points which may be"|FALSE
39064|"said to emerge out of the confusion of dispute. Phenomena at least"|FALSE
39064|"analogous to those styled hypnotic have a wide range in the"|FALSE
39064|"anthropological sphere(87): and the proper characters which belong to them"|FALSE
39064|"will only be caught by an observer who examines them in the widest variety"|FALSE
39064|"of examples. Another feature which has been put in prominence is what has"|FALSE
39064|"been called “psychological automatism.” And in this name two points seem"|FALSE
39064|"to deserve note. The first is the spontaneous and as it were mechanical"|FALSE
39064|"consecution of mental states in the soul whence the interfering effect of"|FALSE
39064|"voluntary consciousness has been removed. And the second is the unfailing"|FALSE
39064|"or accurate regularity, so contrary to the hesitating and uncertain"|FALSE
39064|"procedure of our conscious and reasoned action, which so often is seen in"|FALSE
39064|"the unreflecting and unreasoned movements. To this invariable sequence of"|FALSE
39064|"psychical movement the superior control and direction by the intelligent"|FALSE
39064|"self has to adapt itself, just as it respects the order of physical laws."|FALSE
39064|"But, perhaps, the chief conclusion to be derived from hypnotic experience"|FALSE
39064|"is the value of suggestion or suggestibility. Even cool thinkers like Kant"|FALSE
39064|"have recognised how much mere mental control has to do with bodily"|FALSE
39064|"state,—how each of us, in this way, is often for good or for ill his own"|FALSE
39064|"physician. An idea is a force, and is only inactive in so far as it is"|FALSE
39064|"held in check by other ideas. “There is no such thing as hypnotism,” says"|FALSE
39064|"one: “there are only different degrees of suggestibility.” This may be to"|FALSE
39064|"exaggerate: yet it serves to impress the comparatively secondary character"|FALSE
39064|"of many of the circumstances on which the specially mesmeric or hypnotic"|FALSE
39064|"experimentalist is apt to lay exclusive stress. The methods may probably"|FALSE
39064|"vary according to circumstances. But the essence of them all is to get the"|FALSE
39064|"patient out of the general frame and system of ideas and perceptions in"|FALSE
39064|"which his ordinary individuality is encased. Considering how for all of us"|FALSE
39064|"the reality of concrete life is bound up with our visual perceptions, how"|FALSE
39064|"largely our sanity depends upon the spatial idea, and how that depends on"|FALSE
39064|"free ocular range, we can understand that darkness and temporary loss of"|FALSE
39064|"vision are powerful auxiliaries in the hypnotic process, as in magical and"|FALSE
39064|"superstitious rites. But a great deal short of this may serve to establish"|FALSE
39064|"influence. The mind of the majority of human beings, but especially of the"|FALSE
39064|"young, may be compared to a vacant seat waiting for some one to fill it."|FALSE
39064|"In Hegel’s view hypnotic phenomena produce a kind of temporary and"|FALSE
39064|"artificial atavism. Mechanical or chemical means, or morbid conditions of"|FALSE
39064|"body, may cause even for the intelligent adult a relapse into states of"|FALSE
39064|"mind closely resembling those exhibited by the primitive or the infantile"|FALSE
39064|"sensibility. The intelligent personality, where powers are bound up with"|FALSE
39064|"limitations and operate through a chain of means and ends, is reduced to"|FALSE
39064|"its primitively undifferentiated condition. Not that it is restored to its"|FALSE
39064|"infantile simplicity; but that all subsequent acquirements operate only as"|FALSE
39064|"a concentrated individuality, or mass of will and character, released from"|FALSE
39064|"the control of the self-possessed mind, and invested (by the latter’s"|FALSE
39064|"withdrawal) with a new quasi-personality of their own. With the loss of"|FALSE
39064|"the world of outward things, there may go, it is supposed, a clearer"|FALSE
39064|"perception of the inward and particularly of the organic life. The Soul"|FALSE
39064|"contains the form of unity which other experiences had impressed upon it:"|FALSE
39064|"but this form avails in its subterranean existence where it creates a sort"|FALSE
39064|"of inner self. And this inner self is no longer, like the embodied self of"|FALSE
39064|"ordinary consciousness, an intelligence served by organs, and proceeding"|FALSE
39064|"by induction and inference. Its knowledge is not mediated or carried along"|FALSE
