39064|"synthesis and analysis, by gradual idealisation, the organised totality of"|FALSE
39064|"its intellectual world. The somnambulist and the clairvoyant see without"|FALSE
39064|"eyes, and carry their vision directly into regions where the waking"|FALSE
39064|"consciousness of orderly intelligence cannot enter. But that region is not"|FALSE
39064|"the world of our higher ideas,—of art, religion, and philosophy. It is"|FALSE
39064|"still the sensitivity—that realm of sensitivity which is ordinarily"|FALSE
39064|"covered by unconsciousness. Such sensitive clairvoyants may, as it were,"|FALSE
39064|"hear themselves growing; they may discern the hidden quivers and pulses of"|FALSE
39064|"blood and tissue, the seats of secret pain and all the unrevealed workings"|FALSE
39064|"in the dark chambers of the flesh. But always their vision seems confined"|FALSE
39064|"to that region, and will fall short of the world of light and ideal truth."|FALSE
39064|"It is towards the nature-bond of sensitive solidarity with earth, and"|FALSE
39064|"flowers, and trees, the life that “rolls through all things,” not towards"|FALSE
39064|"the spiritual unity which broods over the world and “impels all thinking"|FALSE
39064|"things,” that these immersions in the selfless universe lead us."|FALSE
39064|"What Hegel chiefly sees in these phenomena is their indication, even on"|FALSE
39064|"the natural side of man, of that ideality of the material, which it is the"|FALSE
39064|"work of intelligence to produce in the more spiritual life, in the"|FALSE
39064|"fully-developed mind. The latter is the supreme over-soul, that Absolute"|FALSE
39064|"Mind which in our highest moods, aesthetic and religious, we approximate"|FALSE
39064|"to. But mind, as it tends towards the higher end to “merge itself in"|FALSE
39064|"light,” to identify itself yet not wholly lost, but retained, in the"|FALSE
39064|"fullness of undivided intellectual being, so at the lower end it springs"|FALSE
39064|"from a natural and underlying unity, the immense solidarity of"|FALSE
39064|"nether-soul, the great Soul of Nature—the “Substance” which is to be"|FALSE
39064|"raised into the “Subject” which is true divinity. Between these two"|FALSE
39064|"unities, the nature-given nether-soul and the spirit-won over-soul, lies"|FALSE
39064|"the conscious life of man: a process of differentiation which narrows and"|FALSE
39064|"of redintegration which enlarges,—which alternately builds up an isolated"|FALSE
39064|"personality and dissolves it in a common intelligence and sympathy. It is"|FALSE
39064|"because mental or tacit “suggestion”(88) (i.e. will-influence exercised"|FALSE
39064|"without word or sign, or other sensible mode of connexion),"|FALSE
39064|"thought-transference, or thought-reading (which is more than dexterous"|FALSE
39064|"apprehension of delicate muscular signs), exteriorisation or transposition"|FALSE
39064|"of sensibility into objects primarily non-sensitive, clairvoyance (i.e."|FALSE
39064|"the power of describing, as if from direct perception, objects or events"|FALSE
39064|"removed in space beyond the recognised limits of sensation), and"|FALSE
39064|"somnambulism, so far as it implies lucid vision with sealed eyes,—it is"|FALSE
39064|"because these things seem to show the essential ideality of matter, that"|FALSE
39064|"Hegel is interested in them. The ordinary conditions of consciousness and"|FALSE
39064|"even of practical life in society are a derivative and secondary state; a"|FALSE
39064|"product of processes of individualism, which however are never completed,"|FALSE
39064|"and leave a large margin for idealising intelligence to fulfil. From a"|FALSE
39064|"state which is not yet personality to a state which is more than can be"|FALSE
39064|"described as personality—lies the mental movement. So Fichte, too, had"|FALSE
39064|"regarded the power of the somnambulist as laying open a world underlying"|FALSE
39064|"the development of egoity and self-consciousness(89): “the merely sensuous"|FALSE
39064|"man is still in somnambulism,” only a somnambulism of waking hours: “the"|FALSE
39064|"true waking is the life in God, to be free in him, all else is sleep and"|FALSE
39064|"dream.” “Egoity,” he adds, “is a merely _formal_ principle, utterly, and"|FALSE
39064|"never qualitative (i.e. the essence and universal force).” For"|FALSE
39064|"Schopenhauer, too, the experiences of animal magnetism had seemed to prove"|FALSE
39064|"the absolute supernatural power of the radical will in its superiority to"|FALSE
