39064|"the reality of the metaphysical which is at the basis of all conscious"|FALSE
39064|"divisions."|FALSE
39064|"(iii.) The Development of Inner Freedom."|FALSE
39064|"The result of the first range in the process of psycho-genesis was to make"|FALSE
39064|"the body a sign and utterance of the Soul, with a fixed and determinate"|FALSE
39064|"type. The “anthropological process” has defined and settled the mere"|FALSE
39064|"general sentiency of soul into an individualised shape, a localised and"|FALSE
39064|"limited self, a bundle of habits. It has made the soul an Ego or self: a"|FALSE
39064|"power which looks out upon the world as a spectator, lifted above"|FALSE
39064|"immanence in the general tide of being, but only so lifted because it has"|FALSE
39064|"made itself one in the world of objects, a thing among things. The Mind"|FALSE
39064|"has reached the point of view of reflection. Instead of a general"|FALSE
39064|"identifiability with all nature, it has encased itself in a limited range,"|FALSE
39064|"from which it looks forth on what is now other than itself. If previously"|FALSE
39064|"it was mere inward sensibility, it is now sense, perceptive of an object"|FALSE
39064|"here and now, of an external world. The step has involved some price: and"|FALSE
39064|"that price is, that it has attained independence and self-hood at the cost"|FALSE
39064|"of surrendering the content it had hitherto held in one with itself. It is"|FALSE
39064|"now a blank receptivity, open to the impressions of an outside world: and"|FALSE
39064|"the changes which take place in its process of apprehension seem to it to"|FALSE
39064|"be given from outside. The world it perceives is a world of isolated and"|FALSE
39064|"independent objects: and it takes them as they are given. But a closer"|FALSE
39064|"insistance on the perception develops the implicit intelligence, which"|FALSE
39064|"makes it possible. The percipient mind is no mere recipiency or"|FALSE
39064|"susceptibility with its forms of time and space: it is spontaneously"|FALSE
39064|"active, it is the source of categories, or is an apperceptive power,—an"|FALSE
39064|"understanding. Consciousness, thus discovered to be a creative or"|FALSE
39064|"constructive faculty, is strictly speaking self-consciousness(90)."|FALSE
39064|"Self-consciousness appears at first in the selfish or narrowly egoistic"|FALSE
39064|"form of appetite and impulse. The intelligence which claims to mould and"|FALSE
39064|"construe the world of objects—which, in Kant’s phrase, professes to give"|FALSE
39064|"us nature—is implicitly the lord of that world. And that supremacy it"|FALSE
39064|"carries out as appetite—as destruction. The self is but a bundle of"|FALSE
39064|"wants—its supremacy over things is really subjection to them: the"|FALSE
39064|"satisfaction of appetite is baffled by a new desire which leaves it as it"|FALSE
39064|"was before. The development of self-consciousness to a more adequate shape"|FALSE
39064|"is represented by Hegel as taking place through the social struggle for"|FALSE
39064|"existence. Human beings, too, are in the first instance to the"|FALSE
39064|"uninstructed appetite or the primitive self-consciousness (which is simply"|FALSE
39064|"a succession of individual desires for satisfaction of natural want) only"|FALSE
39064|"things,—adjectival to that self’s individual existence. To them, too, his"|FALSE
39064|"primary relation is to appropriate and master them. Might precedes right."|FALSE
39064|"But the social struggle for existence forces him to recognise something"|FALSE
39064|"other which is kindred to himself,—a limiting principle, another self"|FALSE
39064|"which has to form an element in his calculations, not to be neglected. And"|FALSE
39064|"gradually, we may suppose, the result is the division of humanity into two"|FALSE
39064|"levels, a ruling lordly class, and a class of slaves,—a state of"|FALSE
39064|"inequality in which each knows that his appetite is in some measure"|FALSE
39064|"checked by a more or less permanent other. Lastly, perhaps soonest in the"|FALSE
39064|"inferior order, there is fashioned the perception that its self-seeking in"|FALSE
39064|"its isolated appetites is subject to an abiding authority, a continuing"|FALSE
39064|"consciousness. There grows up a social self—a sense of general humanity"|FALSE
39064|"and solidarity with other beings—a larger self with which each identifies"|FALSE
39064|"himself, a common ground. Understanding was selfish intelligence:"|FALSE
39064|"practical in the egoistic sense. In the altruistic or universal sense"|FALSE
39064|"practical, a principle social and unifying character, intelligence is"|FALSE
39064|"Reason."|FALSE
39064|"Thus, Man, beginning as a percipient consciousness, apprehending single"|FALSE
39064|"objects in space and time, and as an appetitive self bent upon single"|FALSE
39064|"gratifications, has ended as a rational being,—a consciousness purged of"|FALSE
39064|"its selfishness and isolation, looking forward openly and impartially on"|FALSE
39064|"the universe of things and beings. He has ceased to be a mere animal,"|FALSE
39064|"swallowed up in the moment and the individual, using his intelligence only"|FALSE
39064|"in selfish satisfactions. He is no longer bound down by the struggle for"|FALSE
39064|"existence, looking on everything as a mere thing, a mere means. He has"|FALSE
39064|"erected himself above himself and above his environment, but that because"|FALSE
39064|"he occupies a point of view at which he and his environment are no longer"|FALSE
39064|"purely antithetical and exclusive(91). He has reached what is really the"|FALSE
39064|"moral standpoint: the point i.e. at which he is inspired by a universal"|FALSE
39064|"self-consciousness, and lives in that peaceful world where the antitheses"|FALSE
39064|"of individualities and of outward and inward have ceased to trouble. “The"|FALSE
39064|"natural man,” says Hegel(92), “sees in the woman flesh of his flesh: the"|FALSE
39064|"moral and spiritual man sees spirit of his spirit in the moral and"|FALSE
39064|"spiritual being and by its means.” Hitherto we have been dealing with"|FALSE
39064|"something falling below the full truth of mind: the region of immediate"|FALSE
39064|"sensibility with its thorough immersion of mind in body, first of all, and"|FALSE
39064|"secondly its gradual progress to a general standpoint. It is only in the"|FALSE
39064|"third part of Subjective mind that we are dealing with the psychology of a"|FALSE
39064|"being who in the human sense knows and wills, i.e. apprehends general"|FALSE
39064|"truth, and carries out ideal purposes."|FALSE
39064|"Thus, for the third time, but now on a higher plane, that of intelligence"|FALSE
39064|"and rationality, is traced the process of development or realisation by"|FALSE
39064|"which reason becomes reasoned knowledge and rational will, a free or"|FALSE
39064|"autonomous intelligence. And, as before, the starting-point, alike in"|FALSE
39064|"theoretical and practical mind, is feeling—or immediate knowledge and"|FALSE
39064|"immediate sense of Ought. The basis of thought is an immediate"|FALSE
39064|"perception—a sensuous affection or given something, and the basis of the"|FALSE
39064|"idea of a general satisfaction is the natural claim to determine the"|FALSE
39064|"outward existence conformably to individual feeling. In intelligent"|FALSE
39064|"perception or intuition the important factor is attention, which raises it"|FALSE
39064|"above mere passive acceptance and awareness of a given fact. Attention"|FALSE
39064|"thus involves on one hand the externality of its object, and on the other"|FALSE
39064|"affirms its dependence on the act of the subject: it sets the objects"|FALSE
39064|"before and out of itself, in space and time, but yet in so doing it shows"|FALSE
39064|"itself master of the objects. If perception presuppose attention, in"|FALSE
39064|"short, they cease to be wholly outward: we make them ours, and the space"|FALSE
39064|"and time they fill are projected by us. So attended to, they are"|FALSE
39064|"appropriated, inwardised and recollected: they take their place in a"|FALSE
39064|"mental place and mental time: they receive a general or de-individualised"|FALSE
39064|"character in the memory-image. These are retained as mental property, but"|FALSE
39064|"retained actually only in so far they are revivable and revived. Such"|FALSE
39064|"revival is the work of imagination working by the so-called laws of"|FALSE
39064|"association. But the possession of its ideas thus inwardised and"|FALSE
39064|"recollected by the mind is largely a matter of chance. The mind is not"|FALSE
39064|"really fully master of them until it has been able to give them a certain"|FALSE
39064|"objectivity, by replacing the mental image by a vocal, i.e. a sensible"|FALSE
39064|"sign. By means of words, intelligence turns its ideas or representations"|FALSE
39064|"into quasi-realities: it creates a sort of superior sense-world, the world"|FALSE
39064|"of language, where ideas live a potential, which is also an actual, life."|FALSE
39064|"Words are sensibles, but they are sensibles which completely lose"|FALSE
39064|"themselves in their meaning. As sensibles, they render possible that"|FALSE
39064|"verbal memory which is the handmaid of thought: but which also as merely"|FALSE
39064|"mechanical can leave thought altogether out of account. It is through"|FALSE
39064|"words that thought is made possible: for it alone permits the movement"|FALSE
39064|"through ideas without being distracted through a multitude of"|FALSE
39064|"associations. In them thought has an instrument completely at its own"|FALSE
39064|"level, but still only a machine, and in memory the working of that"|FALSE
39064|"machine. We think in names, not in general images, but in terms which only"|FALSE
39064|"serve as vehicles for mental synthesis and analysis."|FALSE
39064|"It is as such a thinking being—a being who can use language, and"|FALSE
39064|"manipulate general concepts or take comprehensive views, that man is a"|FALSE
39064|"rational will. A concept of something to be done—a feeling even of some"|FALSE
39064|"end more or less comprehensive in its quality, is the implication of what"|FALSE
39064|"can be called will. At first indeed its material may be found as"|FALSE
39064|"immediately given and all its volitionality may lie in the circumstance"|FALSE
39064|"that the intelligent being sets this forward as a governing and"|FALSE
39064|"controlling Ought. Its vehicle, in short, may be mere impulse, or"|FALSE
39064|"inclination, and even passion: but it is the choice and the purposive"|FALSE
39064|"adoption of means to the given end. Gradually it attains to the idea of a"|FALSE
39064|"general satisfaction, or of happiness. And this end seems positive and"|FALSE
39064|"definite. It soon turns out however to be little but a prudent and"|FALSE
39064|"self-denying superiority to particular passions and inclinations in the"|FALSE
39064|"interest of a comprehensive ideal. The free will or intelligence has so"|FALSE
39064|"far only a negative and formal value: it is the perfection of an"|FALSE
39064|"autonomous and freely self-developing mind. Such a mind, which in language"|FALSE
39064|"has acquired the means of realising an intellectual system of things"|FALSE
39064|"superior to the restrictions of sense, and which has emancipated reason"|FALSE
39064|"from the position of slave to inclination, is endued with the formal"|FALSE
39064|"conditions of moral conduct. Such a mind will transform its own primarily"|FALSE
39064|"physical dependence into an image of the law of reason and create the"|FALSE
39064|"ethical life: and in the strength of that establishment will go forth to"|FALSE
39064|"conquer the world into a more and more adequate realisation of the eternal"|FALSE
39064|"Idea."|FALSE
39064|"Essay V. Ethics And Politics."|FALSE
39064|"“In dealing,” says Hegel, “with the Idea of the State, we must not have"|FALSE
39064|"before our eyes a particular state, or a particular institution: we must"|FALSE
39064|"rather study the Idea, this actual God, on his own account. Every State,"|FALSE
39064|"however bad we may find it according to our principles, however defective"|FALSE
39064|"we may discover this or that feature to be, still contains, particularly"|FALSE
