39064|"affirmative, Life, subsists in spite of the defect: and this affirmative"|FALSE
39064|"is here the theme(93).” “It is the theme of philosophy,” he adds, “to"|FALSE
39064|"ascertain the substance which is immanent in the show of the temporal and"|FALSE
39064|"transient, and the eternal which is present.”"|FALSE
39064|"(i.) Hegel as a Political Critic."|FALSE
39064|"But if this is true, it is also to be remembered that the philosopher is,"|FALSE
39064|"like other men, the son of his age, and estimates the value of reality"|FALSE
39064|"from preconceptions and aspirations due to his generation. The historical"|FALSE
39064|"circumstances of his nation as well as the personal experiences of his"|FALSE
39064|"life help to determine his horizon, even in the effort to discover the"|FALSE
39064|"hidden pulse and movement of the social organism. This is specially"|FALSE
39064|"obvious in political philosophy. The conception of ethics and politics"|FALSE
39064|"which is presented in the _Encyclopaedia_ was in 1820 produced with more"|FALSE
39064|"detail as the _Grundlinien der Philosophie des Rechts_. Appearing, as it"|FALSE
39064|"did, two years after his appointment to a professorship at Berlin, and in"|FALSE
39064|"the midst of a political struggle between the various revolutionary and"|FALSE
39064|"conservative powers and parties of Germany, the book became, and long"|FALSE
39064|"remained, a target for embittered criticism. The so-called War of"|FALSE
39064|"Liberation or national movement to shake off the French yoke was due to a"|FALSE
39064|"coalition of parties, and had naturally been in part supported by"|FALSE
39064|"tendencies and aims which went far beyond the ostensive purpose either of"|FALSE
39064|"leaders or of combatants. Aspirations after a freer state were entwined"|FALSE
39064|"with radical and socialistic designs to reform the political hierarchy of"|FALSE
39064|"the Fatherland: high ideals and low vulgarities were closely intermixed:"|FALSE
39064|"and the noble enthusiasm of youth was occasionally played on by criminal"|FALSE
39064|"and anarchic intriguers. In a strong and wise and united Germany some of"|FALSE
39064|"these schemes might have been tolerated. But strength, wisdom, and unity"|FALSE
39064|"were absent. In the existing tension between Austria and Prussia for the"|FALSE
39064|"leadership, in the ill-adapted and effete constitutions of the several"|FALSE
39064|"principalities which were yet expected to realise the advance which had"|FALSE
39064|"taken place in society and ideas during the last thirty years, the outlook"|FALSE
39064|"on every hand seemed darker and more threatening than it might have"|FALSE
39064|"otherwise done. Governments, which had lost touch with their peoples,"|FALSE
39064|"suspected conspiracy and treason: and a party in the nation credited their"|FALSE
39064|"rulers with gratuitous designs against private liberty and rights. There"|FALSE
39064|"was a vast but ill-defined enthusiasm in the breasts of the younger world,"|FALSE
39064|"and it was shared by many of their teachers. It seemed to their immense"|FALSE
39064|"aspirations that the war of liberation had failed of its true object and"|FALSE
39064|"left things much as they were. The volunteers had not fought for the"|FALSE
39064|"political systems of Austria or Prussia, or for the three-and-thirty"|FALSE
39064|"princes of Germany: but for ideas, vague, beautiful, stimulating. To such"|FALSE
39064|"a mood the continuance of the old system was felt as a cruel deception and"|FALSE
39064|"a reaction. The governments on their part had not realised the full"|FALSE
39064|"importance of the spirit that had been aroused, and could not at a"|FALSE
39064|"moment’s notice set their house in order, even had there been a clearer"|FALSE
39064|"outlook for reform than was offered. They too had suffered, and had"|FALSE
39064|"realised their insecurity: and were hardly in a mood to open their gates"|FALSE
39064|"to the enemy."|FALSE
39064|"Coming on such a situation of affairs, Hegel’s book would have been likely"|FALSE
39064|"in any case to provoke criticism. For it took up a line of political"|FALSE
39064|"theory which was little in accord with the temper of the age. The"|FALSE
39064|"conception of the state which it expounded is not far removed in"|FALSE
39064|"essentials from the conception which now dominates the political life of"|FALSE
39064|"the chief European nations. But in his own time it came upon ears which"|FALSE
39064|"were naturally disposed to misconceive it. It was unacceptable to the"|FALSE
39064|"adherents of the _ancien régime_, as much as to the liberals. It was"|FALSE
39064|"declared by one party to be a glorification of the Prussian state: by"|FALSE
39064|"another to rationalise the sanctities of authority. It was pointed out"|FALSE
39064|"that the new professor was a favourite of the leading minister, that his"|FALSE
39064|"influence was dominant in scholastic appointments, and that occasional"|FALSE
39064|"gratuities from the crown proved his acceptability. A contemporary"|FALSE
39064|"professor, Fries, remarked that Hegel’s theory of the state had grown “not"|FALSE
39064|"in the gardens of science but on the dung-hill of servility.” Hegel"|FALSE
39064|"himself was aware that he had planted a blow in the face of a “shallow and"|FALSE
39064|"pretentious sect,” and that his book had “given great offence to the"|FALSE
39064|"demagogic folk.” Alike in religious and political life he was impatient of"|FALSE
39064|"sentimentalism, of rhetorical feeling, of wordy enthusiasm. A positive"|FALSE
