39064|"find realisation."|FALSE
39064|"The “positive supersession(107)” of individualism and naturalism in ethics"|FALSE
39064|"is by Hegel called “Absolute Ethics.” Under this title he describes the"|FALSE
39064|"ethics and religion of the state—a religion which is immanent in the"|FALSE
39064|"community, and an ethics which rises superior to particularity. The"|FALSE
39064|"picture he draws is a romance fashioned upon the model of the Greek"|FALSE
39064|"commonwealth as that had been idealised by Greek literature and by the"|FALSE
39064|"longings of later ages for a freer life. It is but one of the many modes"|FALSE
39064|"in which Helena—to quote Goethe—has fascinated the German Faust. He dreams"|FALSE
39064|"himself away from the prosaic worldliness of a German municipality to the"|FALSE
39064|"unfading splendour of the Greek city with its imagined coincidence of"|FALSE
39064|"individual will with universal purpose. There is in such a commonwealth no"|FALSE
39064|"pain of surrender and of sacrifice, and no subsequent compensation: for,"|FALSE
39064|"at the very moment of resigning self-will to common aims, he enjoys it"|FALSE
39064|"retained with the added zest of self-expansion. He is not so left to"|FALSE
39064|"himself as to feel from beyond the restraint of a law which controls—even"|FALSE
39064|"if it wisely and well controls—individual effort. There is for his happy"|FALSE
39064|"circumstances no possibility of doing otherwise. Or, it may be, Hegel has"|FALSE
39064|"reminiscences from the ideals of other nations than the Greek. He recalls"|FALSE
39064|"the Israelite depicted by the Law-adoring psalmist, whose delight is to do"|FALSE
39064|"the will of the Lord, whom the zeal of God’s house has consumed, whose"|FALSE
39064|"whole being runs on in one pellucid stream with the universal and eternal"|FALSE
39064|"stream of divine commandment. Such a frame of spirit, where the empirical"|FALSE
39064|"consciousness with all its soul and strength and mind identifies its"|FALSE
39064|"mission into conformity with the absolute order, is the mood of absolute"|FALSE
39064|"Ethics. It is what some have spoken of as the True life, as the Eternal"|FALSE
39064|"life; in it, says Hegel, the individual exists _auf ewige Weise_(108), as"|FALSE
39064|"it were _sub specie aeternitatis_: his life is hid with his fellows in the"|FALSE
39064|"common life of his people. His every act, and thought, and will, get their"|FALSE
39064|"being and significance from a reality which is established in him as a"|FALSE
39064|"permanent spirit. It is there that he, in the fuller sense, attains"|FALSE
39064|"αὐτάρκεια, or finds himself no longer a mere part, but an ideal totality."|FALSE
39064|"This totality is realised under the particular form of a Nation (_Volk_),"|FALSE
39064|"which in the visible sphere represents (or rather is, as a particular) the"|FALSE
39064|"absolute and infinite. Such a unity is neither the mere sum of isolated"|FALSE
39064|"individuals, nor a mere majority ruling by numbers: but the fraternal and"|FALSE
39064|"organic commonwealth which brings all classes and all rights from their"|FALSE
39064|"particularistic independence into an ideal identity and indifference(109)."|FALSE
39064|"Here all are not merely equal before the laws: but the law itself is a"|FALSE
39064|"living and organic unity, self-correcting, subordinating and organising,"|FALSE
39064|"and no longer merely defining individual privileges and so-called"|FALSE
39064|"liberties. “In such conjunction of the universal with the particularity"|FALSE
39064|"lies the divinity of a nation: or, if we give this universal a separate"|FALSE
39064|"place in our ideas, it is the God of the nation.” But in this complete"|FALSE
39064|"accordance between concept and intuition, between visible and invisible,"|FALSE
39064|"where symbol and significate are one, religion and ethics are"|FALSE
39064|"indistinguishable. It is the old conception (and in its highest sense) of"|FALSE
39064|"Theocracy(110). God is the national head and the national life: and in him"|FALSE
39064|"all individuals have their “difference” rendered “indifferent.” “Such an"|FALSE
39064|"ethical life is absolute truth, for untruth is only in the fixture of a"|FALSE
39064|"single mode: but in the everlasting being of the nation all singleness is"|FALSE
