39064|"If we compare this language with the statement of the Encyclopaedia we can"|FALSE
39064|"see how for the moment Hegel’s eye is engrossed with the glory of the"|FALSE
39064|"ideal nation. In it, the moral life embraces and is co-extensive with"|FALSE
39064|"religion, art and science: practice and theory are at one: life in the"|FALSE
39064|"idea knows none of those differences which, in the un-ideal world, make"|FALSE
39064|"art and morality often antithetical, and set religion at variance with"|FALSE
39064|"science. It is, as we have said, a memory of Greek and perhaps Hebrew"|FALSE
39064|"ideals. Or rather it is by the help of such memories the affirmation of"|FALSE
39064|"the essential unity of life—the true, complete, many-sided life—which is"|FALSE
39064|"the presupposition and idea that culture and morals rest upon and from"|FALSE
39064|"which they get their supreme sanction, i.e. their constitutive principle"|FALSE
39064|"and unity. Even in the Encyclopaedia(112) Hegel endeavours to guard"|FALSE
39064|"against the severance of morality and art and philosophy which may be"|FALSE
39064|"rashly inferred in consequence of his serial order of treatment."|FALSE
39064|"“Religion,” he remarks, “is the very substance of the moral life itself"|FALSE
39064|"and of the state.... The ethical life is the divine spirit indwelling in"|FALSE
39064|"consciousness, as it is actually present in a nation and its individual"|FALSE
39064|"members.” Yet, as we see, there is a distinction. The process of history"|FALSE
39064|"carries out a judgment on nation after nation, and reveals the divine as"|FALSE
39064|"not only immanent in the ethical life but as ever expanding the limited"|FALSE
39064|"national spirit till it become a spirit of universal humanity. Still—and"|FALSE
39064|"this is perhaps for each time always the more important—the national"|FALSE
39064|"unity—not indeed as a multitude, nor as a majority—is the supreme real"|FALSE
39064|"appearance of the Eternal and Absolute."|FALSE
39064|"Having thus described the nation as an organic totality, he goes on to"|FALSE
39064|"point out that the political constitution shows this character by forming"|FALSE
39064|"a triplicity of political orders. In one of these there is but a silent,"|FALSE
39064|"practical identity, in faith and trust, with the totality: in the second"|FALSE
39064|"there is a thorough disruption of interest into particularity: and in the"|FALSE
39064|"third, there is a living and intellectual identity or indifference, which"|FALSE
39064|"combines the widest range of individual development with the completest"|FALSE
39064|"unity of political loyalty. This last order is that which lives in"|FALSE
39064|"conscious identification of private with public duty: all that it does has"|FALSE
39064|"a universal and public function. Such a body is the ideal Nobility—the"|FALSE
39064|"nobility which is the _servus servorum Dei_, the supreme servant of"|FALSE
39064|"humanity. Its function is to maintain general interests, to give the other"|FALSE
39064|"orders (peasantry and industrials) security,—receiving in return from"|FALSE
39064|"these others the means of subsistence. _Noblesse oblige_ gives the"|FALSE
39064|"death-blow to particular interests, and imposes the duty of exhibiting, in"|FALSE
39064|"the clearest form, the supreme reality of absolute morality, and of being"|FALSE
39064|"to the rest an unperturbed ideal of aesthetic, ethical, religious, and"|FALSE
39064|"philosophical completeness."|FALSE
39064|"It is here alone, in this estate which is absolutely disinterested, that"|FALSE
39064|"the virtues appear in their true light. To the ordinary moralising"|FALSE
39064|"standpoint they seem severally to be, in their separation, charged with"|FALSE
39064|"independent value. But from the higher point of view the existence, and"|FALSE
39064|"still more the accentuation of single virtues, is a mark of"|FALSE
39064|"incompleteness. Even quality, it has been said, involves its defects: it"|FALSE
39064|"can only shine by eclipsing or reflecting something else. The completely"|FALSE
39064|"moral is not the sum of the several virtues, but the reduction of them to"|FALSE
39064|"indifference. It is thus that when Plato tries to get at the unity of"|FALSE
39064|"virtue, their aspect of difference tends to be subordinated. “The movement"|FALSE
39064|"of absolute morality runs through all the virtues, but settles fixedly in"|FALSE
39064|"none.” It is more than love _to_ fatherland, and nation, and laws:—that"|FALSE
39064|"still implies a relation to something and involves a difference. For"|FALSE
39064|"love—the mortal passion, where “self is not annulled”—is the process of"|FALSE
39064|"approximation, while unity is not yet attained, but wished and aimed at:"|FALSE
39064|"and when it is complete—and become “such love as spirits know(113)”—it"|FALSE
39064|"gives place to a calmer rest and an active immanence. The absolute"|FALSE
39064|"morality is _life in_ the fatherland and for the nation. In the individual"|FALSE
39064|"however it is the process upward and inward that we see, not the"|FALSE
39064|"consummation. Then the identity appears as an ideal, as a tendency not yet"|FALSE
39064|"accomplished to its end, a possibility not yet made fully actual. At"|FALSE
39064|"bottom—in the divine substance in which the individual inheres—the"|FALSE
39064|"identity is present: but in the appearance, we have only the passage from"|FALSE
39064|"possible to actual, a passage which has the aspect of a struggle. Hence"|FALSE
39064|"the moral act appears as a virtue, with merit or desert. It is accordingly"|FALSE
39064|"the very characteristic of virtue to signalise its own incompleteness: it"|FALSE
39064|"emerges into actuality only through antagonism, and with a taint of"|FALSE
39064|"imperfection clinging to it. Thus, in the field of absolute morality, if"|FALSE
39064|"the virtues appear, it is only in their transiency. If they were"|FALSE
39064|"undisputedly real in morality, they would not separately show. To feel"|FALSE
39064|"that you have done well implies that you have not done wholly well:"|FALSE
39064|"self-gratulation in meritorious deed is the re-action from the shudder at"|FALSE
39064|"feeling that the self was not wholly good."|FALSE
39064|"The essential unity of virtue—its negative character as regards all the"|FALSE
39064|"empirical variety of virtues—is seen in the excellences required by the"|FALSE
39064|"needs of war. These military requirements demonstrate the mere relativity"|FALSE
39064|"and therefore non-virtuousness of the special virtues. They equally"|FALSE
39064|"protest against the common beliefs in the supreme dignity of labour and"|FALSE
39064|"its utilities. But if bravery or soldierlike virtue be essentially a"|FALSE
39064|"virtue of virtues, it is only a negative virtue after all. It is the blast"|FALSE
39064|"of the universal sweeping away all the habitations and fixed structures of"|FALSE
39064|"particularist life. If it is a unity of virtue, it is only a negative"|FALSE
39064|"unity—an indifference. If it avoid the parcelling of virtue into a number"|FALSE
39064|"of imperfect and sometimes contradictory parts, it does so only to present"|FALSE
39064|"a bare negation. The soldier, therefore, if in potentiality the unity of"|FALSE
39064|"all the virtues, may tend in practice to represent the ability to do"|FALSE
39064|"without any of them(114)."|FALSE
39064|"The home of these “relative” virtues—of morality in the ordinary sense—is"|FALSE
39064|"the life of the second order in the commonwealth: the order of industry"|FALSE
39064|"and commerce. In this sphere the idea of the universal is gradually lost"|FALSE
39064|"to view: it becomes, says Hegel, only a thought or a creature of the mind,"|FALSE
39064|"which does not affect practice. The materialistic worker of civilisation"|FALSE
39064|"does not see further than the empirical existence of individuals: his"|FALSE
39064|"horizon is limited by the family, and his final ideal is a competency of"|FALSE
39064|"comfort in possessions and revenues. The supreme universal to which he"|FALSE
39064|"attains as the climax of his evolution is only money. But it is only with"|FALSE
39064|"the vaster development of commerce that this terrible consequence ensues."|FALSE
39064|"At first as a mere individual, he has higher aims, though not the highest."|FALSE
39064|"He has a limited ideal determined by his special sphere of work. To win"|FALSE
39064|"respect—the character for a limited truthfulness and honesty and skilful"|FALSE
39064|"work—is his ambition. He lives in a conceit of his performance—his"|FALSE
39064|"utility—the esteem of his special circle. To his commercial soul the"|FALSE
39064|"military order is a scarecrow and a nuisance: military honour is but"|FALSE
