39064|"INTRODUCTION."|FALSE
39064|"§ 377. The knowledge of Mind is the highest and hardest, just because it"|FALSE
39064|"is the most “concrete” of sciences. The significance of that “absolute”"|FALSE
39064|"commandment, _Know thyself_—whether we look at it in itself or under the"|FALSE
39064|"historical circumstances of its first utterance—is not to promote mere"|FALSE
39064|"self-knowledge in respect of the _particular_ capacities, character,"|FALSE
39064|"propensities, and foibles of the single self. The knowledge it commands"|FALSE
39064|"means that of man’s genuine reality—of what is essentially and ultimately"|FALSE
39064|"true and real—of mind as the true and essential being. Equally little is"|FALSE
39064|"it the purport of mental philosophy to teach what is called _knowledge of"|FALSE
39064|"men_—the knowledge whose aim is to detect the _peculiarities_, passions,"|FALSE
39064|"and foibles of other men, and lay bare what are called the recesses of the"|FALSE
39064|"human heart. Information of this kind is, for one thing, meaningless,"|FALSE
39064|"unless on the assumption that we know the _universal_—man as man, and,"|FALSE
39064|"that always must be, as mind. And for another, being only engaged with"|FALSE
39064|"casual, insignificant and _untrue_ aspects of mental life, it fails to"|FALSE
39064|"reach the underlying essence of them all—the mind itself."|FALSE
39064|"§ 378. Pneumatology, or, as it was also called, Rational Psychology, has"|FALSE
39064|"been already alluded to in the Introduction to the Logic as an _abstract_"|FALSE
39064|"and generalising metaphysic of the subject. _Empirical_ (or inductive)"|FALSE
39064|"psychology, on the other hand, deals with the “concrete” mind: and, after"|FALSE
39064|"the revival of the sciences, when observation and experience had been made"|FALSE
39064|"the distinctive methods for the study of concrete reality, such psychology"|FALSE
39064|"was worked on the same lines as other sciences. In this way it came about"|FALSE
39064|"that the metaphysical theory was kept outside the inductive science, and"|FALSE
39064|"so prevented from getting any concrete embodiment or detail: whilst at the"|FALSE
39064|"same time the inductive science clung to the conventional common-sense"|FALSE
39064|"metaphysic, with its analysis into forces, various activities, &c., and"|FALSE
39064|"rejected any attempt at a “speculative” treatment."|FALSE
39064|"The books of Aristotle on the Soul, along with his discussions on its"|FALSE
39064|"special aspects and states, are for this reason still by far the most"|FALSE
39064|"admirable, perhaps even the sole, work of philosophical value on this"|FALSE
39064|"topic. The main aim of a philosophy of mind can only be to re-introduce"|FALSE
39064|"unity of idea and principle into the theory of mind, and so re-interpret"|FALSE
39064|"the lesson of those Aristotelian books."|FALSE
39064|"§ 379. Even our own sense of the mind’s _living_ unity naturally protests"|FALSE
39064|"against any attempt to break it up into different faculties, forces, or,"|FALSE
39064|"what comes to the same thing, activities, conceived as independent of each"|FALSE
39064|"other. But the craving for a _comprehension_ of the unity is still further"|FALSE
39064|"stimulated, as we soon come across distinctions between mental freedom and"|FALSE
39064|"mental determinism, antitheses between free _psychic_ agency and the"|FALSE
39064|"corporeity that lies external to it, whilst we equally note the intimate"|FALSE
39064|"interdependence of the one upon the other. In modern times especially the"|FALSE
39064|"phenomena of _animal magnetism_ have given, even in experience, a lively"|FALSE
39064|"and visible confirmation of the underlying unity of soul, and of the power"|FALSE
39064|"of its “ideality.” Before these facts, the rigid distinctions of practical"|FALSE
39064|"common sense were struck with confusion; and the necessity of a"|FALSE
39064|"“speculative” examination with a view to the removal of difficulties was"|FALSE
39064|"more directly forced upon the student."|FALSE
39064|"§ 380. The “concrete” nature of mind involves for the observer the"|FALSE
39064|"peculiar difficulty that the several grades and special types which"|FALSE
39064|"develop its intelligible unity in detail are not left standing as so many"|FALSE
39064|"separate existences confronting its more advanced aspects. It is otherwise"|FALSE
39064|"in external nature. There, matter and movement, for example, have a"|FALSE
39064|"manifestation all their own—it is the solar system; and similarly the"|FALSE
39064|"_differentiae_ of sense-perception have a sort of earlier existence in the"|FALSE
39064|"properties of _bodies_, and still more independently in the four elements."|FALSE
39064|"The species and grades of mental evolution, on the contrary, lose their"|FALSE
39064|"separate existence and become factors, states and features in the higher"|FALSE
39064|"grades of development. As a consequence of this, a lower and more abstract"|FALSE
39064|"aspect of mind betrays the presence in it, even to experience, of a higher"|FALSE
39064|"grade. Under the guise of sensation, e.g., we may find the very highest"|FALSE
39064|"mental life as its modification or its embodiment. And so sensation, which"|FALSE
39064|"is but a mere form and vehicle, may to the superficial glance seem to be"|FALSE
39064|"the proper seat and, as it were, the source of those moral and religious"|FALSE
39064|"principles with which it is charged; and the moral and religious"|FALSE
39064|"principles thus modified may seem to call for treatment as species of"|FALSE
39064|"sensation. But at the same time, when lower grades of mental life are"|FALSE
39064|"under examination, it becomes necessary, if we desire to point to actual"|FALSE
39064|"cases of them in experience, to direct attention to more advanced grades"|FALSE
39064|"for which they are mere forms. In this way subjects will be treated of by"|FALSE
39064|"anticipation which properly belong to later stages of development (e.g. in"|FALSE
39064|"dealing with natural awaking from sleep we speak by anticipation of"|FALSE
39064|"consciousness, or in dealing with mental derangement we must speak of"|FALSE
39064|"intellect)."|FALSE
39064|"What Mind (or Spirit) is."|FALSE
39064|"§ 381. From our point of view Mind has for its _presupposition_ Nature, of"|FALSE
39064|"which it is the truth, and for that reason its _absolute prius_. In this"|FALSE
39064|"its truth Nature is vanished, and mind has resulted as the “Idea” entered"|FALSE
39064|"on possession of itself. Here the subject and object of the Idea are"|FALSE
39064|"one—either is the intelligent unity, the notion. This identity is"|FALSE
39064|"_absolute negativity_—for whereas in Nature the intelligent unity has its"|FALSE
39064|"objectivity perfect but externalised, this self-externalisation has been"|FALSE
39064|"nullified and the unity in that way been made one and the same with"|FALSE
39064|"itself. Thus at the same time it is this identity only so far as it is a"|FALSE
39064|"return out of nature."|FALSE
39064|"§ 382. For this reason the essential, but formally essential, feature of"|FALSE
39064|"mind is Liberty: i.e. it is the notion’s absolute negativity or"|FALSE
39064|"self-identity. Considered as this formal aspect, it _may_ withdraw itself"|FALSE
39064|"from everything external and from its own externality, its very existence;"|FALSE
39064|"it can thus submit to infinite _pain_, the negation of its individual"|FALSE
39064|"immediacy: in other words, it can keep itself affirmative in this"|FALSE
39064|"negativity and possess its own identity. All this is possible so long as"|FALSE
39064|"it is considered in its abstract self-contained universality."|FALSE
39064|"§ 383. This universality is also its determinate sphere of being. Having a"|FALSE
39064|"being of its own, the universal is self-particularising, whilst it still"|FALSE
39064|"remains self-identical. Hence the special mode of mental being is"|FALSE
39064|"“_manifestation_.” The spirit is not some one mode or meaning which finds"|FALSE
39064|"utterance or externality only in a form distinct from itself: it does not"|FALSE
39064|"manifest or reveal _something_, but its very mode and meaning is this"|FALSE
39064|"revelation. And thus in its mere possibility Mind is at the same moment an"|FALSE
39064|"infinite, “absolute,” _actuality_."|FALSE
39064|"§ 384. _Revelation_, taken to mean the revelation of the _abstract_ Idea,"|FALSE
39064|"is an unmediated transition to Nature which _comes_ to be. As Mind is"|FALSE
39064|"free, its manifestation is to _set forth_ Nature as _its_ world; but"|FALSE
39064|"because it is reflection, it, in thus setting forth its world, at the same"|FALSE
39064|"time _presupposes_ the world as a nature independently existing. In the"|FALSE
39064|"intellectual sphere to reveal is thus to create a world as its being—a"|FALSE
39064|"being in which the mind procures the _affirmation_ and _truth_ of its"|FALSE
39064|"freedom."|FALSE
39064|"_The Absolute is Mind_ (Spirit)—this is the supreme definition of the"|FALSE
39064|"Absolute. To find this definition and to grasp its meaning and burthen"|FALSE
39064|"was, we may say, the ultimate purpose of all education and all philosophy:"|FALSE
39064|"it was the point to which turned the impulse of all religion and science:"|FALSE
39064|"and it is this impulse that must explain the history of the world. The"|FALSE
39064|"word “Mind” (Spirit)—and some glimpse of its meaning—was found at an early"|FALSE
39064|"period: and the spirituality of God is the lesson of Christianity. It"|FALSE
39064|"remains for philosophy in its own element of intelligible unity to get"|FALSE
39064|"hold of what was thus given as a mental image, and what implicitly is the"|FALSE
39064|"ultimate reality: and that problem is not genuinely, and by rational"|FALSE
39064|"methods, solved so long as liberty and intelligible unity is not the theme"|FALSE
39064|"and the soul of philosophy."|FALSE
39064|"Subdivision."|FALSE
39064|"§ 385. The development of Mind (Spirit) is in three stages:—"|FALSE
39064|"(1) In the form of self-relation: within it it has the _ideal_ totality of"|FALSE
39064|"the Idea—i.e. it has before it all that its notion contains: its being is"|FALSE
39064|"to be self-contained and free. This is _Mind Subjective_."|FALSE
39064|"(2) In the form of _reality_: realised, i.e. in a _world_ produced and to"|FALSE
39064|"be produced by it: in this world freedom presents itself under the shape"|FALSE
39064|"of necessity. This is _Mind Objective_."|FALSE
39064|"(3) In that unity of mind as objectivity and, of mind as ideality and"|FALSE
39064|"concept, which essentially and actually is and for ever produces itself,"|FALSE
39064|"mind in its absolute truth. This is _Mind Absolute_."|FALSE
39064|"§ 386. The two first parts of the doctrine of Mind embrace the finite"|FALSE
39064|"mind. Mind is the infinite Idea; thus finitude here means the"|FALSE
39064|"disproportion between the concept and the reality—but with the"|FALSE
39064|"qualification that it is a shadow cast by the mind’s own light—a show or"|FALSE
39064|"illusion which the mind implicitly imposes as a barrier to itself, in"|FALSE
39064|"order, by its removal, actually to realise and become conscious of freedom"|FALSE
39064|"as _its_ very being, i.e. to be fully _manifested_. The several steps of"|FALSE
39064|"this activity, on each of which, with their semblance of being, it is the"|FALSE
39064|"function of the finite mind to linger, and through which it has to pass,"|FALSE
39064|"are steps in its liberation. In the full truth of that liberation is given"|FALSE
39064|"the identification of the three stages—finding a world presupposed before"|FALSE
39064|"us, generating a world as our own creation, and gaining freedom from it"|FALSE
39064|"and in it. To the infinite form of this truth the show purifies itself"|FALSE
39064|"till it becomes a consciousness of it."|FALSE
39064|"A rigid application of the category of finitude by the abstract logician"|FALSE
39064|"is chiefly seen in dealing with Mind and reason: it is held not a mere"|FALSE
39064|"matter of strict logic, but treated also as a moral and religious concern,"|FALSE
39064|"to adhere to the point of view of finitude, and the wish to go further is"|FALSE
39064|"reckoned a mark of audacity, if not of insanity, of thought. Whereas in"|FALSE
39064|"fact such a _modesty_ of thought, as treats the finite as something"|FALSE
39064|"altogether fixed and _absolute_, is the worst of virtues; and to stick to"|FALSE
39064|"a post which has no sound ground in itself is the most unsound sort of"|FALSE
39064|"theory. The category of finitude was at a much earlier period elucidated"|FALSE
39064|"and explained at its place in the Logic: an elucidation which, as in logic"|FALSE
39064|"for the more specific though still simple thought-forms of finitude, so in"|FALSE
39064|"the rest of philosophy for the concrete forms, has merely to show that the"|FALSE
39064|"finite _is not_, i.e. is not the truth, but merely a transition and an"|FALSE
39064|"emergence to something higher. This finitude of the spheres so far"|FALSE
39064|"examined is the dialectic that makes a thing have its cessation by another"|FALSE
39064|"and in another: but Spirit, the intelligent unity and the _implicit_"|FALSE
39064|"Eternal, is itself just the consummation of that internal act by which"|FALSE
39064|"nullity is nullified and vanity is made vain. And so, the modesty alluded"|FALSE
39064|"to is a retention of this vanity—the finite—in opposition to the true: it"|FALSE
39064|"is itself therefore vanity. In the course of the mind’s development we"|FALSE
39064|"shall see this vanity appear as _wickedness_ at that turning-point at"|FALSE
39064|"which mind has reached its extreme immersion in its subjectivity and its"|FALSE
39064|"most central contradiction."|FALSE
39064|"SECTION I. MIND SUBJECTIVE."|FALSE
39064|"§ 387. Mind, on the ideal stage of its development, is mind as"|FALSE
39064|"_cognitive_: Cognition, however, being taken here not as a merely logical"|FALSE
39064|"category of the Idea (§ 223), but in the sense appropriate to the"|FALSE
39064|"_concrete_ mind."|FALSE
39064|"Subjective mind is:—"|FALSE
39064|"(A) Immediate or implicit: a soul—the Spirit in _Nature_—the object"|FALSE
39064|"treated by _Anthropology_."|FALSE
39064|"(B) Mediate or explicit: still as identical reflection into itself and"|FALSE
39064|"into other things: mind in correlation or particularisation:"|FALSE
39064|"consciousness—the object treated by the _Phenomenology of Mind_."|FALSE
39064|"(C) Mind defining itself in itself, as an independent subject—the object"|FALSE
39064|"treated by _Psychology_."|FALSE
39064|"In the Soul is the _awaking of Consciousness_: Consciousness sets itself"|FALSE
39064|"up as Reason, awaking at one bound to the sense of its rationality: and"|FALSE
39064|"this Reason by its activity emancipates itself to objectivity and the"|FALSE
39064|"consciousness of its intelligent unity."|FALSE
39064|"For an intelligible unity or principle of comprehension each modification"|FALSE
39064|"it presents is an advance of _development_: and so in mind every character"|FALSE
39064|"under which it appears is a stage in a process of specification and"|FALSE
39064|"development, a step forward towards its goal, in order to make itself"|FALSE
39064|"into, and to realise in itself, what it implicitly is. Each step, again,"|FALSE
39064|"is itself such a process, and its product is that what the mind was"|FALSE
39064|"implicitly at the beginning (and so for the observer) it is _for"|FALSE
39064|"itself_—for the special form, viz. which the mind has in that step. The"|FALSE
39064|"ordinary method of psychology is to narrate what the mind or soul is, what"|FALSE
39064|"happens to it, what it does. The soul is presupposed as a ready-made"|FALSE
39064|"agent, which displays such features as its acts and utterances, from which"|FALSE
39064|"we can learn what it is, what sort of faculties and powers it"|FALSE
39064|"possesses—all without being aware that the act and utterance of what the"|FALSE
39064|"soul is really invests it with that character in our conception and makes"|FALSE
39064|"it reach a higher stage of being than it explicitly had before."|FALSE
39064|"We must, however, distinguish and keep apart from the progress here"|FALSE
39064|"studied what we call education and instruction. The sphere of education is"|FALSE
39064|"the individual’s only: and its aim is to bring the universal mind to exist"|FALSE
39064|"in them. But in the philosophic theory of mind, mind is studied as"|FALSE
39064|"self-instruction and self-education in very essence; and its acts and"|FALSE
39064|"utterances are stages in the process which brings it forward to itself,"|FALSE
39064|"links it in unity with itself, and so makes it actual mind."|FALSE
39064|"Sub-Section A. Anthropology. The Soul."|FALSE
39064|"§ 388. Spirit (Mind) _came into_ being as the truth of Nature. But not"|FALSE
39064|"merely is it, as such a result, to be held the true and real first of what"|FALSE
39064|"went before: this becoming or transition bears in the sphere of the notion"|FALSE
39064|"the special meaning of “_free judgment_.” Mind, thus come into being,"|FALSE
39064|"means therefore that Nature in its own self realises its untruth and sets"|FALSE
39064|"itself aside: it means that Mind presupposes itself no longer as the"|FALSE
39064|"universality which in corporal individuality is always self-externalised,"|FALSE
39064|"but as a universality which in its concretion and totality is one and"|FALSE
39064|"simple. At such a stage it is not yet mind, but _soul_."|FALSE
39064|"§ 389. The soul is no separate immaterial entity. Wherever there is"|FALSE
39064|"Nature, the soul is its universal immaterialism, its simple “ideal” life."|FALSE
39064|"Soul is the _substance_ or “absolute” basis of all the particularising and"|FALSE
39064|"individualising of mind: it is in the soul that mind finds the material on"|FALSE
39064|"which its character is wrought, and the soul remains the pervading,"|FALSE
39064|"identical ideality of it all. But as it is still conceived thus"|FALSE
39064|"abstractly, the soul is only the _sleep_ of mind—the passive νοῦς of"|FALSE
39064|"Aristotle, which is potentially all things."|FALSE
39064|"The question of the immateriality of the soul has no interest, except"|FALSE
39064|"where, on the one hand, matter is regarded as something _true_, and mind"|FALSE
39064|"conceived as a _thing_, on the other. But in modern times even the"|FALSE
39064|"physicists have found matters grow thinner in their hands: they have come"|FALSE
39064|"upon _imponderable_ matters, like heat, light, &c., to which they might"|FALSE
39064|"perhaps add space and time. These “imponderables,” which have lost the"|FALSE
39064|"property (peculiar to matter) of gravity and, in a sense, even the"|FALSE
39064|"capacity of offering resistance, have still, however, a sensible existence"|FALSE
39064|"and outness of part to part; whereas the “vital”_ matter_, which may also"|FALSE
39064|"be found enumerated among them, not merely lacks gravity, but even every"|FALSE
39064|"other aspect of existence which might lead us to treat it as material. The"|FALSE
39064|"fact is that in the Idea of Life the self-externalism of nature is"|FALSE
39064|"_implicitly_ at an end: subjectivity is the very substance and conception"|FALSE
39064|"of life—with this proviso, however, that its existence or objectivity is"|FALSE
39064|"still at the same time forfeited to the sway of self-externalism. It is"|FALSE
39064|"otherwise with Mind. There, in the intelligible unity which exists as"|FALSE
39064|"freedom, as absolute negativity, and not as the immediate or natural"|FALSE
39064|"individual, the object or the reality of the intelligible unity is the"|FALSE
39064|"unity itself; and so the self-externalism, which is the fundamental"|FALSE
39064|"feature of matter, has been completely dissipated and transmuted into"|FALSE
39064|"universality, or the subjective ideality of the conceptual unity. Mind is"|FALSE
39064|"the existent truth of matter—the truth that matter itself has no truth."|FALSE
39064|"A cognate question is that of the _community of soul and body_. This"|FALSE
39064|"community (interdependence) was assumed as a _fact_, and the only problem"|FALSE
39064|"was how to _comprehend_ it. The usual answer, perhaps, was to call it an"|FALSE
39064|"_incomprehensible_ mystery; and, indeed, if we take them to be absolutely"|FALSE
39064|"antithetical and absolutely independent, they are as impenetrable to each"|FALSE
39064|"other as one piece of matter to another, each being supposed to be found"|FALSE
39064|"only in the pores of the other, i.e. where the other is not: whence"|FALSE
39064|"Epicurus, when attributing to the gods a residence in the pores, was"|FALSE
39064|"consistent in not imposing on them any connexion with the world. A"|FALSE
39064|"somewhat different answer has been given by all philosophers since this"|FALSE
39064|"relation came to be expressly discussed. Descartes, Malebranche, Spinoza,"|FALSE
39064|"and Leibnitz have all indicated God as this _nexus_. They meant that the"|FALSE
39064|"finitude of soul and matter were only ideal and unreal distinctions; and,"|FALSE
39064|"so holding, these philosophers took God, not, as so often is done, merely"|FALSE
39064|"as another word for the incomprehensible, but rather as the sole true"|FALSE
39064|"identity of finite mind and matter. But either this identity, as in the"|FALSE
39064|"case of Spinoza, is too abstract, or, as in the case of Leibnitz, though"|FALSE
39064|"his Monad of monads brings things into being, it does so only by an act of"|FALSE
39064|"judgment or choice. Hence, with Leibnitz, the result is a distinction"|FALSE
39064|"between soul and the corporeal (or material), and the identity is only"|FALSE
39064|"like the _copula_ of a judgment, and does not rise or develop into system,"|FALSE
39064|"into the absolute syllogism."|FALSE
39064|"§ 390. The Soul is at first—"|FALSE
39064|"(_a_) In its immediate natural mode—the natural soul, which only _is_."|FALSE
39064|"(_b_) Secondly, it is a soul which _feels_, as individualised, enters into"|FALSE
39064|"correlation with its immediate being, and, in the modes of that being,"|FALSE
39064|"retains an abstract independence."|FALSE
39064|"(_c_) Thirdly, its immediate being—or corporeity—is moulded into it, and"|FALSE
39064|"with that corporeity it exists as _actual_ soul."|FALSE
39064|"(a) The Physical Soul(119)."|FALSE
39064|"§ 391. The soul universal, described, it may be, as an _anima mundi_, a"|FALSE
39064|"world-soul, must not be fixed on that account as a single subject; it is"|FALSE
39064|"rather the universal _substance_ which has its actual truth only in"|FALSE
39064|"individuals and single subjects. Thus, when it presents itself as a single"|FALSE
39064|"soul, it is a single soul which _is_ merely: its only modes are modes of"|FALSE
39064|"natural life. These have, so to speak, behind its ideality a free"|FALSE
39064|"existence: i.e. they are natural objects for consciousness, but objects to"|FALSE
39064|"which the soul as such does not behave as to something external. These"|FALSE
39064|"features rather are _physical qualities_ of which it finds itself"|FALSE
39064|"possessed."|FALSE
39064|"(α) Physical Qualities(120)."|FALSE
39064|"§ 392. While still a “substance” (i.e. a physical soul) the mind (1) takes"|FALSE
39064|"part in the general planetary life, feels the difference of climates, the"|FALSE
39064|"changes of the seasons and the periods of the day, &c. This life of nature"|FALSE
39064|"for the main shows itself only in occasional strain or disturbance of"|FALSE
39064|"mental tone."|FALSE
39064|"In recent times a good deal has been said of the cosmical, sidereal, and"|FALSE
39064|"telluric life of man. In such a sympathy with nature the animals"|FALSE
39064|"essentially live: their specific characters and their particular phases of"|FALSE
39064|"growth depend, in many cases completely, and always more or less, upon it."|FALSE
39064|"In the case of man these points of dependence lose importance, just in"|FALSE
39064|"proportion to his civilisation, and the more his whole frame of soul is"|FALSE
39064|"based upon a substructure of mental freedom. The history of the world is"|FALSE
39064|"not bound up with revolutions in the solar system, any more than the"|FALSE
39064|"destinies of individuals with the positions of the planets."|FALSE
39064|"The difference of climate has a more solid and vigorous influence. But the"|FALSE
39064|"response to the changes of the seasons and hours of the day is found only"|FALSE
39064|"in faint changes of mood, which come expressly to the fore only in morbid"|FALSE
39064|"states (including insanity) and at periods when the self-conscious life"|FALSE
39064|"suffers depression."|FALSE
39064|"In nations less intellectually emancipated, which therefore live more in"|FALSE
39064|"harmony with nature, we find amid their superstitions and aberrations of"|FALSE
39064|"imbecility _a few_ real cases of such sympathy, and on that foundation"|FALSE
39064|"what seems to be marvellous prophetic vision of coming conditions and of"|FALSE
39064|"events arising therefrom. But as mental freedom gets a deeper hold, even"|FALSE
39064|"these few and slight susceptibilities, based upon participation in the"|FALSE
39064|"common life of nature, disappear. Animals and plants, on the contrary,"|FALSE
39064|"remain for ever subject to such influences."|FALSE
39064|"§ 393. (2) According to the concrete differences of the terrestrial globe,"|FALSE
39064|"the general planetary life of the nature-governed mind specialises itself"|FALSE
39064|"and breaks up into the several nature-governed minds which, on the whole,"|FALSE
39064|"give expression to the nature of the geographical continents and"|FALSE
39064|"constitute the diversities of _race_."|FALSE
39064|"The contrast between the earth’s poles, the land towards the north pole"|FALSE
39064|"being more aggregated and preponderant over sea, whereas in the southern"|FALSE
39064|"hemisphere it runs out in sharp points, widely distant from each other,"|FALSE
39064|"introduces into the differences of continents a further modification which"|FALSE
39064|"Treviranus (_Biology_, Part II) has exhibited in the case of the flora and"|FALSE
39064|"fauna."|FALSE
39064|"§ 394. This diversity descends into specialities, that may be termed"|FALSE
39064|"_local_ minds—shown in the outward modes of life and occupation, bodily"|FALSE
39064|"structure and disposition, but still more in the inner tendency and"|FALSE
39064|"capacity of the intellectual and moral character of the several peoples."|FALSE
39064|"Back to the very beginnings of national history we see the several nations"|FALSE
39064|"each possessing a persistent type of its own."|FALSE
39064|"§ 395. (3) The soul is further de-universalised into the individualised"|FALSE
39064|"subject. But this subjectivity is here only considered as a"|FALSE
39064|"differentiation and singling out of the modes which nature gives; we find"|FALSE
39064|"it as the special temperament, talent, character, physiognomy, or other"|FALSE
39064|"disposition and idiosyncrasy, of families or single individuals."|FALSE
39064|"(β) Physical Alterations."|FALSE
39064|"§ 396. Taking the soul as an individual, we find its diversities, as"|FALSE
39064|"alterations in it, the one permanent subject, and as stages in its"|FALSE
39064|"development. As they are at once physical and mental diversities, a more"|FALSE
39064|"concrete definition or description of them would require us to anticipate"|FALSE
39064|"an acquaintance with the formed and matured mind."|FALSE
39064|"The (1) first of these is the natural lapse of the ages in man’s life. He"|FALSE
39064|"begins with _Childhood_—mind wrapt up in itself. His next step is the"|FALSE
39064|"fully-developed antithesis, the strain and struggle of a universality"|FALSE
39064|"which is still subjective (as seen in ideals, fancies, hopes, ambitions)"|FALSE
39064|"against his immediate individuality. And that individuality marks both the"|FALSE
39064|"world which, as it exists, fails to meet his ideal requirements, and the"|FALSE
39064|"position of the individual himself, who is still short of independence and"|FALSE
39064|"not fully equipped for the part he has to play (_Youth_). Thirdly, we see"|FALSE
39064|"man in his true relation to his environment, recognising the objective"|FALSE
39064|"necessity and reasonableness of the world as he finds it,—a world no"|FALSE
39064|"longer incomplete, but able in the work which it collectively achieves to"|FALSE
39064|"afford the individual a place and a security for his performance. By his"|FALSE
39064|"share in this collective work he first is really _somebody_, gaining an"|FALSE
39064|"effective existence and an objective value (_Manhood_). Last of all comes"|FALSE
39064|"the finishing touch to this unity with objectivity: a unity which, while"|FALSE
39064|"on its realist side it passes into the _inertia_ of deadening habit, on"|FALSE
39064|"its idealist side gains freedom from the limited interests and"|FALSE
39064|"entanglements of the outward present (_Old Age_)."|FALSE
39064|"§ 397. (2) Next we find the individual subject to a _real_ antithesis,"|FALSE
39064|"leading it to seek and find _itself_ in _another_ individual. This—the"|FALSE
39064|"_sexual relation_—on a physical basis, shows, on its one side,"|FALSE
39064|"subjectivity remaining in an instinctive and emotional harmony of moral"|FALSE
39064|"life and love, and not pushing these tendencies to an extreme _universal_"|FALSE
39064|"phase, in purposes political, scientific or artistic; and on the other,"|FALSE
39064|"shows an active half, where the individual is the vehicle of a struggle of"|FALSE
39064|"universal and objective interests with the given conditions (both of his"|FALSE
39064|"own existence and of that of the external world), carrying out these"|FALSE
39064|"universal principles into a unity with the world which is his own work."|FALSE
39064|"The sexual tie acquires its moral and spiritual significance and function"|FALSE
39064|"in the _family_."|FALSE
39064|"§ 398. (3) When the individuality, or self-centralised being,"|FALSE
39064|"distinguishes itself from its _mere_ being, this immediate judgment is the"|FALSE
39064|"_waking_ of the soul, which confronts its self-absorbed natural life, in"|FALSE
39064|"the first instance, as one natural quality and state confronts another"|FALSE
39064|"state, viz. _sleep_.—The waking is not merely for the observer, or"|FALSE
39064|"externally distinct from the sleep: it is itself the _judgment_ (primary"|FALSE
39064|"partition) of the individual soul—which is self-existing only as it"|FALSE
39064|"relates its self-existence to its mere existence, distinguishing itself"|FALSE
39064|"from its still undifferentiated universality. The waking state includes"|FALSE
39064|"generally all self-conscious and rational activity in which the mind"|FALSE
39064|"realises its own distinct self.—Sleep is an invigoration of this"|FALSE
39064|"activity—not as a merely negative rest from it, but as a return back from"|FALSE
39064|"the world of specialisation, from dispersion into phases where it has"|FALSE
39064|"grown hard and stiff,—a return into the general nature of subjectivity,"|FALSE
39064|"which is the substance of those specialised energies and their absolute"|FALSE
39064|"master."|FALSE
39064|"The distinction between sleep and waking is one of those _posers_, as they"|FALSE
39064|"may be called, which are often addressed to philosophy:—Napoleon, e.g., on"|FALSE
39064|"a visit to the University of Pavia, put this question to the class of"|FALSE
39064|"ideology. The characterisation given in the section is abstract; it"|FALSE
39064|"primarily treats waking merely as a natural fact, containing the mental"|FALSE
39064|"element _implicite_ but not yet as invested with a special being of its"|FALSE
39064|"own. If we are to speak more concretely of this distinction (in"|FALSE
39064|"fundamentals it remains the same), we must take the self-existence of the"|FALSE
39064|"individual soul in its higher aspects as the Ego of consciousness and as"|FALSE
39064|"intelligent mind. The difficulty raised anent the distinction of the two"|FALSE
39064|"states properly arises, only when we also take into account the dreams in"|FALSE
39064|"sleep and describe these dreams, as well as the mental representations in"|FALSE
39064|"the sober waking consciousness, under one and the same title of mental"|FALSE
39064|"representations. Thus superficially classified as states of mental"|FALSE
39064|"representation the two coincide, because we have lost sight of the"|FALSE
39064|"difference; and in the case of any assignable distinction of waking"|FALSE
39064|"consciousness, we can always return to the trivial remark that all this is"|FALSE
39064|"nothing more than mental idea. But the concrete theory of the waking soul"|FALSE
39064|"in its realised being views it as _consciousness_ and _intellect_: and the"|FALSE
39064|"world of intelligent consciousness is something quite different from a"|FALSE
39064|"picture of mere ideas and images. The latter are in the main only"|FALSE
39064|"externally conjoined, in an unintelligent way, by the laws of the"|FALSE
39064|"so-called _Association of Ideas_; though here and there of course logical"|FALSE
39064|"principles may also be operative. But in the waking state man behaves"|FALSE
39064|"essentially as a concrete ego, an intelligence: and because of this"|FALSE
39064|"intelligence his sense-perception stands before him as a concrete totality"|FALSE
39064|"of features in which each member, each point, takes up its place as at the"|FALSE
39064|"same time determined through and with all the rest. Thus the facts"|FALSE
39064|"embodied in his sensation are authenticated, not by his mere subjective"|FALSE
39064|"representation and distinction of the facts as something external from the"|FALSE
39064|"person, but by virtue of the concrete interconnexion in which each part"|FALSE
39064|"stands with all parts of this complex. The waking state is the concrete"|FALSE
39064|"consciousness of this mutual corroboration of each single factor of its"|FALSE
39064|"content by all the others in the picture as perceived. The consciousness"|FALSE
39064|"of this interdependence need not be explicit and distinct. Still this"|FALSE
39064|"general setting to all sensations is implicitly present in the concrete"|FALSE
39064|"feeling of self.—In order to see the difference of dreaming and waking we"|FALSE
39064|"need only keep in view the Kantian distinction between subjectivity and"|FALSE
39064|"objectivity of mental representation (the latter depending upon"|FALSE
39064|"determination through categories): remembering, as already noted, that"|FALSE
