39064|"treat this visionary state as a sublime mental phase and as a truer state,"|FALSE
39064|"capable of conveying general truths(123)."|FALSE
39064|"(δ) An essential feature of this sensitivity, with its absence of"|FALSE
39064|"intelligent and volitional personality, is this, that it is a state of"|FALSE
39064|"passivity, like that of the child in the womb. The patient in this"|FALSE
39064|"condition is accordingly made, and continues to be, subject to the power"|FALSE
39064|"of another person, the magnetiser; so that when the two are thus in"|FALSE
39064|"psychical _rapport_, the selfless individual, not really a “person,” has"|FALSE
39064|"for his subjective consciousness the consciousness of the other. This"|FALSE
39064|"latter self-possessed individual is thus the effective subjective soul of"|FALSE
39064|"the former, and the genius which may even supply him with a train of"|FALSE
39064|"ideas. That the somnambulist perceives in himself tastes and smells which"|FALSE
39064|"are present in the person with whom he stands _en rapport_, and that he is"|FALSE
39064|"aware of the other inner ideas and present perceptions of the latter as if"|FALSE
39064|"they were his own, shows the substantial identity which the soul (which"|FALSE
39064|"even in its concreteness is also truly immaterial) is capable of holding"|FALSE
39064|"with another. When the substance of both is thus made one, there is only"|FALSE
39064|"one subjectivity of consciousness: the patient has a sort of"|FALSE
39064|"individuality, but it is empty, not on the spot, not actual: and this"|FALSE
39064|"nominal self accordingly derives its whole stock of ideas from the"|FALSE
39064|"sensations and ideas of the other, in whom it sees, smells, tastes, reads,"|FALSE
39064|"and hears. It is further to be noted on this point that the somnambulist"|FALSE
39064|"is thus brought into _rapport_ with two genii and a twofold set of ideas,"|FALSE
39064|"his own and that of the magnetiser. But it is impossible to say precisely"|FALSE
39064|"which sensations and which visions he, in this nominal perception,"|FALSE
39064|"receives, beholds and brings to knowledge from his own inward self, and"|FALSE
39064|"which from the suggestions of the person with whom he stands in relation."|FALSE
39064|"This uncertainty may be the source of many deceptions, and accounts among"|FALSE
39064|"other things for the diversity that inevitably shows itself among"|FALSE
39064|"somnambulists from different countries and under _rapport_ with persons of"|FALSE
39064|"different education, as regards their views on morbid states and the"|FALSE
39064|"methods of cure, or medicines for them, as well as on scientific and"|FALSE
39064|"intellectual topics."|FALSE
39064|"(ε) As in this sensitive substantiality there is no contrast to external"|FALSE
39064|"objectivity, so within itself the subject is so entirely one that all"|FALSE
39064|"varieties of sensation have disappeared, and hence, when the activity of"|FALSE
39064|"the sense-organs is asleep, the “common sense,” or “general feeling”"|FALSE
39064|"specifies itself to several functions; one sees and hears with the"|FALSE
39064|"fingers, and especially with the pit of the stomach, &c."|FALSE
39064|"To comprehend a thing means in the language of practical intelligence to"|FALSE
39064|"be able to trace the series of means intervening between a phenomenon and"|FALSE
39064|"some other existence on which it depends,—to discover what is called the"|FALSE
39064|"ordinary course of nature, in compliance with the laws and relations of"|FALSE
39064|"the intellect, e.g. causality, reasons, &c. The purely sensitive life, on"|FALSE
39064|"the contrary, even when it retains that mere nominal consciousness, as in"|FALSE
39064|"the morbid state alluded to, is just this form of immediacy, without any"|FALSE
39064|"distinctions between subjective and objective, between intelligent"|FALSE
39064|"personality and objective world, and without the aforementioned finite"|FALSE
39064|"ties between them. Hence to understand this intimate conjunction, which,"|FALSE
39064|"though all-embracing, is without any definite points of attachment, is"|FALSE
39064|"impossible, so long as we assume independent personalities, independent"|FALSE
39064|"one of another and of the objective world which is their content—so long"|FALSE
39064|"as we assume the absolute spatial and material externality of one part of"|FALSE
39064|"being to another."|FALSE
39064|"(β) Self-feeling (Sense of Self)(124)."|FALSE
39064|"§ 407. (αα) The sensitive totality is, in its capacity of individual,"|FALSE
39064|"essentially the tendency to distinguish itself in itself, and to wake up"|FALSE
39064|"to the _judgment in itself_, in virtue of which it has _particular_"|FALSE
39064|"feelings and stands as a _subject_ in respect of these aspects of itself."|FALSE
39064|"The subject as such gives these feelings a place as _its own_ in itself."|FALSE
39064|"In these private and personal sensations it is immersed, and at the same"|FALSE
39064|"time, because of the “ideality” of the particulars, it combines itself in"|FALSE
39064|"them with itself as a subjective unit. In this way it is _self-feeling_,"|FALSE
39064|"and is so at the same time only in the _particular feeling_."|FALSE
39064|"§ 408. (ββ) In consequence of the immediacy, which still marks the"|FALSE
39064|"self-feeling, i.e. in consequence of the element of corporeality which is"|FALSE
39064|"still undetached from the mental life, and as the feeling too is itself"|FALSE
39064|"particular and bound up with a special corporeal form, it follows that"|FALSE
39064|"although the subject has been brought to acquire intelligent"|FALSE
39064|"consciousness, it is still susceptible of disease, so far as to remain"|FALSE
39064|"fast in a _special_ phase of its self-feeling, unable to refine it to"|FALSE
39064|"“ideality” and get the better of it. The fully-furnished self of"|FALSE
39064|"intelligent consciousness is a conscious subject, which is consistent in"|FALSE
39064|"itself according to an order and behaviour which follows from its"|FALSE
39064|"individual position and its connexion with the external world, which is no"|FALSE
39064|"less a world of law. But when it is engrossed with a single phase of"|FALSE
39064|"feeling, it fails to assign that phase its proper place and due"|FALSE
39064|"subordination in the individual system of the world which a conscious"|FALSE
39064|"subject is. In this way the subject finds itself in contradiction between"|FALSE
39064|"the totality systematised in its consciousness, and the single phase or"|FALSE
39064|"fixed idea which is not reduced to its proper place and rank. This is"|FALSE
39064|"Insanity or mental Derangement."|FALSE
39064|"In considering insanity we must, as in other cases, anticipate the"|FALSE
39064|"full-grown and intelligent conscious subject, which is at the same time"|FALSE
39064|"the _natural_ self of _self-feeling_. In such a phase the self can be"|FALSE
39064|"liable to the contradiction between its own free subjectivity and a"|FALSE
39064|"particularity which, instead of being “idealised” in the former, remains"|FALSE
39064|"as a fixed element in self-feeling. Mind as such is free, and therefore"|FALSE
39064|"not susceptible of this malady. But in older metaphysics mind was treated"|FALSE
39064|"as a soul, as a thing; and it is only as a thing, i.e. as something"|FALSE
39064|"natural and existent, that it is liable to insanity—the settled fixture of"|FALSE
39064|"some finite element in it. Insanity is therefore a psychical disease, i.e."|FALSE
39064|"a disease of body and mind alike: the commencement may appear to start"|FALSE
39064|"from one more than other, and so also may the cure."|FALSE
39064|"The self-possessed and healthy subject has an active and present"|FALSE
39064|"consciousness of the ordered whole of his individual world, into the"|FALSE
39064|"system of which he subsumes each special content of sensation, idea,"|FALSE
39064|"desire, inclination, &c., as it arises, so as to insert them in their"|FALSE
39064|"proper place. He is the _dominant genius_ over these particularities."|FALSE
39064|"Between this and insanity the difference is like that between waking and"|FALSE
39064|"dreaming: only that in insanity the dream falls within the waking limits,"|FALSE
39064|"and so makes part of the actual self-feeling. Error and that sort of thing"|FALSE
39064|"is a proposition consistently admitted to a place in the objective"|FALSE
39064|"interconnexion of things. In the concrete, however, it is often difficult"|FALSE
39064|"to say where it begins to become derangement. A violent, but groundless"|FALSE
39064|"and senseless outburst of hatred, &c., may, in contrast to a presupposed"|FALSE
39064|"higher self-possession and stability of character, make its victim seem to"|FALSE
39064|"be beside himself with frenzy. But the main point in derangement is the"|FALSE
39064|"contradiction which a feeling with a fixed corporeal embodiment sets up"|FALSE
39064|"against the whole mass of adjustments forming the concrete consciousness."|FALSE
39064|"The mind which is in a condition of mere _being_, and where such being is"|FALSE
39064|"not rendered fluid in its consciousness, is diseased. The contents which"|FALSE
39064|"are set free in this reversion to mere nature are the self-seeking"|FALSE
39064|"affections of the heart, such as vanity, pride, and the rest of the"|FALSE
39064|"passions—fancies and hopes—merely personal love and hatred. When the"|FALSE
39064|"influence of self-possession and of general principles, moral and"|FALSE
39064|"theoretical, is relaxed, and ceases to keep the natural temper under lock"|FALSE
39064|"and key, the earthly elements are set free—that evil which is always"|FALSE
39064|"latent in the heart, because the heart as immediate is natural and"|FALSE
39064|"selfish. It is the evil genius of man which gains the upper hand in"|FALSE
39064|"insanity, but in distinction from and contrast to the better and more"|FALSE
39064|"intelligent part, which is there also. Hence this state is mental"|FALSE
39064|"derangement and distress. The right psychical treatment therefore keeps in"|FALSE
39064|"view the truth that insanity is not an abstract _loss_ of reason (neither"|FALSE
39064|"in the point of intelligence nor of will and its responsibility), but only"|FALSE
39064|"derangement, only a contradiction in a still subsisting reason;—just as"|FALSE
39064|"physical disease is not an abstract, i.e. mere and total, loss of health"|FALSE
39064|"(if it were that, it would be death), but a contradiction in it. This"|FALSE
39064|"humane treatment, no less benevolent than reasonable (the services of"|FALSE
39064|"Pinel towards which deserve the highest acknowledgment), presupposes the"|FALSE
39064|"patient’s rationality, and in that assumption has the sound basis for"|FALSE
39064|"dealing with him on this side—just as in the case of bodily disease the"|FALSE
39064|"physician bases his treatment on the vitality which as such still contains"|FALSE
39064|"health."|FALSE
39064|"(γ) Habit(125)."|FALSE
39064|"§ 409. Self-feeling, immersed in the detail of the feelings (in simple"|FALSE
39064|"sensations, and also desires, instincts, passions, and their"|FALSE
39064|"gratification), is undistinguished from them. But in the self there is"|FALSE
39064|"latent a simple self-relation of ideality, a nominal universality (which"|FALSE
39064|"is the truth of these details): and as so universal, the self is to be"|FALSE
39064|"stamped upon, and made appear in, this life of feeling, yet so as to"|FALSE
39064|"distinguish itself from the particular details, and be a realised"|FALSE
39064|"universality. But this universality is not the full and sterling truth of"|FALSE
39064|"the specific feelings and desires; what they specifically contain is as"|FALSE
39064|"yet left out of account. And so too the particularity is, as now regarded,"|FALSE
39064|"equally formal; it counts only as the _particular being_ or immediacy of"|FALSE
39064|"the soul in opposition to its equally formal and abstract realisation."|FALSE
39064|"This particular being of the soul is the factor of its corporeity; here we"|FALSE
39064|"have it breaking with this corporeity, distinguishing it from"|FALSE
39064|"itself,—itself a _simple_ being,—and becoming the “ideal,” subjective"|FALSE
39064|"substantiality of it,—just as in its latent notion (§ 359) it was the"|FALSE
39064|"substance, and the mere substance, of it."|FALSE
39064|"But this abstract realisation of the soul in its corporeal vehicle is not"|FALSE
39064|"yet the self—not the existence of the universal which is for the"|FALSE
39064|"universal. It is the corporeity reduced to its mere _ideality_; and so far"|FALSE
39064|"only does corporeity belong to the soul as such. That is to say, as space"|FALSE
39064|"and time—the abstract one-outside-another, as, in short, empty space and"|FALSE
39064|"empty time—are only subjective form—pure act of intuition; so that pure"|FALSE
39064|"being (which through the supersession in it of the particularity of the"|FALSE
39064|"corporeity, or of the immediate corporeity as such has realised itself) is"|FALSE
39064|"mere intuition and no more, lacking consciousness, but the basis of"|FALSE
39064|"consciousness. And consciousness it becomes, when the corporeity, of which"|FALSE
39064|"it is the subjective substance, and which still continues to exist, and"|FALSE
39064|"that as a barrier for it, has been absorbed by it, and it has been"|FALSE
39064|"invested with the character of self-centred subject."|FALSE
39064|"§ 410. The soul’s making itself an abstract universal being, and reducing"|FALSE
39064|"the particulars of feelings (and of consciousness) to a mere feature of"|FALSE
39064|"its being is Habit. In this manner the soul has the contents in"|FALSE
39064|"possession, and contains them in such manner that in these features it is"|FALSE
39064|"not as sentient, nor does it stand in relationship with them as"|FALSE
39064|"distinguishing itself from them, nor is absorbed in them, but has them and"|FALSE
39064|"moves in them, without feeling or consciousness of the fact. The soul is"|FALSE
39064|"freed from them, so far as it is not interested in or occupied with them:"|FALSE
39064|"and whilst existing in these forms as its possession, it is at the same"|FALSE
39064|"time open to be otherwise occupied and engaged—say with feeling and with"|FALSE
39064|"mental consciousness in general."|FALSE
39064|"This process of building up the particular and corporeal expressions of"|FALSE
39064|"feeling into the being of the soul appears as a _repetition_ of them, and"|FALSE
39064|"the generation of habit as _practice_. For, this being of the soul, if in"|FALSE
39064|"respect of the natural particular phase it be called an abstract"|FALSE
39064|"universality to which the former is transmuted, is a reflexive"|FALSE
39064|"universality (§ 175); i.e. the one and the same, that recurs in a series"|FALSE
39064|"of units of sensation, is reduced to unity, and this abstract unity"|FALSE
39064|"expressly stated."|FALSE
39064|"Habit, like memory, is a difficult point in mental organisation: habit is"|FALSE
39064|"the mechanism of self-feeling, as memory is the mechanism of intelligence."|FALSE
39064|"The natural qualities and alterations of age, sleep and waking, are"|FALSE
39064|"“immediately” natural: habit, on the contrary, is the mode of feeling (as"|FALSE
39064|"well as intelligence, will, &c., so far as they belong to self-feeling)"|FALSE
39064|"made into a natural and mechanical existence. Habit is rightly called a"|FALSE
39064|"second nature; nature, because it is an immediate being of the soul; a"|FALSE
39064|"second nature, because it is an immediacy created by the soul, impressing"|FALSE
39064|"and moulding the corporeality which enters into the modes of feeling as"|FALSE
39064|"such and into the representations and volitions so far as they have taken"|FALSE
39064|"corporeal form (§ 401)."|FALSE
39064|"In habit the human being’s mode of existence is “natural,” and for that"|FALSE
39064|"reason not free; but still free, so far as the merely natural phase of"|FALSE
39064|"feeling is by habit reduced to a mere being of _his_, and he is no longer"|FALSE
39064|"involuntarily attracted or repelled by it, and so no longer interested,"|FALSE
39064|"occupied, or dependent in regard to it. The want of freedom in habit is"|FALSE
39064|"partly merely formal, as habit merely attaches to the being of the soul;"|FALSE
39064|"partly only relative, so far as it strictly speaking arises only in the"|FALSE
39064|"case of bad habits, or so far as a habit is opposed by another purpose:"|FALSE
39064|"whereas the habit of right and goodness is an embodiment of liberty. The"|FALSE
39064|"main point about Habit is that by its means man gets emancipated from the"|FALSE
39064|"feelings, even in being affected by them. The different forms of this may"|FALSE
39064|"be described as follows: (α) The _immediate_ feeling is negated and"|FALSE
39064|"treated as indifferent. One who gets inured against external sensations"|FALSE
39064|"(frost, heat, weariness of the limbs, &c., sweet tastes, &c.), and who"|FALSE
39064|"hardens the heart against misfortune, acquires a strength which consists"|FALSE
39064|"in this, that although the frost, &c.—or the misfortune—is felt, the"|FALSE
39064|"affection is deposed to a mere externality and immediacy; the universal"|FALSE
39064|"psychical life keeps its own abstract independence in it, and the"|FALSE
39064|"self-feeling as such, consciousness, reflection, and any other purposes"|FALSE
39064|"and activity, are no longer bothered with it. (β) There is indifference"|FALSE
39064|"towards the satisfaction: the desires and impulses are by the _habit_ of"|FALSE
39064|"their satisfaction deadened. This is the rational liberation from them;"|FALSE
39064|"whereas monastic renunciation and forcible interference do not free from"|FALSE
39064|"them, nor are they in conception rational. Of course in all this it is"|FALSE
39064|"assumed that the impulses are kept as the finite modes they naturally are,"|FALSE
39064|"and that they, like their satisfaction, are subordinated as partial"|FALSE
39064|"factors to the reasonable will. (γ) In habit regarded as _aptitude_, or"|FALSE
39064|"skill, not merely has the abstract psychical life to be kept intact _per"|FALSE
39064|"se_, but it has to be imposed as a subjective aim, to be made a power in"|FALSE
39064|"the bodily part, which is rendered subject and thoroughly pervious to it."|FALSE
39064|"Conceived as having the inward purpose of the subjective soul thus imposed"|FALSE
39064|"upon it, the body is treated as an immediate externality and a barrier."|FALSE
39064|"Thus comes out the more decided rupture between the soul as simple"|FALSE
39064|"self-concentration, and its earlier naturalness and immediacy; it has lost"|FALSE
39064|"its original and immediate identity with the bodily nature, and as"|FALSE
39064|"external has first to be reduced to that position. Specific feelings can"|FALSE
39064|"only get bodily shape in a perfectly specific way (§ 401); and the"|FALSE
39064|"immediate portion of body is a particular possibility for a specific aim"|FALSE
39064|"(a particular aspect of its differentiated structure, a particular organ"|FALSE
39064|"of its organic system). To mould such an aim in the organic body is to"|FALSE
39064|"bring out and express the “ideality” which is implicit in matter always,"|FALSE
39064|"and especially so in the specific bodily part, and thus to enable the"|FALSE
39064|"soul, under its volitional and conceptual characters, to exist as"|FALSE
39064|"substance in its corporeity. In this way an aptitude shows the corporeity"|FALSE
39064|"rendered completely pervious, made into an instrument, so that when the"|FALSE
39064|"conception (e.g. a series of musical notes) is in me, then without"|FALSE
39064|"resistance and with ease the body gives them correct utterance."|FALSE
39064|"The form of habit applies to all kinds and grades of mental action. The"|FALSE
39064|"most external of them, i.e. the spatial direction of an individual, viz."|FALSE
39064|"his upright posture, has been by will made a habit—a position taken"|FALSE
39064|"without adjustment and without consciousness—which continues to be an"|FALSE
39064|"affair of his persistent will; for the man stands only because and in so"|FALSE
39064|"far as he wills to stand, and only so long as he wills it without"|FALSE
39064|"consciousness. Similarly our eyesight is the concrete habit which, without"|FALSE
39064|"an express adjustment, combines in a single act the several modifications"|FALSE
39064|"of sensation, consciousness, intuition, intelligence, &c., which make it"|FALSE
39064|"up. Thinking, too, however free and active in its own pure element it"|FALSE
39064|"becomes, no less requires habit and familiarity (this impromptuity or form"|FALSE
39064|"of immediacy), by which it is the property of my single self where I can"|FALSE
39064|"freely and in all directions range. It is through this habit that I come"|FALSE
39064|"to realise my _existence_ as a thinking being. Even here, in this"|FALSE
39064|"spontaneity of self-centred thought, there is a partnership of soul and"|FALSE
39064|"body (hence, want of habit and too-long-continued thinking cause"|FALSE
39064|"headache); habit diminishes this feeling, by making the natural function"|FALSE
39064|"an immediacy of the soul. Habit on an ampler scale, and carried out in the"|FALSE
39064|"strictly intellectual range, is recollection and memory, whereof we shall"|FALSE
39064|"speak later."|FALSE
39064|"Habit is often spoken of disparagingly and called lifeless, casual and"|FALSE
39064|"particular. And it is true that the form of habit, like any other, is open"|FALSE
39064|"to anything we chance to put into it; and it is habit of living which"|FALSE
39064|"brings on death, or, if quite abstract, is death itself: and yet habit is"|FALSE
39064|"indispensable for the _existence_ of all intellectual life in the"|FALSE
39064|"individual, enabling the subject to be a concrete immediacy, an “ideality”"|FALSE
39064|"of soul—enabling the matter of consciousness, religious, moral, &c., to be"|FALSE
39064|"his as _this_ self, _this_ soul, and no other, and be neither a mere"|FALSE
39064|"latent possibility, nor a transient emotion or idea, nor an abstract"|FALSE
39064|"inwardness, cut off from action and reality, but part and parcel of his"|FALSE
39064|"being. In scientific studies of the soul and the mind, habit is usually"|FALSE
39064|"passed over—either as something contemptible—or rather for the further"|FALSE
39064|"reason that it is one of the most difficult questions of psychology."|FALSE
39064|"(c) The Actual Soul.(126)"|FALSE
39064|"§ 411. The Soul, when its corporeity has been moulded and made thoroughly"|FALSE
39064|"its own, finds itself there a _single_ subject; and the corporeity is an"|FALSE
39064|"externality which stands as a predicate, in being related to which, it is"|FALSE
39064|"related to itself. This externality, in other words, represents not"|FALSE
39064|"itself, but the soul, of which it is the _sign_. In this identity of"|FALSE
39064|"interior and exterior, the latter subject to the former, the soul is"|FALSE
39064|"_actual_: in its corporeity it has its free shape, in which it _feels"|FALSE
39064|"itself_ and makes _itself felt_, and which as the Soul’s work of art has"|FALSE
39064|"_human_ pathognomic and physiognomic expression."|FALSE
39064|"Under the head of human expression are included, e.g., the upright figure"|FALSE
39064|"in general, and the formation of the limbs, especially the hand, as the"|FALSE
39064|"absolute instrument, of the mouth—laughter, weeping, &c., and the note of"|FALSE
