39064|"the human figure, though its proximate phase of existence, is at the same"|FALSE
39064|"time in its physiognomic and pathognomic quality something contingent to"|FALSE
39064|"it. To try to raise physiognomy and above all cranioscopy (phrenology) to"|FALSE
39064|"the rank of sciences, was therefore one of the vainest fancies, still"|FALSE
39064|"vainer than a _signatura rerum_, which supposed the shape of a plant to"|FALSE
39064|"afford indication of its medicinal virtue."|FALSE
39064|"§ 412. Implicitly the soul shows the untruth and unreality of matter; for"|FALSE
39064|"the soul, in its concentrated self, cuts itself off from its immediate"|FALSE
39064|"being, placing the latter over against it as a corporeity incapable of"|FALSE
39064|"offering resistance to its moulding influence. The soul, thus setting in"|FALSE
39064|"opposition its being to its (conscious) self, absorbing it, and making it"|FALSE
39064|"its own, has lost the meaning of mere soul, or the “immediacy” of mind."|FALSE
39064|"The actual soul with its sensation and its concrete self-feeling turned"|FALSE
39064|"into habit, has implicitly realised the ’ideality’ of its qualities; in"|FALSE
39064|"this externality it has recollected and inwardised itself, and is infinite"|FALSE
39064|"self-relation. This free universality thus made explicit shows the soul"|FALSE
39064|"awaking to the higher stage of the ego, or abstract universality in so far"|FALSE
39064|"as it is _for_ the abstract universality. In this way it gains the"|FALSE
39064|"position of thinker and subject—specially a subject of the judgment in"|FALSE
39064|"which the ego excludes from itself the sum total of its merely natural"|FALSE
39064|"features as an object, a world external to it,—but with such respect to"|FALSE
39064|"that object that in it it is immediately reflected into itself. Thus soul"|FALSE
39064|"rises to become _Consciousness_."|FALSE
39064|"Sub-Section B. Phenomenology Of Mind. Consciousness."|FALSE
39064|"§ 413. Consciousness constitutes the reflected or correlational grade of"|FALSE
39064|"mind: the grade of mind as _appearance_. _Ego_ is infinite self-relation"|FALSE
39064|"of mind, but as subjective or as self-certainty. The immediate identity of"|FALSE
39064|"the natural soul has been raised to this pure “ideal” self-identity; and"|FALSE
39064|"what the former _contained_ is for this self-subsistent reflection set"|FALSE
39064|"forth as an _object_. The pure abstract freedom of mind lets go from it"|FALSE
39064|"its specific qualities,—the soul’s natural life—to an equal freedom as an"|FALSE
39064|"independent _object_. It is of this latter, as external to it, that the"|FALSE
39064|"_ego_ is in the first instance aware (conscious), and as such it is"|FALSE
39064|"Consciousness. Ego, as this absolute negativity, is implicitly the"|FALSE
39064|"identity in the otherness: the _ego_ is itself that other and stretches"|FALSE
39064|"over the object (as if that object were implicitly cancelled)—it is one"|FALSE
39064|"side of the relationship and the whole relationship—the light, which"|FALSE
39064|"manifests itself and something else too."|FALSE
39064|"§ 414. The self-identity of the mind, thus first made explicit as the Ego,"|FALSE
39064|"is only its abstract formal identity. As _soul_ it was under the phase of"|FALSE
39064|"_substantial_ universality; now, as subjective reflection in itself, it is"|FALSE
39064|"referred to this substantiality as to its negative, something dark and"|FALSE
39064|"beyond it. Hence consciousness, like reciprocal dependence in general, is"|FALSE
39064|"the contradiction between the independence of the two sides and their"|FALSE
39064|"identity in which they are merged into one. The mind as ego is _essence_;"|FALSE
39064|"but since reality, in the sphere of essence, is represented as in"|FALSE
39064|"immediate being and at the same time as “ideal,” it is as consciousness"|FALSE
39064|"only the _appearance_ (phenomenon) of mind."|FALSE
