39064|"universality. The creations of imagination are on all hands recognised as"|FALSE
39064|"such combinations of the mind’s own and inward with the matter of"|FALSE
39064|"intuition; what further and more definite aspects they have is a matter"|FALSE
39064|"for other departments. For the present this internal studio of"|FALSE
39064|"intelligence is only to be looked at in these abstract"|FALSE
39064|"aspects.—Imagination, when regarded as the agency of this unification, is"|FALSE
39064|"reason, but only a nominal reason, because the matter or theme it embodies"|FALSE
39064|"is to imagination _quâ_ imagination a matter of indifference; whilst"|FALSE
39064|"reason _quâ_ reason also insists upon the _truth_ of its content."|FALSE
39064|"Another point calling for special notice is that, when imagination"|FALSE
39064|"elevates the internal meaning to an image and intuition, and this is"|FALSE
39064|"expressed by saying that it gives the former the character of an"|FALSE
39064|"_existent_, the phrase must not seem surprising that intelligence makes"|FALSE
39064|"itself _be_ as a _thing_; for its ideal import is itself, and so is the"|FALSE
39064|"aspect which it imposes upon it. The image produced by imagination of an"|FALSE
39064|"object is a bare mental or subjective intuition: in the sign or symbol it"|FALSE
39064|"adds intuitability proper; and in mechanical memory it completes, so far"|FALSE
39064|"as it is concerned, this form of _being_."|FALSE
39064|"§ 458. In this unity (initiated by intelligence) of an independent"|FALSE
39064|"representation with an intuition, the matter of the latter is, in the"|FALSE
39064|"first instance, something accepted, somewhat immediate or given (e.g. the"|FALSE
39064|"colour of the cockade, &c.). But in the fusion of the two elements, the"|FALSE
39064|"intuition does not count positively or as representing itself, but as"|FALSE
39064|"representative of something else. It is an image, which has received as"|FALSE
39064|"its soul and meaning an independent mental representation. This intuition"|FALSE
39064|"is the _Sign_."|FALSE
39064|"The sign is some immediate intuition, representing a totally different"|FALSE
39064|"import from what naturally belongs to it; it is the pyramid into which a"|FALSE
39064|"foreign soul has been conveyed, and where it is conserved. The _sign_ is"|FALSE
39064|"different from the _symbol_: for in the symbol the original characters (in"|FALSE
39064|"essence and conception) of the visible object are more or less identical"|FALSE
39064|"with the import which it bears as symbol; whereas in the sign, strictly"|FALSE
39064|"so-called, the natural attributes of the intuition, and the connotation of"|FALSE
39064|"which it is a sign, have nothing to do with each other. Intelligence"|FALSE
39064|"therefore gives proof of wider choice and ampler authority in the use of"|FALSE
39064|"intuitions when it treats them as designatory (significative) rather than"|FALSE
39064|"as symbolical."|FALSE
39064|"In logic and psychology, signs and language are usually foisted in"|FALSE
39064|"somewhere as an appendix, without any trouble being taken to display their"|FALSE
39064|"necessity and systematic place in the economy of intelligence. The right"|FALSE
39064|"place for the sign is that just given: where intelligence—which as"|FALSE
39064|"intuiting generates the form of time and space, but is apparently"|FALSE
39064|"recipient of sensible matter, out of which it forms ideas—now gives its"|FALSE
39064|"own original ideas a definite existence from itself, treating the"|FALSE
39064|"intuition (or time and space as filled full) as its own property, deleting"|FALSE
39064|"the connotation which properly and naturally belongs to it, and conferring"|FALSE
39064|"on it an other connotation as its soul and import. This sign-creating"|FALSE
39064|"activity may be distinctively named “productive” Memory (the primarily"|FALSE
39064|"abstract “Mnemosyne”); since memory, which in ordinary life is often used"|FALSE
39064|"as interchangeable and synonymous with remembrance (recollection), and"|FALSE
39064|"even with conception and imagination, has always to do with signs only."|FALSE
39064|"§ 459. The intuition—in its natural phase a something given and given in"|FALSE
39064|"space—acquires, when employed as a sign, the peculiar characteristic of"|FALSE
39064|"existing only as superseded and sublimated. Such is the negativity of"|FALSE
39064|"intelligence; and thus the truer phase of the intuition used as a sign is"|FALSE
39064|"existence in _time_ (but its existence vanishes in the moment of being),"|FALSE
39064|"and if we consider the rest of its external psychical quality, its"|FALSE
39064|"_institution_ by intelligence, but an institution growing out of its"|FALSE
39064|"(anthropological) own naturalness. This institution of the natural is the"|FALSE
39064|"vocal note, where the inward idea manifests itself in adequate utterance."|FALSE
39064|"The vocal note which receives further articulation to express specific"|FALSE
39064|"ideas—speech and, its system, language—gives to sensations, intuitions,"|FALSE
39064|"conceptions, a second and higher existence than they naturally"|FALSE
39064|"possess,—invests them with the right of existence in the ideational realm."|FALSE
39064|"Language here comes under discussion only in the special aspect of a"|FALSE
39064|"product of intelligence for manifesting its ideas in an external medium."|FALSE
39064|"If language had to be treated in its concrete nature, it would be"|FALSE
39064|"necessary for its vocabulary or material part to recall the"|FALSE
39064|"anthropological or psycho-physiological point of view (§ 401), and for the"|FALSE
39064|"grammar or formal portion to anticipate the standpoint of analytic"|FALSE
39064|"understanding. With regard to the elementary _material_ of language, while"|FALSE
39064|"on one hand the theory of mere accident has disappeared, on the other the"|FALSE
39064|"principle of imitation has been restricted to the slight range it actually"|FALSE
39064|"covers—that of vocal objects. Yet one may still hear the German language"|FALSE
39064|"praised for its wealth—that wealth consisting in its special expression"|FALSE
39064|"for special sounds—_Rauschen_, _Sausen_, _Knarren_, &c.;—there have been"|FALSE
39064|"collected more than a hundred such words, perhaps: the humour of the"|FALSE
39064|"moment creates fresh ones when it pleases. Such superabundance in the"|FALSE
39064|"realm of sense and of triviality contributes nothing to form the real"|FALSE
39064|"wealth of a cultivated language. The strictly raw material of language"|FALSE
39064|"itself depends more upon an inward symbolism than a symbolism referring to"|FALSE
39064|"external objects; it depends, i.e. on anthropological articulation, as it"|FALSE
39064|"were the posture in the corporeal act of oral utterance. For each vowel"|FALSE
39064|"and consonant accordingly, as well as for their more abstract elements"|FALSE
39064|"(the posture of lips, palate, tongue in each) and for their combinations,"|FALSE
39064|"people have tried to find the appropriate signification. But these dull"|FALSE
39064|"sub-conscious beginnings are deprived of their original importance and"|FALSE
39064|"prominence by new influences, it may be by external agencies or by the"|FALSE
39064|"needs of civilisation. Having been originally sensuous intuitions, they"|FALSE
39064|"are reduced to signs, and thus have only traces left of their original"|FALSE
39064|"meaning, if it be not altogether extinguished. As to the _formal_ element,"|FALSE
39064|"again, it is the work of analytic intellect which informs language with"|FALSE
39064|"its categories: it is this logical instinct which gives rise to grammar."|FALSE
39064|"The study of languages still in their original state, which we have first"|FALSE
39064|"really begun to make acquaintance with in modern times, has shown on this"|FALSE
39064|"point that they contain a very elaborate grammar and express distinctions"|FALSE
39064|"which are lost or have been largely obliterated in the languages of more"|FALSE
39064|"civilised nations. It seems as if the language of the most civilised"|FALSE
39064|"nations has the most imperfect grammar, and that the same language has a"|FALSE
39064|"more perfect grammar when the nation is in a more uncivilised state than"|FALSE
39064|"when it reaches a higher civilisation. (Cf. W. von Humboldt’s _Essay on"|FALSE
39064|"the Dual_.)"|FALSE
39064|"In speaking of vocal (which is the original) language, we may touch, only"|FALSE
39064|"in passing, upon written language,—a further development in the particular"|FALSE
39064|"sphere of language which borrows the help of an externally practical"|FALSE
39064|"activity. It is from the province of immediate spatial intuition to which"|FALSE
39064|"written language proceeds that it takes and produces the signs (§ 454). In"|FALSE
39064|"particular, hieroglyphics uses spatial figures to designate _ideas_;"|FALSE
39064|"alphabetical writing, on the other hand, uses them to designate vocal"|FALSE
39064|"notes which are already signs. Alphabetical writing thus consists of signs"|FALSE
39064|"of signs,—the words or concrete signs of vocal language being analysed"|FALSE
39064|"into their simple elements, which severally receive"|FALSE
39064|"designation.—Leibnitz’s practical mind misled him to exaggerate the"|FALSE
39064|"advantages which a complete written language, formed on the hieroglyphic"|FALSE
39064|"method (and hieroglyphics are used even where there is alphabetic writing,"|FALSE
39064|"as in our signs for the numbers, the planets, the chemical elements, &c.),"|FALSE
39064|"would have as a universal language for the intercourse of nations and"|FALSE
39064|"especially of scholars. But we may be sure that it was rather the"|FALSE
39064|"intercourse of nations (as was probably the case in Phoenicia, and still"|FALSE
39064|"takes place in Canton—see _Macartney’s Travels_ by Staunton) which"|FALSE
39064|"occasioned the need of alphabetical writing and led to its formation. At"|FALSE
39064|"any rate a comprehensive hieroglyphic language for ever completed is"|FALSE
39064|"impracticable. Sensible objects no doubt admit of permanent signs; but, as"|FALSE
39064|"regards signs for mental objects, the progress of thought and the"|FALSE
39064|"continual development of logic lead to changes in the views of their"|FALSE
39064|"internal relations and thus also of their nature; and this would involve"|FALSE
39064|"the rise of a new hieroglyphical denotation. Even in the case of"|FALSE
39064|"sense-objects it happens that their names, i.e. their signs in vocal"|FALSE
39064|"language, are frequently changed, as e.g. in chemistry and mineralogy. Now"|FALSE
39064|"that it has been forgotten what names properly are, viz. externalities"|FALSE
39064|"which of themselves have no sense, and only get signification as signs,"|FALSE
39064|"and now that, instead of names proper, people ask for terms expressing a"|FALSE
39064|"sort of definition, which is frequently changed capriciously and"|FALSE
39064|"fortuitously, the denomination, i.e. the composite name formed of signs of"|FALSE
39064|"their generic characters or other supposed characteristic properties, is"|FALSE
39064|"altered in accordance with the differences of view with regard to the"|FALSE
39064|"genus or other supposed specific property. It is only a stationary"|FALSE
39064|"civilisation, like the Chinese, which admits of the hieroglyphic language"|FALSE
39064|"of that nation; and its method of writing moreover can only be the lot of"|FALSE
39064|"that small part of a nation which is in exclusive possession of mental"|FALSE
39064|"culture.—The progress of the vocal language depends most closely on the"|FALSE
39064|"habit of alphabetical writing; by means of which only does vocal language"|FALSE
39064|"acquire the precision and purity of its articulation. The imperfection of"|FALSE
39064|"the Chinese vocal language is notorious: numbers of its words possess"|FALSE
39064|"several utterly different meanings, as many as ten and twenty, so that, in"|FALSE
39064|"speaking, the distinction is made perceptible merely by accent and"|FALSE
39064|"intensity, by speaking low and soft or crying out. The European, learning"|FALSE
39064|"to speak Chinese, falls into the most ridiculous blunders before he has"|FALSE
39064|"mastered these absurd refinements of accentuation. Perfection here"|FALSE
39064|"consists in the opposite of that _parler sans accent_ which in Europe is"|FALSE
39064|"justly required of an educated speaker. The hieroglyphic mode of writing"|FALSE
39064|"keeps the Chinese vocal language from reaching that objective precision"|FALSE
39064|"which is gained in articulation by alphabetic writing."|FALSE
39064|"Alphabetic writing is on all accounts the more intelligent: in it the"|FALSE
39064|"_word_—the mode, peculiar to the intellect, of uttering its ideas most"|FALSE
39064|"worthily—is brought to consciousness and made an object of reflection."|FALSE
39064|"Engaging the attention of intelligence, as it does, it is analysed; the"|FALSE
39064|"work of sign-making is reduced to its few simple elements (the primary"|FALSE
39064|"postures of articulation) in which the sense-factor in speech is brought"|FALSE
39064|"to the form of universality, at the same time that in this elementary"|FALSE
39064|"phase it acquires complete precision and purity. Thus alphabetic writing"|FALSE
39064|"retains at the same time the advantage of vocal language, that the ideas"|FALSE
39064|"have names strictly so called: the name is the simple sign for the exact"|FALSE
39064|"idea, i.e. the simple plain idea, not decomposed into its features and"|FALSE
39064|"compounded out of them. Hieroglyphics, instead of springing from the"|FALSE
39064|"direct analysis of sensible signs, like alphabetic writing, arise from an"|FALSE
39064|"antecedent analysis of ideas. Thus a theory readily arises that all ideas"|FALSE
39064|"may be reduced to their elements, or simple logical terms, so that from"|FALSE
39064|"the elementary signs chosen to express these (as, in the case of the"|FALSE
39064|"Chinese _Koua_, the simple straight stroke, and the stroke broken into two"|FALSE
39064|"parts) a hieroglyphic system would be generated by their composition. This"|FALSE
39064|"feature of hieroglyphic—the analytical designations of ideas—which misled"|FALSE
39064|"Leibnitz to regard it as preferable to alphabetic writing is rather in"|FALSE
39064|"antagonism with the fundamental desideratum of language,—the name. To want"|FALSE
39064|"a name means that for the immediate idea (which, however ample a"|FALSE
39064|"connotation it may include, is still for the mind simple in the name), we"|FALSE
39064|"require a simple immediate sign which for its own sake does not suggest"|FALSE
39064|"anything, and has for its sole function to signify and represent sensibly"|FALSE
39064|"the simple idea as such. It is not merely the image-loving and"|FALSE
39064|"image-limited intelligence that lingers over the simplicity of ideas and"|FALSE
39064|"redintegrates them from the more abstract factors into which they have"|FALSE
39064|"been analysed: thought too reduces to the form of a simple thought the"|FALSE
39064|"concrete connotation which it “resumes” and reunites from the mere"|FALSE
39064|"aggregate of attributes to which analysis has reduced it. Both alike"|FALSE
39064|"require such signs, simple in respect of their meaning: signs, which"|FALSE
39064|"though consisting of several letters or syllables and even decomposed into"|FALSE
39064|"such, yet do not exhibit a combination of several ideas.—What has been"|FALSE
39064|"stated is the principle for settling the value of these written languages."|FALSE
39064|"It also follows that in hieroglyphics the relations of concrete mental"|FALSE
39064|"ideas to one another must necessarily be tangled and perplexed, and that"|FALSE
39064|"the analysis of these (and the proximate results of such analysis must"|FALSE
39064|"again be analysed) appears to be possible in the most various and"|FALSE
39064|"divergent ways. Every divergence in analysis would give rise to another"|FALSE
39064|"formation of the written name; just as in modern times (as already noted,"|FALSE
39064|"even in the region of sense) muriatic acid has undergone several changes"|FALSE
39064|"of name. A hieroglyphic written language would require a philosophy as"|FALSE
39064|"stationary as is the civilisation of the Chinese."|FALSE
39064|"What has been said shows the inestimable and not sufficiently appreciated"|FALSE
39064|"educational value of learning to read and write an alphabetic character."|FALSE
39064|"It leads the mind from the sensibly concrete image to attend to the more"|FALSE
39064|"formal structure of the vocal word and its abstract elements, and"|FALSE
39064|"contributes much to give stability and independence to the inward realm of"|FALSE
39064|"mental life. Acquired habit subsequently effaces the peculiarity by which"|FALSE
39064|"alphabetic writing appears, in the interest of vision, as a roundabout way"|FALSE
39064|"to ideas by means of audibility; it makes them a sort of hieroglyphic to"|FALSE
39064|"us, so that in using them we need not consciously realise them by means of"|FALSE
39064|"tones, whereas people unpractised in reading utter aloud what they read in"|FALSE
39064|"order to catch its meaning in the sound. Thus, while (with the faculty"|FALSE
39064|"which transformed alphabetic writing into hieroglyphics) the capacity of"|FALSE
39064|"abstraction gained by the first practice remains, hieroglyphic reading is"|FALSE
39064|"of itself a deaf reading and a dumb writing. It is true that the audible"|FALSE
39064|"(which is in time) and the visible (which is in space), each have their"|FALSE
39064|"own basis, one no less authoritative than the other. But in the case of"|FALSE
39064|"alphabetic writing there is only a _single_ basis: the two aspects occupy"|FALSE
39064|"their rightful relation to each other: the visible language is related to"|FALSE
39064|"the vocal only as a sign, and intelligence expresses itself immediately"|FALSE
39064|"and unconditionally by speaking.—The instrumental function of the"|FALSE
39064|"comparatively non-sensuous element of tone for all ideational work shows"|FALSE
39064|"itself further as peculiarly important in memory which forms the passage"|FALSE
39064|"from representation to thought."|FALSE
39064|"§ 460. The name, combining the intuition (an intellectual production) with"|FALSE
39064|"its signification, is primarily a single transient product; and"|FALSE
39064|"conjunction of the idea (which is inward) with the intuition (which is"|FALSE
39064|"outward) is itself outward. The reduction of this outwardness to"|FALSE
39064|"inwardness is (verbal) Memory."|FALSE
39064|"(γγ) Memory(141)."|FALSE
39064|"§ 461. Under the shape of memory the course of intelligence passes through"|FALSE
39064|"the same inwardising (recollecting) functions, as regards the intuition of"|FALSE
39064|"the _word_, as representation in general does in dealing with the first"|FALSE
39064|"immediate intuition (§ 451). (1) Making its own the synthesis achieved in"|FALSE
39064|"the sign, intelligence, by this inwardising (memorising) elevates the"|FALSE
39064|"_single_ synthesis to a universal, i.e. permanent, synthesis, in which"|FALSE
39064|"name and meaning are for it objectively united, and renders the intuition"|FALSE
39064|"(which the name originally is) a representation. Thus the import"|FALSE
39064|"(connotation) and sign, being identified, form one representation: the"|FALSE
39064|"representation in its inwardness is rendered concrete and gets existence"|FALSE
39064|"for its import: all this being the work of memory which retains names"|FALSE
39064|"(retentive Memory)."|FALSE
39064|"§ 462. The name is thus the thing so far as it exists and counts in the"|FALSE
39064|"ideational realm. (2) In the name, _Reproductive_ memory has and"|FALSE
39064|"recognises the thing, and with the thing it has the name, apart from"|FALSE
39064|"intuition and image. The name, as giving an _existence_ to the content in"|FALSE
39064|"intelligence, is the externality of intelligence to itself; and the"|FALSE
39064|"inwardising or recollection of the name, i.e. of an intuition of"|FALSE
39064|"intellectual origin, is at the same time a self-externalisation to which"|FALSE
39064|"intelligence reduces itself on its own ground. The association of the"|FALSE
39064|"particular names lies in the meaning of the features sensitive,"|FALSE
39064|"representative, or cogitant,—series of which the intelligence traverses as"|FALSE
39064|"it feels, represents, or thinks."|FALSE
39064|"Given the name lion, we need neither the actual vision of the animal, nor"|FALSE
39064|"its image even: the name alone, if we _understand_ it, is the unimaged"|FALSE
39064|"simple representation. We _think_ in names."|FALSE
39064|"The recent attempts—already, as they deserved, forgotten—to rehabilitate"|FALSE
39064|"the Mnemonic of the ancients, consist in transforming names into images,"|FALSE
39064|"and thus again deposing memory to the level of imagination. The place of"|FALSE
39064|"the power of memory is taken by a permanent tableau of a series of images,"|FALSE
39064|"fixed in the imagination, to which is then attached the series of ideas"|FALSE
39064|"forming the composition to be learned by rote. Considering the"|FALSE
39064|"heterogeneity between the import of these ideas and those permanent"|FALSE
39064|"images, and the speed with which the attachment has to be made, the"|FALSE
39064|"attachment cannot be made otherwise than by shallow, silly, and utterly"|FALSE
39064|"accidental links. Not merely is the mind put to the torture of being"|FALSE
39064|"worried by idiotic stuff, but what is thus learnt by rote is just as"|FALSE
39064|"quickly forgotten, seeing that the same tableau is used for getting by"|FALSE
39064|"rote every other series of ideas, and so those previously attached to it"|FALSE
39064|"are effaced. What is mnemonically impressed is not like what is retained"|FALSE
39064|"in memory really got by heart, i.e. strictly produced from within"|FALSE
39064|"outwards, from the deep pit of the ego, and thus recited, but is, so to"|FALSE
39064|"speak, read off the tableau of fancy.—Mnemonic is connected with the"|FALSE
39064|"common prepossession about memory, in comparison with fancy and"|FALSE
39064|"imagination; as if the latter were a higher and more intellectual activity"|FALSE
39064|"than memory. On the contrary, memory has ceased to deal with an image"|FALSE
39064|"derived from intuition,—the immediate and incomplete mode of intelligence;"|FALSE
39064|"it has rather to do with an object which is the product of intelligence"|FALSE
39064|"itself,—such a _without book_(142) as remains locked up in the"|FALSE
39064|"_within-book_(143) of intelligence, and is, within intelligence, only its"|FALSE
39064|"outward and existing side."|FALSE
39064|"§ 463. (3) As the interconnexion of the names lies in the meaning, the"|FALSE
39064|"conjunction of their meaning with the reality as names is still an"|FALSE
39064|"(external) synthesis; and intelligence in this its externality has not"|FALSE
39064|"made a complete and simple return into self. But intelligence is the"|FALSE
39064|"universal,—the single plain truth of its particular self-divestments; and"|FALSE
39064|"its consummated appropriation of them abolishes that distinction between"|FALSE
39064|"meaning and name. This extreme inwardising of representation is the"|FALSE
39064|"supreme self-divestment of intelligence, in which it renders itself the"|FALSE
39064|"mere _being_, the universal space of names as such, i.e. of meaningless"|FALSE
39064|"words. The ego, which is this abstract being, is, because subjectivity, at"|FALSE
39064|"the same time the power over the different names,—the link which, having"|FALSE
39064|"nothing in itself, fixes in itself series of them and keeps them in stable"|FALSE
39064|"order. So far as they merely _are_, and intelligence is here itself this"|FALSE
39064|"_being_ of theirs, its power is a merely abstract subjectivity,—memory;"|FALSE
39064|"which, on account of the complete externality in which the members of such"|FALSE
39064|"series stand to one another, and because it is itself this externality"|FALSE
39064|"(subjective though that be), is called mechanical (§ 195)."|FALSE
39064|"A composition is, as we know, not thoroughly conned by rote, until one"|FALSE
39064|"attaches no meaning to the words. The recitation of what has been thus got"|FALSE
39064|"by heart is therefore of course accentless. The correct accent, if it is"|FALSE
39064|"introduced, suggests the meaning: but this introduction of the"|FALSE
39064|"signification of an idea disturbs the mechanical nexus and therefore"|FALSE
39064|"easily throws out the reciter. The faculty of conning by rote series of"|FALSE
39064|"words, with no principle governing their succession, or which are"|FALSE
39064|"separately meaningless, e.g. a series of proper names, is so supremely"|FALSE
39064|"marvellous, because it is the very essence of mind to have its wits about"|FALSE
39064|"it; whereas in this case the mind is estranged in itself, and its action"|FALSE
39064|"is like machinery. But it is only as uniting subjectivity with objectivity"|FALSE
39064|"that the mind has its wits about it. Whereas in the case before us, after"|FALSE
39064|"it has in intuition been at first so external as to pick up its facts"|FALSE
39064|"ready-made, and in representation inwardises or recollects this datum and"|FALSE
39064|"makes it its own,—it proceeds as memory to make itself external in itself,"|FALSE
39064|"so that what is its own assumes the guise of something found. Thus one of"|FALSE
39064|"the two dynamic factors of thought, viz. objectivity, is here put in"|FALSE
39064|"intelligence itself as a quality of it.—It is only a step further to treat"|FALSE
39064|"memory as mechanical—the act implying no intelligence—in which case it is"|FALSE
39064|"only justified by its uses, its indispensability perhaps for other"|FALSE
39064|"purposes and functions of mind. But by so doing we overlook the proper"|FALSE
39064|"signification it has in the mind."|FALSE
39064|"§ 464. If it is to be the fact and true objectivity, the mere name as an"|FALSE
39064|"existent requires something else,—to be interpreted by the representing"|FALSE
39064|"intellect. Now in the shape of mechanical memory, intelligence is at once"|FALSE
39064|"that external objectivity and the meaning. In this way intelligence is"|FALSE
39064|"explicitly made an _existence_ of this identity, i.e. it is explicitly"|FALSE
39064|"active as such an identity which as reason it is implicitly. Memory is in"|FALSE
39064|"this manner the passage into the function of _thought_, which no longer"|FALSE
39064|"has a _meaning_, i.e. its objectivity is no longer severed from the"|FALSE
39064|"subjective, and its inwardness does not need to go outside for its"|FALSE
39064|"existence."|FALSE
39064|"The German language has etymologically assigned memory (_Gedächtniß_), of"|FALSE
39064|"which it has become a foregone conclusion to speak contemptuously, the"|FALSE
39064|"high position of direct kindred with thought (_Gedanke_).—It is not matter"|FALSE
39064|"of chance that the young have a better memory than the old, nor is their"|FALSE
39064|"memory solely exercised for the sake of utility. The young have a good"|FALSE
39064|"memory because they have not yet reached the stage of reflection; their"|FALSE
39064|"memory is exercised with or without design so as to level the ground of"|FALSE
39064|"their inner life to pure being or to pure space in which the fact, the"|FALSE
39064|"implicit content, may reign and unfold itself with no antithesis to a"|FALSE
39064|"subjective inwardness. Genuine ability is in youth generally combined with"|FALSE
39064|"a good memory. But empirical statements of this sort help little towards a"|FALSE
39064|"knowledge of what memory intrinsically is. To comprehend the position and"|FALSE
39064|"meaning of memory and to understand its organic interconnexion with"|FALSE
39064|"thought is one of the hardest points, and hitherto one quite unregarded in"|FALSE
39064|"the theory of mind. Memory _quâ_ memory is itself the merely _external_"|FALSE
39064|"mode, or merely _existential_ aspect of thought, and thus needs a"|FALSE
39064|"complementary element. The passage from it to thought is to our view and"|FALSE
39064|"implicitly the identity of reason with this existential mode: an identity"|FALSE
39064|"from which it follows that reason only exists in a subject, and as the"|FALSE
39064|"function of that subject. Thus active reason is _Thinking_."|FALSE
39064|"(γ) Thinking(144)."|FALSE
39064|"§ 465. Intelligence is recognitive: it cognises an intuition, but only"|FALSE
39064|"because that intuition is already its own (§ 454); and in the name it"|FALSE
39064|"re-discovers the fact (§ 462): but now it finds _its_ universal in the"|FALSE
39064|"double signification of the universal as such, and of the universal as"|FALSE
39064|"immediate or as being,—finds i.e. the genuine universal which is its own"|FALSE
39064|"unity overlapping and including its other, viz. being. Thus intelligence"|FALSE
39064|"is explicitly, and on its own part cognitive: _virtually_ it is the"|FALSE
39064|"universal,—its product (the thought) is the thing: it is a plain identity"|FALSE
39064|"of subjective and objective. It knows that what is _thought_, _is_, and"|FALSE
39064|"that what _is_, only _is_ in so far as it is a thought (§ 521); the"|FALSE
39064|"thinking of intelligence is to _have thoughts_: these are as its content"|FALSE
39064|"and object."|FALSE
39064|"§ 466. But cognition by thought is still in the first instance formal: the"|FALSE
39064|"universality and its being is the plain subjectivity of intelligence. The"|FALSE
39064|"thoughts therefore are not yet fully and freely determinate, and the"|FALSE
39064|"representations which have been inwardised to thoughts are so far still"|FALSE
39064|"the given content."|FALSE
39064|"§ 467. As dealing with this given content, thought is (α) _understanding_"|FALSE
39064|"with its formal identity, working up the representations, that have been"|FALSE
39064|"memorised, into species, genera, laws, forces, &c., in short into"|FALSE
39064|"categories,—thus indicating that the raw material does not get the truth"|FALSE
39064|"of its being save in these thought-forms. As intrinsically infinite"|FALSE
39064|"negativity, thought is (β) essentially an act of partition,—_judgment_,"|FALSE
39064|"which however does not break up the concept again into the old antithesis"|FALSE
39064|"of universality and being, but distinguishes on the lines supplied by the"|FALSE
39064|"interconnexions peculiar to the concept. Thirdly (γ), thought supersedes"|FALSE
39064|"the formal distinction and institutes at the same time an identity of the"|FALSE
39064|"differences,—thus being nominal _reason_ or inferential understanding."|FALSE
39064|"Intelligence, as the act of thought, cognises. And (α) understanding out"|FALSE
39064|"of its generalities (the categories) _explains_ the individual, and is"|FALSE
39064|"then said to comprehend or understand itself: (β) in the judgment it"|FALSE
39064|"explains the individual to be an universal (species, genus). In these"|FALSE
39064|"forms the _content_ appears as given: (γ) but in inference (syllogism) it"|FALSE
39064|"characterises a content from itself, by superseding that form-difference."|FALSE
39064|"With the perception of the necessity, the last immediacy still attaching"|FALSE
39064|"to formal thought has vanished."|FALSE
39064|"In _Logic_ there was thought, but in its implicitness, and as reason"|FALSE
39064|"develops itself in this distinction-lacking medium. So in _consciousness_"|FALSE
39064|"thought occurs as a stage (§ 437 note). Here reason is as the truth of the"|FALSE
39064|"antithetical distinction, as it had taken shape within the mind’s own"|FALSE
39064|"limits. Thought thus recurs again and again in these different parts of"|FALSE
39064|"philosophy, because these parts are different only through the medium they"|FALSE
39064|"are in and the antithesis they imply; while thought is this one and the"|FALSE
39064|"same centre, to which as to their truth the antithesis return."|FALSE
39064|"§ 468. Intelligence which as theoretical appropriates an immediate mode of"|FALSE
39064|"being, is, now that it has completed _taking possession_, in its own"|FALSE
39064|"_property_: the last negation of immediacy has implicitly required that"|FALSE
39064|"the intelligence shall itself determine its content. Thus thought, as free"|FALSE
39064|"notion, is now also free in point of _content_. But when intelligence is"|FALSE
39064|"aware that it is determinative of the content, which is _its_ mode no less"|FALSE
39064|"than it is a mode of being, it is Will."|FALSE
39064|"(b) Mind Practical(145)."|FALSE
39064|"§ 469. As will, the mind is aware that it is the author of its own"|FALSE
39064|"conclusions, the origin of its self-fulfilment. Thus fulfilled, this"|FALSE
39064|"independency or individuality form the side of existence or of _reality_"|FALSE
39064|"for the Idea of mind. As will, the mind steps into actuality; whereas as"|FALSE
39064|"cognition it is on the soil of notional generality. Supplying its own"|FALSE
39064|"content, the will is self-possessed, and in the widest sense free: this is"|FALSE
39064|"its characteristic trait. Its finitude lies in the formalism that the"|FALSE
39064|"spontaneity of its self-fulfilment means no more than a general and"|FALSE
39064|"abstract ownness, not yet identified with matured reason. It is the"|FALSE
39064|"function of the essential will to bring liberty to exist in the formal"|FALSE
39064|"will, and it is therefore the aim of that formal will to fill itself with"|FALSE
39064|"its essential nature, i.e. to make liberty its pervading character,"|FALSE
39064|"content, and aim, as well as its sphere of existence. The essential"|FALSE
39064|"freedom of will is, and must always be, a thought: hence the way by which"|FALSE
39064|"will can make itself objective mind is to rise to be a thinking will,—to"|FALSE
39064|"give itself the content which it can only have as it thinks itself."|FALSE
39064|"True liberty, in the shape of moral life, consists in the will finding its"|FALSE
39064|"purpose in a universal content, not in subjective or selfish interests."|FALSE
39064|"But such a content is only possible in thought and through thought: it is"|FALSE
39064|"nothing short of absurd to seek to banish thought from the moral,"|FALSE
39064|"religious, and law-abiding life."|FALSE
39064|"§ 470. Practical mind, considered at first as formal or immediate will,"|FALSE
39064|"contains a double ought—(1) in the contrast which the new mode of being"|FALSE
39064|"projected outward by the will offers to the immediate positivity of its"|FALSE
39064|"old existence and condition,—an antagonism which in consciousness grows to"|FALSE
39064|"correlation with external objects. (2) That first self-determination,"|FALSE
39064|"being itself immediate, is not at once elevated into a thinking"|FALSE
39064|"universality: the latter, therefore, virtually constitutes an obligation"|FALSE
39064|"on the former in point of form, as it may also constitute it in point of"|FALSE
39064|"matter;—a distinction which only exists for the observer."|FALSE
39064|"(α) Practical Sense or Feeling(146)."|FALSE
39064|"§ 471. The autonomy of the practical mind at first is immediate and"|FALSE
39064|"therefore formal, i.e. it _finds_ itself as an _individuality_ determined"|FALSE
39064|"in _its_ inward _nature_. It is thus “practical feeling,” or instinct of"|FALSE
39064|"action. In this phase, as it is at bottom a subjectivity simply identical"|FALSE
39064|"with reason, it has no doubt a rational content, but a content which as it"|FALSE
39064|"stands is individual, and for that reason also natural, contingent and"|FALSE
39064|"subjective,—a content which may be determined quite as much by mere"|FALSE
39064|"personalities of want and opinion, &c., and by the subjectivity which"|FALSE
39064|"selfishly sets itself against the universal, as it may be virtually in"|FALSE
39064|"conformity with reason."|FALSE
39064|"An appeal is sometimes made to the sense (feeling) of right and morality,"|FALSE
39064|"as well as of religion, which man is alleged to possess,—to his benevolent"|FALSE
39064|"dispositions,—and even to his heart generally,—i.e. to the subject so far"|FALSE
39064|"as the various practical feelings are in it all combined. So far as this"|FALSE
39064|"appeal implies (1) that these ideas are immanent in his own self, and (2)"|FALSE
39064|"that when feeling is opposed to the logical understanding, it, and not the"|FALSE
39064|"partial abstractions of the latter, _may_ be the _totality_—the appeal has"|FALSE
39064|"a legitimate meaning. But on the other hand feeling too _may_ be onesided,"|FALSE
39064|"unessential and bad. The rational, which exists in the shape of"|FALSE
39064|"rationality when it is apprehended by thought, is the same content as the"|FALSE
39064|"_good_ practical feeling has, but presented in its universality and"|FALSE
39064|"necessity, in its objectivity and truth."|FALSE
39064|"Thus it is on the one hand _silly_ to suppose that in the passage from"|FALSE
39064|"feeling to law and duty there is any loss of import and excellence; it is"|FALSE
39064|"this passage which lets feeling first reach its truth. It is equally silly"|FALSE
39064|"to consider intellect as superfluous or even harmful to feeling, heart,"|FALSE
39064|"and will; the truth and, what is the same thing, the actual rationality of"|FALSE
39064|"the heart and will can only be at home in the universality of intellect,"|FALSE
39064|"and not in the singleness of feeling as feeling. If feelings are of the"|FALSE
39064|"right sort, it is because of their quality or content,—which is right only"|FALSE
39064|"so far as it is intrinsically universal or has its source in the thinking"|FALSE
39064|"mind. The difficulty for the logical intellect consists in throwing off"|FALSE
39064|"the separation it has arbitrarily imposed between the several faculties of"|FALSE
39064|"feeling and thinking mind, and coming to see that in the human being there"|FALSE
39064|"is only _one_ reason, in feeling, volition, and thought. Another"|FALSE
39064|"difficulty connected with this is found in the fact that the Ideas which"|FALSE
39064|"are the special property of the thinking mind, viz. God, law and morality,"|FALSE
39064|"can also be _felt_. But feeling is only the form of the immediate and"|FALSE
39064|"peculiar individuality of the subject, in which these facts, like any"|FALSE
39064|"other objective facts (which consciousness also sets over against itself),"|FALSE
39064|"may be placed."|FALSE
39064|"On the other hand, it is _suspicious_ or even worse to cling to feeling"|FALSE
39064|"and heart in place of the intelligent rationality of law, right and duty;"|FALSE
39064|"because all that the former holds more than the latter is only the"|FALSE
39064|"particular subjectivity with its vanity and caprice. For the same reason"|FALSE
39064|"it is out of place in a scientific treatment of the feelings to deal with"|FALSE
39064|"anything beyond their form, and to discuss their content; for the latter,"|FALSE
39064|"when thought, is precisely what constitutes, in their universality and"|FALSE
39064|"necessity, the rights and duties which are the true works of mental"|FALSE
39064|"autonomy. So long as we study practical feelings and dispositions"|FALSE
39064|"specially, we have only to deal with the selfish, bad, and evil; it is"|FALSE
39064|"these alone which belong to the individuality which retains its opposition"|FALSE
39064|"to the universal: their content is the reverse of rights and duties, and"|FALSE
39064|"precisely in that way do they—but only in antithesis to the latter—retain"|FALSE
39064|"a speciality of their own."|FALSE
39064|"§ 472. The “Ought” of practical feeling is the claim of its essential"|FALSE
39064|"autonomy to control some existing mode of fact—which is assumed to be"|FALSE
39064|"worth nothing save as adapted to that claim. But as both, in their"|FALSE
39064|"immediacy, lack objective determination, this relation of the"|FALSE
39064|"_requirement_ to existent fact is the utterly subjective and superficial"|FALSE
39064|"feeling of pleasant or unpleasant."|FALSE
39064|"Delight, joy, grief, &c., shame, repentance, contentment, &c., are partly"|FALSE
39064|"only modifications of the formal “practical feeling” in _general_, but are"|FALSE
39064|"partly different in the features that give the special tone and character"|FALSE
39064|"mode to their “Ought.”"|FALSE
39064|"The celebrated question as to the origin of evil in the world, so far at"|FALSE
39064|"least as evil is understood to mean what is disagreeable and painful"|FALSE
39064|"merely, arises on this stage of the formal practical feeling. Evil is"|FALSE
39064|"nothing but the incompatibility between what is and what ought to be."|FALSE
39064|"“Ought” is an ambiguous term,—indeed infinitely so, considering that"|FALSE
39064|"casual aims may also come under the form of Ought. But where the objects"|FALSE
39064|"sought are thus casual, evil only executes what is rightfully due to the"|FALSE
39064|"vanity and nullity of their planning: for they themselves were radically"|FALSE
39064|"evil. The finitude of life and mind is seen in their judgment: the"|FALSE
39064|"contrary which is separated from them they also have as a negative in"|FALSE
39064|"them, and thus they are the contradiction called evil. In the dead there"|FALSE
39064|"is neither evil nor pain: for in inorganic nature the intelligible unity"|FALSE
39064|"(concept) does not confront its existence and does not in the difference"|FALSE
39064|"at the same time remain its permanent subject. Whereas in life, and still"|FALSE
39064|"more in mind, we have this immanent distinction present: hence arises the"|FALSE
39064|"Ought: and this negativity, subjectivity, ego, freedom are the principles"|FALSE
39064|"of evil and pain. Jacob Böhme viewed egoity (selfhood) as pain and"|FALSE
39064|"torment, and as the fountain of nature and of spirit."|FALSE
39064|"(β) The Impulses and Choice(147)."|FALSE
39064|"§ 473. The practical ought is a “real” judgment. Will, which is"|FALSE
39064|"essentially self-determination, finds in the conformity—as immediate and"|FALSE
39064|"merely _found_ to hand—of the existing mode to its requirement a negation,"|FALSE
39064|"and something inappropriate to it. If the will is to satisfy itself, if"|FALSE
39064|"the implicit unity of the universality and the special mode is to be"|FALSE
39064|"realised, the conformity of its inner requirement and of the existent"|FALSE
39064|"thing ought to be its act and institution. The will, as regards the form"|FALSE
39064|"of its content, is at first still a natural will, directly identical with"|FALSE
39064|"its specific mode:—natural _impulse_ and _inclination_. Should, however,"|FALSE
39064|"the totality of the practical spirit throw itself into a single one of the"|FALSE
39064|"many restricted forms of impulse, each being always in conflict to"|FALSE
39064|"another, it is _passion_."|FALSE
39064|"§ 474. Inclinations and passions embody the same constituent features as"|FALSE
39064|"the practical feeling. Thus, while on one hand they are based on the"|FALSE
39064|"rational nature of the mind; they on the other, as part and parcel of the"|FALSE
39064|"still subjective and single will, are infected with contingency, and"|FALSE
39064|"appear as particular to stand to the individual and to each other in an"|FALSE
39064|"external relation and with a necessity which creates bondage."|FALSE
39064|"The special note in _passion_ is its restriction to one special mode of"|FALSE
39064|"volition, in which the whole subjectivity of the individual is merged, be"|FALSE
39064|"the value of that mode what it may. In consequence of this formalism,"|FALSE
39064|"passion is neither good nor bad; the title only states that a subject has"|FALSE
39064|"thrown his whole soul,—his interests of intellect, talent, character,"|FALSE
39064|"enjoyment,—on one aim and object. Nothing great has been and nothing great"|FALSE
39064|"can be accomplished without passion. It is only a dead, too often, indeed,"|FALSE
39064|"a hypocritical moralising which inveighs against the form of passion as"|FALSE
39064|"such."|FALSE
39064|"But with regard to the inclinations, the question is directly raised,"|FALSE
39064|"Which are good and bad?—Up to what degree the good continue good;—and (as"|FALSE
39064|"there are many, each with its private range) In what way have they, being"|FALSE
39064|"all in one subject and hardly all, as experience shows, admitting of"|FALSE
39064|"gratification, to suffer at least reciprocal restriction? And, first of"|FALSE
39064|"all, as regards the numbers of these impulses and propensities, the case"|FALSE
39064|"is much the same as with the psychical powers, whose aggregate is to form"|FALSE
39064|"the mind theoretical,—an aggregate which is now increased by the host of"|FALSE
39064|"impulses. The nominal rationality of impulse and propensity lies merely in"|FALSE
39064|"their general impulse not to be subjective merely, but to get realised,"|FALSE
39064|"overcoming the subjectivity by the subject’s own agency. Their genuine"|FALSE
39064|"rationality cannot reveal its secret to a method of outer reflection which"|FALSE
39064|"pre-supposes a number of _independent_ innate tendencies and immediate"|FALSE
39064|"instincts, and therefore is wanting in a single principle and final"|FALSE
39064|"purpose for them. But the immanent “reflection” of mind itself carries it"|FALSE
39064|"beyond their particularity and their natural immediacy, and gives their"|FALSE
39064|"contents a rationality and objectivity, in which they exist as necessary"|FALSE
39064|"ties of social relation, as rights and duties. It is this objectification"|FALSE
39064|"which evinces their real value, their mutual connexions, and their truth."|FALSE
39064|"And thus it was a true perception when Plato (especially including as he"|FALSE
39064|"did the mind’s whole nature under its right) showed that the full reality"|FALSE
39064|"of justice could be exhibited only in the _objective_ phase of justice,"|FALSE
39064|"viz. in the construction of the State as the ethical life."|FALSE
39064|"The answer to the question, therefore, What are the good and rational"|FALSE
39064|"propensities, and how they are to be co-ordinated with each other?"|FALSE
