39064|"together with it: the concept accordingly perfected to the Idea. Liberty,"|FALSE
39064|"shaped into the actuality of a world, receives the _form of Necessity_ the"|FALSE
39064|"deeper substantial nexus of which is the system or organisation of the"|FALSE
39064|"principles of liberty, whilst its phenomenal nexus is power or authority,"|FALSE
39064|"and the sentiment of obedience awakened in consciousness."|FALSE
39064|"§ 485. This unity of the rational will with the single will (this being"|FALSE
39064|"the peculiar and immediate medium in which the former is actualised)"|FALSE
39064|"constitutes the simple actuality of liberty. As it (and its content)"|FALSE
39064|"belongs to thought, and is the virtual _universal_, the content has its"|FALSE
39064|"right and true character only in the form of universality. When invested"|FALSE
39064|"with this character for the intelligent consciousness, or instituted as an"|FALSE
39064|"authoritative power, it is a _Law_(150). When, on the other hand, the"|FALSE
39064|"content is freed from the mixedness and fortuitousness, attaching to it in"|FALSE
39064|"the practical feeling and in impulse, and is set and grafted in the"|FALSE
39064|"individual will, not in the form of impulse, but in its universality, so"|FALSE
39064|"as to become its habit, temper and character, it exists as manner and"|FALSE
39064|"custom, or _Usage_(151)."|FALSE
39064|"§ 486. This “reality,” in general, where free will has _existence_, is the"|FALSE
39064|"_Law_ (Right),—the term being taken in a comprehensive sense not merely as"|FALSE
39064|"the limited juristic law, but as the actual body of all the conditions of"|FALSE
39064|"freedom. These conditions, in relation to the _subjective_ will, where"|FALSE
39064|"they, being universal, ought to have and can only have their existence,"|FALSE
39064|"are its _Duties_; whereas as its temper and habit they are _Manners_. What"|FALSE
39064|"is a right is also a duty, and what is a duty, is also a right. For a mode"|FALSE
39064|"of existence is a right, only as a consequence of the free substantial"|FALSE
39064|"will: and the same content of fact, when referred to the will"|FALSE
39064|"distinguished as subjective and individual, is a duty. It is the same"|FALSE
39064|"content which the subjective consciousness recognises as a duty, and"|FALSE
39064|"brings into existence in these several wills. The finitude of the"|FALSE
39064|"objective will thus creates the semblance of a distinction between rights"|FALSE
39064|"and duties."|FALSE
39064|"In the phenomenal range right and duty are _correlata_, at least in the"|FALSE
39064|"sense that to a right on my part corresponds a duty in some one else. But,"|FALSE
39064|"in the light of the concept, my right to a thing is not merely possession,"|FALSE
39064|"but as possession by a _person_ it is _property_, or legal possession, and"|FALSE
39064|"it is a _duty_ to possess things as _property_, i.e. to be as a person."|FALSE
39064|"Translated into the phenomenal relationship, viz. relation to another"|FALSE
39064|"person—this grows into the duty of some one _else_ to respect _my_ right."|FALSE
39064|"In the morality of the conscience, duty in general is in me—a free"|FALSE
39064|"subject—at the same time a right of my subjective will or disposition. But"|FALSE
39064|"in this individualist moral sphere, there arises the division between what"|FALSE
39064|"is only inward purpose (disposition or intention), which only has its"|FALSE
39064|"being in me and is merely subjective duty, and the actualisation of that"|FALSE
39064|"purpose: and with this division a contingency and imperfection which makes"|FALSE
39064|"the inadequacy of mere individualistic morality. In social ethics these"|FALSE
39064|"two parts have reached their truth, their absolute unity; although even"|FALSE
39064|"right and duty return to one another and combine by means of certain"|FALSE
39064|"adjustments and under the guise of necessity. The rights of the father of"|FALSE
39064|"the family over its members are equally duties towards them; just as the"|FALSE
39064|"children’s duty of obedience is their right to be educated to the liberty"|FALSE
39064|"of manhood. The penal judicature of a government, its rights of"|FALSE
39064|"administration, &c., are no less its duties to punish, to administer, &c.;"|FALSE
39064|"as the services of the members of the State in dues, military services,"|FALSE
39064|"&c., are duties and yet their right to the protection of their private"|FALSE
39064|"property and of the general substantial life in which they have their"|FALSE
39064|"root. All the aims of society and the State are the private aim of the"|FALSE
39064|"individuals. But the set of adjustments, by which their duties come back"|FALSE
39064|"to them as the exercise and enjoyment of right, produces an appearance of"|FALSE
39064|"diversity: and this diversity is increased by the variety of shapes which"|FALSE
39064|"value assumes in the course of exchange, though it remains intrinsically"|FALSE
39064|"the same. Still it holds fundamentally good that he who has no rights has"|FALSE
39064|"no duties and _vice versa_."|FALSE
39064|"Distribution."|FALSE
39064|"§ 487. The free will is"|FALSE
39064|"A. itself at first immediate, and hence as a single being—the _person_:"|FALSE
39064|"the existence which the person gives to its liberty is _property_. The"|FALSE
39064|"_Right as_ right (law) is _formal, abstract right_."|FALSE
39064|"B. When the will is reflected into self, so as to have its existence"|FALSE
39064|"inside it, and to be thus at the same time characterised as a"|FALSE
39064|"_particular_, it is the right of the _subjective_ will, _morality_ of the"|FALSE
39064|"individual conscience."|FALSE
39064|"C. When the free will is the substantial will, made actual in the subject"|FALSE
39064|"and conformable to its concept and rendered a totality of necessity,—it is"|FALSE
39064|"the ethics of actual life in family, civil society, and state."|FALSE
39064|"Sub-Section A. Law.(152)"|FALSE
39064|"(a) Property."|FALSE
39064|"§ 488. Mind, in the immediacy of its self-secured liberty, is an"|FALSE
39064|"individual, but one that knows its individuality as an absolutely free"|FALSE
39064|"will: it is a _person_, in whom the inward sense of this freedom, as in"|FALSE
39064|"itself still abstract and empty, has its particularity and fulfilment not"|FALSE
39064|"yet on its own part, but on an external _thing_. This thing, as something"|FALSE
39064|"devoid of will, has no rights against the subjectivity of intelligence and"|FALSE
39064|"volition, and is by that subjectivity made adjectival to it, the external"|FALSE
39064|"sphere of its liberty;—_possession_."|FALSE
39064|"§ 489. By the judgment of possession, at first in the outward"|FALSE
39064|"appropriation, the thing acquires the predicate of “mine.” But this"|FALSE
39064|"predicate, on its own account merely “practical,” has here the"|FALSE
39064|"signification that I import my personal will into the thing. As so"|FALSE
39064|"characterised, possession is _property_, which as possession is a _means_,"|FALSE
39064|"but as existence of the personality is an _end_."|FALSE
39064|"§ 490. In his property the person is brought into union with itself. But"|FALSE
39064|"the thing is an abstractly external thing, and the I in it is abstractly"|FALSE
39064|"external. The concrete return of me into me in the externality is that I,"|FALSE
39064|"the infinite self-relation, am as a person the repulsion of me from"|FALSE
39064|"myself, and have the existence of my personality in the _being of other"|FALSE
39064|"persons_, in my relation to them and in my recognition by them, which is"|FALSE
39064|"thus mutual."|FALSE
39064|"§ 491. The thing is the _mean_ by which the extremes meet in one. These"|FALSE
39064|"extremes are the persons who, in the knowledge of their identity as free,"|FALSE
39064|"are simultaneously mutually independent. For them my will has its"|FALSE
39064|"_definite recognisable existence_ in the thing by the immediate bodily act"|FALSE
39064|"of taking possession, or by the formation of the thing or, it may be, by"|FALSE
39064|"mere designation of it."|FALSE
39064|"§ 492. The casual aspect of property is that I place my will in _this_"|FALSE
39064|"thing: so far my will is _arbitrary_, I can just as well put it in it as"|FALSE
39064|"not,—just as well withdraw it as not. But so far as my will lies in a"|FALSE
39064|"thing, it is only I who can withdraw it: it is only with my will that the"|FALSE
39064|"thing can pass to another, whose property it similarly becomes only with"|FALSE
39064|"his will:—_Contract_."|FALSE
39064|"(b) Contract."|FALSE
39064|"§ 493. The two wills and their agreement in the contract are as an"|FALSE
39064|"_internal_ state of mind different from its realisation in the"|FALSE
39064|"_performance_. The comparatively “ideal” utterance (of contract) in the"|FALSE
39064|"_stipulation_ contains the actual surrender of a property by the one, its"|FALSE
39064|"changing hands, and its acceptance by the other will. The contract is thus"|FALSE
39064|"thoroughly binding: it does not need the performance of the one or the"|FALSE
39064|"other to become so—otherwise we should have an infinite regress or"|FALSE
39064|"infinite division of thing, labour, and time. The utterance in the"|FALSE
39064|"stipulation is complete and exhaustive. The inwardness of the will which"|FALSE
39064|"surrenders and the will which accepts the property is in the realm of"|FALSE
39064|"ideation, and in that realm the word is deed and thing (§ 462)—the full"|FALSE
39064|"and complete deed, since here the conscientiousness of the will does not"|FALSE
39064|"come under consideration (as to whether the thing is meant in earnest or"|FALSE
39064|"is a deception), and the will refers only to the external thing."|FALSE
39064|"§ 494. Thus in the stipulation we have the _substantial_ being of the"|FALSE
39064|"contract standing out in distinction from its real utterance in the"|FALSE
39064|"performance, which is brought down to a mere sequel. In this way there is"|FALSE
39064|"put into the thing or performance a distinction between its immediate"|FALSE
39064|"specific _quality_ and its substantial being or _value_, meaning by value"|FALSE
39064|"the quantitative terms into which that qualitative feature has been"|FALSE
39064|"translated. One piece of property is thus made comparable with another,"|FALSE
39064|"and may be made equivalent to a thing which is (in quality) wholly"|FALSE
39064|"heterogeneous. It is thus treated in general as an abstract, universal"|FALSE
39064|"thing or commodity."|FALSE
39064|"§ 495. The contract, as an agreement which has a voluntary origin and"|FALSE
39064|"deals with a casual commodity, involves at the same time the giving to"|FALSE
39064|"this “accidental” will a positive fixity. This will may just as well not"|FALSE
39064|"be conformable to law (right), and, in that case, produces a _wrong_: by"|FALSE
39064|"which however the absolute law (right) is not superseded, but only a"|FALSE
39064|"relationship originated of right to wrong."|FALSE
39064|"(c) Right versus Wrong."|FALSE
39064|"§ 496. Law (right) considered as the realisation of liberty in externals,"|FALSE
39064|"breaks up into a multiplicity of relations to this external sphere and to"|FALSE
39064|"other persons (§§ 491, 493 seqq.). In this way there are (1) several"|FALSE
39064|"titles or grounds at law, of which (seeing that property both on the"|FALSE
39064|"personal and the real side is exclusively individual) only one is the"|FALSE
39064|"right, but which, because they face each other, each and all are invested"|FALSE
39064|"with a _show_ of right, against which the former is defined as the"|FALSE
39064|"intrinsically right."|FALSE
39064|"§ 497. Now so long as (compared against this show) the one intrinsically"|FALSE
39064|"right, still presumed identical with the several titles, is affirmed,"|FALSE
39064|"willed, and recognised, the only diversity lies in this, that the special"|FALSE
39064|"thing is subsumed under the one law or right by the _particular_ will of"|FALSE
39064|"_these_ several persons. This is naïve, non-malicious wrong. Such wrong in"|FALSE
39064|"the several claimants is a simple _negative judgment_, expressing the"|FALSE
39064|"_civil suit_. To settle it there is required a third judgment, which, as"|FALSE
39064|"the judgment of the intrinsically right, is disinterested, and a power of"|FALSE
39064|"giving the one right existence as against that semblance."|FALSE
39064|"§ 498. But (2) if the semblance of right is willed as such _against_ right"|FALSE
39064|"intrinsical by the particular will, which thus becomes _wicked_, then the"|FALSE
39064|"external _recognition_ of right is separated from the right’s true value;"|FALSE
39064|"and while the former only is respected, the latter is violated. This gives"|FALSE
39064|"the wrong of _fraud_—the infinite judgment as identical (§ 173),—where the"|FALSE
39064|"nominal relation is retained, but the sterling value is let slip."|FALSE
39064|"§ 499. (3) Finally, the particular will sets itself in opposition to the"|FALSE
39064|"intrinsic right by negating that right itself as well as its recognition"|FALSE
39064|"or semblance. [Here there is a negatively infinite judgment (§ 173) in"|FALSE
39064|"which there is denied the class as a whole, and not merely the particular"|FALSE
39064|"mode—in this case the apparent recognition.] Thus the will is violently"|FALSE
39064|"wicked, and commits a _crime_."|FALSE
39064|"§ 500. As an outrage on right, such an action is essentially and actually"|FALSE
39064|"null. In it the agent, as a volitional and intelligent being, sets up a"|FALSE
39064|"law—a law however which is nominal and recognised by him only—a universal"|FALSE
39064|"which holds good _for him_, and under which he has at the same time"|FALSE
39064|"subsumed himself by his action. To display the nullity of such an act, to"|FALSE
39064|"carry out simultaneously this nominal law and the intrinsic right, in the"|FALSE
39064|"first instance by means of a subjective individual will, is the work of"|FALSE
39064|"_Revenge_. But, revenge, starting from the interest of an immediate"|FALSE
39064|"particular personality, is at the same time only a new outrage; and so on"|FALSE
39064|"without end. This progression, like the last, abolishes itself in a third"|FALSE
39064|"judgment, which is disinterested—_punishment_."|FALSE
39064|"§ 501. The instrumentality by which authority is given to intrinsic right"|FALSE
39064|"is (α) that a particular will, that of the judge, being conformable to the"|FALSE
39064|"right, has an interest to turn against the crime (—which in the first"|FALSE
39064|"instance, in revenge, is a matter of chance), and (β) that an executive"|FALSE
39064|"power (also in the first instance casual) negates the negation of right"|FALSE
39064|"that was created by the criminal. This negation of right has its existence"|FALSE
39064|"in the will of the criminal; and consequently revenge or punishment"|FALSE
39064|"directs itself against the person or property of the criminal and"|FALSE
39064|"exercises _coercion_ upon him. It is in this legal sphere that coercion in"|FALSE
39064|"general has possible scope,—compulsion against the thing, in seizing and"|FALSE
39064|"maintaining it against another’s seizure: for in this sphere the will has"|FALSE
39064|"its existence immediately in externals as such, or in corporeity, and can"|FALSE
39064|"be seized only in this quarter. But more than _possible_ compulsion is"|FALSE
39064|"not, so long as I can withdraw myself as free from every mode of"|FALSE
39064|"existence, even from the range of all existence, i.e. from life. It is"|FALSE
39064|"legal only as abolishing a first and original compulsion."|FALSE
39064|"§ 502. A distinction has thus emerged between the law (right) and the"|FALSE
39064|"subjective will. The “reality” of right, which the personal will in the"|FALSE
39064|"first instance gives itself in immediate wise, is seen to be due to the"|FALSE
39064|"instrumentality of the subjective will,—whose influence as on one hand it"|FALSE
39064|"gives existence to the essential right, so may on the other cut itself off"|FALSE
39064|"from and oppose itself to it. Conversely, the claim of the subjective will"|FALSE
39064|"to be in this abstraction a power over the law of right is null and empty"|FALSE
39064|"of itself: it gets truth and reality essentially only so far as that will"|FALSE
39064|"in itself realises the reasonable will. As such it is _morality_(153)"|FALSE
39064|"proper."|FALSE
39064|"The phrase “Law of Nature,” or Natural Right(154), in use for the"|FALSE
39064|"philosophy of law involves the ambiguity that it may mean either right as"|FALSE
39064|"something existing ready-formed in nature, or right as governed by the"|FALSE
39064|"nature of things, i.e. by the notion. The former used to be the common"|FALSE
39064|"meaning, accompanied with the fiction of a _state of nature_, in which the"|FALSE
39064|"law of nature should hold sway; whereas the social and political state"|FALSE
39064|"rather required and implied a restriction of liberty and a sacrifice of"|FALSE
39064|"natural rights. The real fact is that the whole law and its every article"|FALSE
39064|"are based on free personality alone,—on self-determination or autonomy,"|FALSE
39064|"which is the very contrary of determination by nature. The law of"|FALSE
39064|"nature—strictly so called—is for that reason the predominance of the"|FALSE
39064|"strong and the reign of force, and a state of nature a state of violence"|FALSE
39064|"and wrong, of which nothing truer can be said than that one ought to"|FALSE
39064|"depart from it. The social state, on the other hand, is the condition in"|FALSE
39064|"which alone right has its actuality: what is to be restricted and"|FALSE
39064|"sacrificed is just the wilfulness and violence of the state of nature."|FALSE
39064|"Sub-Section B. The Morality Of Conscience(155)."|FALSE
39064|"§ 503. The free individual, who, in mere law, counts only as a _person_,"|FALSE
39064|"is now characterised as a _subject_, a will reflected into itself so that,"|FALSE
39064|"be its affection what it may, it is distinguished (as existing in it) as"|FALSE
39064|"_its own_ from the existence of freedom in an external thing. Because the"|FALSE
39064|"affection of the will is thus inwardised, the will is at the same time"|FALSE
39064|"made a particular, and there arise further particularisations of it and"|FALSE
39064|"relations of these to one another. This affection is partly the essential"|FALSE
39064|"and implicit will, the reason of the will, the essential basis of law and"|FALSE
39064|"moral life: partly it is the existent volition, which is before us and"|FALSE
39064|"throws itself into actual deeds, and thus comes into relationship with the"|FALSE
39064|"former. The subjective will is _morally_ free, so far as these features"|FALSE
39064|"are its inward institution, its own, and willed by it. Its utterance in"|FALSE
39064|"deed with this freedom is an _action_, in the externality of which it only"|FALSE
39064|"admits as its own, and allows to be imputed to it, so much as it has"|FALSE
39064|"consciously willed."|FALSE
39064|"This subjective or “moral” freedom is what a European especially calls"|FALSE
39064|"freedom. In virtue of the right thereto a man must possess a personal"|FALSE
39064|"knowledge of the distinction between good and evil in general: ethical and"|FALSE
39064|"religious principles shall not merely lay their claim on him as external"|FALSE
39064|"laws and precepts of authority to be obeyed, but have their assent,"|FALSE
39064|"recognition, or even justification in his heart, sentiment, conscience,"|FALSE
39064|"intelligence, &c. The subjectivity of the will in itself is its supreme"|FALSE
39064|"aim and absolutely essential to it."|FALSE
39064|"The “moral” must be taken in the wider sense in which it does not signify"|FALSE
39064|"the morally good merely. In French _le moral_ is opposed to _le physique_,"|FALSE
39064|"and means the mental or intellectual in general. But here the moral"|FALSE
39064|"signifies volitional mode, so far as it is in the interior of the will in"|FALSE
39064|"general; it thus includes purpose and intention,—and also moral"|FALSE
39064|"wickedness."|FALSE
39064|"a. Purpose(156)."|FALSE
39064|"§ 504. So far as the action comes into immediate touch with _existence_,"|FALSE
39064|"_my part_ in it is to this extent formal, that external existence is also"|FALSE
39064|"_independent_ of the agent. This externality can pervert his action and"|FALSE
39064|"bring to light something else than lay in it. Now, though any alteration"|FALSE
39064|"as such, which is set on foot by the subject’s action, is its _deed_(157),"|FALSE
39064|"still the subject does not for that reason recognise it as its"|FALSE
39064|"_action_(158), but only admits as its own that existence in the deed which"|FALSE
39064|"lay in its knowledge and will, which was its _purpose_. Only for that does"|FALSE
39064|"it hold itself _responsible_."|FALSE
39064|"b. Intention and Welfare(159)."|FALSE
39064|"§ 505. As regards its empirically concrete _content_ (1) the action has a"|FALSE
39064|"variety of particular aspects and connexions. In point of _form_, the"|FALSE
39064|"agent must have known and willed the action in its essential feature,"|FALSE
39064|"embracing these individual points. This is the right of _intention_. While"|FALSE
39064|"_purpose_ affects only the immediate fact of existence, _intention_"|FALSE
39064|"regards the underlying essence and aim thereof. (2) The agent has no less"|FALSE
39064|"the right to see that the particularity of content in the action, in point"|FALSE
39064|"of its matter, is not something external to him, but is a particularity of"|FALSE
39064|"his own,—that it contains his needs, interests, and aims. These aims, when"|FALSE
39064|"similarly comprehended in a single aim, as in happiness (§ 479),"|FALSE
39064|"constitute his _well-being_. This is the right to well-being. Happiness"|FALSE
39064|"(good fortune) is distinguished from well-being only in this, that"|FALSE
39064|"happiness implies no more than some sort of immediate existence, whereas"|FALSE
39064|"well-being regards it as also justified as regards morality."|FALSE
39064|"§ 506. But the essentiality of the intention is in the first instance the"|FALSE
39064|"abstract form of generality. Reflection can put in this form this and that"|FALSE
39064|"particular aspect in the empirically-concrete action, thus making it"|FALSE
39064|"essential to the intention or restricting the intention to it. In this way"|FALSE
39064|"the supposed essentiality of the intention and the real essentiality of"|FALSE
39064|"the action may be brought into the greatest contradiction—e.g. a good"|FALSE
39064|"intention in case of a crime. Similarly well-being is abstract and may be"|FALSE
39064|"set on this or that: as appertaining to this single agent, it is always"|FALSE
39064|"something particular."|FALSE
39064|"c. Goodness and Wickedness(160)."|FALSE
39064|"§ 507. The truth of these particularities and the concrete unity of their"|FALSE
39064|"formalism is the content of the universal, essential and actual, will,—the"|FALSE
39064|"law and underlying essence of every phase of volition, the essential and"|FALSE
39064|"actual good. It is thus the absolute final aim of the world, and _duty_"|FALSE
39064|"for the agent who _ought_ to have _insight_ into the _good_, make it his"|FALSE
39064|"_intention_ and bring it about by his activity."|FALSE
39064|"§ 508. But though the good is the universal of will—a universal determined"|FALSE
39064|"in itself,—and thus including in it particularity,—still so far as this"|FALSE
39064|"particularity is in the first instance still abstract, there is no"|FALSE
39064|"principle at hand to determine it. Such determination therefore starts up"|FALSE
39064|"also outside that universal; and as heteronomy or determinance of a will"|FALSE
39064|"which is free and has rights of its own, there awakes here the deepest"|FALSE
39064|"contradiction. (α) In consequence of the indeterminate determinism of the"|FALSE
39064|"good, there are always _several sorts_ of good and _many kinds of duties_,"|FALSE
39064|"the variety of which is a dialectic of one against another and brings them"|FALSE
39064|"into _collision_. At the same time because good is one, they _ought_ to"|FALSE
39064|"stand in harmony; and yet each of them, though it is a particular duty, is"|FALSE
39064|"as good and as duty absolute. It falls upon the agent to be the dialectic"|FALSE
39064|"which, superseding this absolute claim of each, concludes such a"|FALSE
39064|"combination of them as excludes the rest."|FALSE
39064|"§ 509. (β) To the agent, who in his existent sphere of liberty is"|FALSE
39064|"essentially as a _particular_, his _interest and welfare_ must, on account"|FALSE
39064|"of that existent sphere of liberty, be essentially an aim and therefore a"|FALSE
39064|"duty. But at the same time in aiming at the good, which is the"|FALSE
39064|"not-particular but only universal of the will, the particular interest"|FALSE
39064|"_ought not_ to be a constituent motive. On account of this independency of"|FALSE
39064|"the two principles of action, it is likewise an accident whether they"|FALSE
39064|"harmonise. And yet they _ought_ to harmonise, because the agent, as"|FALSE
39064|"individual and universal, is always fundamentally one identity."|FALSE
39064|"(γ) But the agent is not only a mere particular in his existence; it is"|FALSE
39064|"also a form of his existence to be an abstract self-certainty, an abstract"|FALSE
39064|"reflection of freedom into himself. He is thus distinct from the reason in"|FALSE
39064|"the will, and capable of making the universal itself a particular and in"|FALSE
39064|"that way a semblance. The good is thus reduced to the level of a mere “may"|FALSE
39064|"happen” for the agent, who can therefore resolve itself to somewhat"|FALSE
39064|"opposite to the good, can be wicked."|FALSE
39064|"§ 510. (δ) The external objectivity, following the distinction which has"|FALSE
39064|"arisen in the subjective will (§ 503), constitutes a peculiar world of its"|FALSE
39064|"own,—another extreme which stands in no rapport with the internal"|FALSE
39064|"will-determination. It is thus a matter of chance, whether it harmonises"|FALSE
39064|"with the subjective aims, whether the good is realised, and the wicked, an"|FALSE
39064|"aim essentially and actually null, nullified in it: it is no less matter"|FALSE
39064|"of chance whether the agent finds in it his well-being, and more precisely"|FALSE
39064|"whether in the world the good agent is happy and the wicked unhappy. But"|FALSE
39064|"at the same time the world _ought_ to allow the good action, the essential"|FALSE
39064|"thing, to be carried out in it; it _ought_ to grant the good agent the"|FALSE
39064|"satisfaction of his particular interest, and refuse it to the wicked; just"|FALSE
39064|"as it _ought_ also to make the wicked itself null and void."|FALSE
39064|"§ 511. The all-round contradiction, expressed by this repeated _ought_,"|FALSE
39064|"with its absoluteness which yet at the same time is _not_—contains the"|FALSE
39064|"most abstract ’analysis’ of the mind in itself, its deepest descent into"|FALSE
39064|"itself. The only relation the self-contradictory principles have to one"|FALSE
39064|"another is in the abstract certainty of self; and for this infinitude of"|FALSE
39064|"subjectivity the universal will, good, right, and duty, no more exist than"|FALSE
39064|"not. The subjectivity alone is aware of itself as choosing and deciding."|FALSE
39064|"This pure self-certitude, rising to its pitch, appears in the two directly"|FALSE
39064|"inter-changing forms—of _Conscience_ and _Wickedness_. The former is the"|FALSE
39064|"will of goodness; but a goodness which to this pure subjectivity is the"|FALSE
39064|"_non-objective_, non-universal, the unutterable; and over which the agent"|FALSE
39064|"is conscious that _he_ in his _individuality_ has the decision. Wickedness"|FALSE
39064|"is the same awareness that the single self possesses the decision, so far"|FALSE
39064|"as the single self does not merely remain in this abstraction, but takes"|FALSE
39064|"up the content of a subjective interest contrary to the good."|FALSE
39064|"§ 512. This supreme pitch of the “_phenomenon_” of will,—sublimating"|FALSE
39064|"itself to this absolute vanity—to a goodness, which has no objectivity,"|FALSE
39064|"but is only sure of itself, and a self-assurance which involves the"|FALSE
39064|"nullification of the universal—collapses by its own force. Wickedness, as"|FALSE
39064|"the most intimate reflection of subjectivity itself, in opposition to the"|FALSE
39064|"objective and universal, (which it treats as mere sham,) is the same as"|FALSE
