39064|"being as such exhibited as current usage."|FALSE
39064|"§ 539. As a living mind, the state only is as an organised whole,"|FALSE
39064|"differentiated into particular agencies, which, proceeding from the one"|FALSE
39064|"notion (though not known as notion) of the reasonable will, continually"|FALSE
39064|"produce it as their result. The _constitution_ is this articulation or"|FALSE
39064|"organisation of state-power. It provides for the reasonable will,—in so"|FALSE
39064|"far as it is in the individuals only _implicitly_ the universal"|FALSE
39064|"will,—coming to a consciousness and an understanding of itself and being"|FALSE
39064|"_found_; also for that will being put in actuality, through the action of"|FALSE
39064|"the government and its several branches, and not left to perish, but"|FALSE
39064|"protected both against _their_ casual subjectivity and against that of the"|FALSE
39064|"individuals. The constitution is existent _justice_,—the actuality of"|FALSE
39064|"liberty in the development all its reasonable provisions."|FALSE
39064|"Liberty and Equality are the simple rubrics into which is frequently"|FALSE
39064|"concentrated what should form the fundamental principle, the final aim and"|FALSE
39064|"result of the constitution. However true this is, the defect of these"|FALSE
39064|"terms is their utter abstractness: if stuck to in this abstract form, they"|FALSE
39064|"are principles which either prevent the rise of the concreteness of the"|FALSE
39064|"state, i.e. its articulation into a constitution and a government in"|FALSE
39064|"general, or destroy them. With the state there arises inequality, the"|FALSE
39064|"difference of governing powers and of governed, magistracies, authorities,"|FALSE
39064|"directories, &c. The principle of equality, logically carried out, rejects"|FALSE
39064|"all differences, and thus allows no sort of political condition to exist."|FALSE
39064|"Liberty and equality are indeed the foundation of the state, but as the"|FALSE
39064|"most abstract also the most superficial, and for that very reason"|FALSE
39064|"naturally the most familiar. It is important therefore to study them"|FALSE
39064|"closer."|FALSE
39064|"As regards, first, Equality, the familiar proposition, All men are by"|FALSE
39064|"nature equal, blunders by confusing the “natural” with the “notion.” It"|FALSE
39064|"ought rather to read: _By nature_ men are only unequal. But the notion of"|FALSE
39064|"liberty, as it exists as such, without further specification and"|FALSE
39064|"development, is abstract subjectivity, as a person capable of property (§"|FALSE
39064|"488). This single abstract feature of personality constitutes the actual"|FALSE
39064|"_equality_ of human beings. But that this freedom should exist, that it"|FALSE
39064|"should be _man_ (and not as in Greece, Rome, &c. _some_ men) that is"|FALSE
39064|"recognised and legally regarded as a person, is so little _by nature_,"|FALSE
39064|"that it is rather only a result and product of the consciousness of the"|FALSE
39064|"deepest principle of mind, and of the universality and expansion of this"|FALSE
39064|"consciousness. That the citizens are equal before the law contains a great"|FALSE
39064|"truth, but which so expressed is a tautology: it only states that the"|FALSE
39064|"legal status in general exists, that the laws rule. But, as regards the"|FALSE
39064|"concrete, the citizens—besides their personality—are equal before the law"|FALSE
39064|"only in these points when they are otherwise equal _outside the law_. Only"|FALSE
39064|"that equality which (in whatever way it be) they, as it happens, otherwise"|FALSE
39064|"have in property, age, physical strength, talent, skill, &c.—or even in"|FALSE
39064|"crime, can and ought to make them deserve equal treatment before the"|FALSE
39064|"law:—only it can make them—as regards taxation, military service,"|FALSE
39064|"eligibility to office, &c.—punishment, &c.—equal in the concrete. The laws"|FALSE
39064|"themselves, except in so far as they concern that narrow circle of"|FALSE
39064|"personality, presuppose unequal conditions, and provide for the unequal"|FALSE
39064|"legal duties and appurtenances resulting therefrom."|FALSE
39064|"As regards Liberty, it is originally taken partly in a negative sense"|FALSE
39064|"against arbitrary intolerance and lawless treatment, partly in the"|FALSE
39064|"affirmative sense of subjective freedom; but this freedom is allowed great"|FALSE
39064|"latitude both as regards the agent’s self-will and action for his"|FALSE
39064|"particular ends, and as regards his claim to have a personal intelligence"|FALSE
39064|"and a personal share in general affairs. Formerly the legally defined"|FALSE
39064|"rights, private as well as public rights of a nation, town, &c. were"|FALSE
39064|"called its “liberties.” Really, every genuine law is a liberty: it"|FALSE
39064|"contains a reasonable principle of objective mind; in other words, it"|FALSE
39064|"embodies a liberty. Nothing has become, on the contrary, more familiar"|FALSE
39064|"than the idea that each must _restrict_ his liberty in relation to the"|FALSE
39064|"liberty of others: that the state is a condition of such reciprocal"|FALSE
39064|"restriction, and that the laws are restrictions. To such habits of mind"|FALSE
39064|"liberty is viewed as only casual good-pleasure and self-will. Hence it has"|FALSE
39064|"also been said that “modern” nations are only susceptible of equality, or"|FALSE
39064|"of equality more than liberty: and that for no other reason than that,"|FALSE
39064|"with an assumed definition of liberty (chiefly the participation of all in"|FALSE
39064|"political affairs and actions), it was impossible to make ends meet in"|FALSE
39064|"actuality—which is at once more reasonable and more powerful than abstract"|FALSE
39064|"presuppositions. On the contrary, it should be said that it is just the"|FALSE
39064|"great development and maturity of form in modern states which produces the"|FALSE
39064|"supreme concrete inequality of individuals in actuality: while, through"|FALSE
39064|"the deeper reasonableness of laws and the greater stability of the legal"|FALSE
39064|"state, it gives rise to greater and more stable liberty, which it can"|FALSE
39064|"without incompatibility allow. Even the superficial distinction of the"|FALSE
39064|"words liberty and equality points to the fact that the former tends to"|FALSE
39064|"inequality: whereas, on the contrary, the current notions of liberty only"|FALSE
39064|"carry us back to equality. But the more we fortify liberty,—as security of"|FALSE
39064|"property, as possibility for each to develop and make the best of his"|FALSE
39064|"talents and good qualities, the more it gets taken for granted: and then"|FALSE
39064|"the sense and appreciation of liberty especially turns in a _subjective_"|FALSE
39064|"direction. By this is meant the liberty to attempt action on every side,"|FALSE
39064|"and to throw oneself at pleasure in action for particular and for general"|FALSE
39064|"intellectual interests, the removal of all checks on the individual"|FALSE
39064|"particularity, as well as the inward liberty in which the subject has"|FALSE
39064|"principles, has an insight and conviction of his own, and thus gains moral"|FALSE
39064|"independence. But this liberty itself on one hand implies that supreme"|FALSE
39064|"differentiation in which men are unequal and make themselves more unequal"|FALSE
39064|"by education; and on another it only grows up under conditions of that"|FALSE
39064|"objective liberty, and is and could grow to such height only in modern"|FALSE
39064|"states. If, with this development of particularity, there be simultaneous"|FALSE
39064|"and endless increase of the number of wants, and of the difficulty of"|FALSE
39064|"satisfying them, of the lust of argument and the fancy of detecting"|FALSE
39064|"faults, with its insatiate vanity, it is all but part of that"|FALSE
39064|"indiscriminating relaxation of individuality in this sphere which"|FALSE
39064|"generates all possible complications, and must deal with them as it can."|FALSE
39064|"Such a sphere is of course also the field of restrictions, because liberty"|FALSE
39064|"is there under the taint of natural self-will and self-pleasing, and has"|FALSE
39064|"therefore to restrict itself: and that, not merely with regard to the"|FALSE
39064|"naturalness, self-will and self-conceit, of others, but especially and"|FALSE
39064|"essentially with regard to reasonable liberty."|FALSE
39064|"The term political liberty, however, is often used to mean formal"|FALSE
39064|"participation in the public affairs of state by the will and action even"|FALSE
39064|"of those individuals who otherwise find their chief function in the"|FALSE
39064|"particular aims and business of civil society. And it has in part become"|FALSE
39064|"usual to give the title constitution only to the side of the state which"|FALSE
39064|"concerns such participation of these individuals in general affairs, and"|FALSE
39064|"to regard a state, in which this is not formally done, as a state without"|FALSE
39064|"a constitution. On this use of the term, the only thing to remark is that"|FALSE
39064|"by constitution must be understood the determination of rights, i.e. of"|FALSE
39064|"liberties in general, and the organisation of the actualisation of them;"|FALSE
39064|"and that political freedom in the above sense can in any case only"|FALSE
39064|"constitute a part of it. Of it the following paragraphs will speak."|FALSE
39064|"§ 540. The guarantee of a constitution (i.e. the necessity that the laws"|FALSE
39064|"be reasonable, and their actualisation secured) lies in the collective"|FALSE
39064|"spirit of the nation,—especially in the specific way in which it is itself"|FALSE
39064|"conscious of its reason. (Religion is that consciousness in its absolute"|FALSE
39064|"substantiality.) But the guarantee lies also at the same time in the"|FALSE
39064|"actual organisation or development of that principle in suitable"|FALSE
39064|"institutions. The constitution presupposes that consciousness of the"|FALSE
39064|"collective spirit, and conversely that spirit presupposes the"|FALSE
39064|"constitution: for the actual spirit only has a definite consciousness of"|FALSE
39064|"its principles, in so far as it has them actually existent before it."|FALSE
39064|"The question—To whom (to what authority and how organised) belongs the"|FALSE
39064|"power to make a constitution? is the same as the question, Who has to make"|FALSE
39064|"the spirit of a nation? Separate our idea of a constitution from that of"|FALSE
39064|"the collective spirit, as if the latter exists or has existed without a"|FALSE
39064|"constitution, and your fancy only proves how superficially you have"|FALSE
39064|"apprehended the nexus between the spirit in its self-consciousness and in"|FALSE
39064|"its actuality. What is thus called “making” a “constitution,” is—just"|FALSE
39064|"because of this inseparability—a thing that has never happened in history,"|FALSE
39064|"just as little as the making of a code of laws. A constitution only"|FALSE
39064|"develops from the national spirit identically with that spirit’s own"|FALSE
39064|"development, and runs through at the same time with it the grades of"|FALSE
39064|"formation and the alterations required by its concept. It is the"|FALSE
39064|"indwelling spirit and the history of the nation (and, be it added, the"|FALSE
39064|"history is only that spirit’s history) by which constitutions have been"|FALSE
39064|"and are made."|FALSE
39064|"§ 541. The really living totality,—that which preserves, in other words"|FALSE
39064|"continually produces the state in general and its constitution, is the"|FALSE
39064|"_government_. The organisation which natural necessity gives is seen in"|FALSE
39064|"the rise of the family and of the ’estates’ of civil society. The"|FALSE
39064|"government is the _universal_ part of the constitution, i.e. the part"|FALSE
39064|"which intentionally aims at preserving those parts, but at the same time"|FALSE
39064|"gets hold of and carries out those general aims of the whole which rise"|FALSE
39064|"above the function of the family and of civil society. The organisation of"|FALSE
39064|"the government is likewise its differentiation into powers, as their"|FALSE
39064|"peculiarities have a basis in principle; yet without that difference"|FALSE
39064|"losing touch with the _actual unity_ they have in the notion’s"|FALSE
39064|"subjectivity."|FALSE
39064|"As the most obvious categories of the notion are those of _universality_"|FALSE
39064|"and _individuality_ and their relationship that of _subsumption_ of"|FALSE
39064|"individual under universal, it has come about that in the state the"|FALSE
39064|"legislative and executive power have been so distinguished as to make the"|FALSE
39064|"former exist apart as the absolute superior, and to subdivide the latter"|FALSE
39064|"again into administrative (government) power and judicial power, according"|FALSE
39064|"as the laws are applied to public or private affairs. The _division_ of"|FALSE
39064|"these powers has been treated as _the_ condition of political equilibrium,"|FALSE
39064|"meaning by division their _independence_ one of another in"|FALSE
39064|"existence,—subject always however to the above-mentioned subsumption of"|FALSE
39064|"the powers of the individual under the power of the general. The theory of"|FALSE
39064|"such “division” unmistakably implies the elements of the notion, but so"|FALSE
39064|"combined by “understanding” as to result in an absurd collocation, instead"|FALSE
39064|"of the self-redintegration of the living spirit. The one essential canon"|FALSE
39064|"to make liberty deep and real is to give every business belonging to the"|FALSE
39064|"general interests of the state a separate organisation wherever they are"|FALSE
39064|"essentially distinct. Such real division must be: for liberty is only deep"|FALSE
39064|"when it is differentiated in all its fullness and these differences"|FALSE
39064|"manifested in existence. But to make the business of legislation an"|FALSE
39064|"independent power—to make it the first power, with the further proviso"|FALSE
39064|"that all citizens shall have part therein, and the government be merely"|FALSE
39064|"executive and dependent, presupposes ignorance that the true idea, and"|FALSE
39064|"therefore the living and spiritual actuality, is the self-redintegrating"|FALSE
39064|"notion, in other words, the subjectivity which contains in it universality"|FALSE
39064|"as only one of its moments. (A mistake still greater, if it goes with the"|FALSE
39064|"fancy that the constitution and the fundamental laws were still one day to"|FALSE
39064|"make,—in a state of society, which includes an already existing"|FALSE
39064|"development of differences.) Individuality is the first and supreme"|FALSE
39064|"principle _which_ makes itself fall through the state’s organisation. Only"|FALSE
39064|"through the government, and by its embracing in itself the particular"|FALSE
39064|"businesses (including the abstract legislative business, which taken apart"|FALSE
39064|"is also particular), is the state _one_. These, as always, are the terms"|FALSE
39064|"on which the different elements essentially and alone truly stand towards"|FALSE
39064|"each other in the logic of “reason,” as opposed to the external footing"|FALSE
39064|"they stand on in ’understanding,’ which never gets beyond subsuming the"|FALSE
39064|"individual and particular under the universal. What disorganises the unity"|FALSE
39064|"of logical reason, equally disorganises actuality."|FALSE
39064|"§ 542. In the government—regarded as organic totality—the sovereign power"|FALSE
39064|"(principate) is (_a_) _subjectivity_ as the _infinite_ self-unity of the"|FALSE
39064|"notion in its development;—the all-sustaining, all-decreeing will of the"|FALSE
39064|"state, its highest peak and all-pervasive unity. In the perfect form of"|FALSE
39064|"the state, in which each and every element of the notion has reached free"|FALSE
39064|"existence, this subjectivity is not a so-called “moral person,” or a"|FALSE
39064|"decree issuing from a majority (forms in which the unity of the decreeing"|FALSE
39064|"will has not an _actual_ existence), but an actual individual,—the will of"|FALSE
39064|"a decreeing individual,—_monarchy_. The monarchical constitution is"|FALSE
39064|"therefore the constitution of developed reason: all other constitutions"|FALSE
39064|"belong to lower grades of the development and realisation of reason."|FALSE
39064|"The unification of all concrete state-powers into one existence, as in the"|FALSE
39064|"patriarchal society,—or, as in a democratic constitution, the"|FALSE
39064|"participation of all in all affairs—impugns the principle of the division"|FALSE
39064|"of powers, i.e. the developed liberty of the constituent factors of the"|FALSE
39064|"Idea. But no whit less must the division (the working out of these factors"|FALSE
39064|"each to a free totality) be reduced to “ideal” unity, i.e. to"|FALSE
39064|"_subjectivity_. The mature differentiation or realisation of the Idea"|FALSE
39064|"means, essentially, that this subjectivity should grow to be a _real_"|FALSE
39064|"“moment,” an _actual_ existence; and this actuality is not otherwise than"|FALSE
39064|"as the individuality of the monarch—the subjectivity of abstract and final"|FALSE
39064|"decision existent in _one_ person. All those forms of collective decreeing"|FALSE
39064|"and willing,—a common will which shall be the sum and the resultant (on"|FALSE
39064|"aristocratical or democratical principles) of the atomistic of single"|FALSE
39064|"wills, have on them the mark of the unreality of an abstraction. Two"|FALSE
39064|"points only are all-important, first to see the necessity of each of the"|FALSE
39064|"notional factors, and secondly the form in which it is actualised. It is"|FALSE
39064|"only the nature of the speculative notion which can really give light on"|FALSE
39064|"the matter. That subjectivity—being the “moment” which emphasises the need"|FALSE
39064|"of abstract deciding in general—partly leads on to the proviso that the"|FALSE
39064|"name of the monarch appear as the bond and sanction under which everything"|FALSE
39064|"is done in the government;—partly, being simple self-relation, has"|FALSE
39064|"attached to it the characteristic of _immediacy_, and then of"|FALSE
39064|"_nature_—whereby the destination of individuals for the dignity of the"|FALSE
39064|"princely power is fixed by inheritance."|FALSE
39064|"§ 543. (_b_) In the _particular_ government-power there emerges, first,"|FALSE
39064|"the division of state-business into its branches (otherwise defined),"|FALSE
39064|"legislative power, administration of justice or judicial power,"|FALSE
39064|"administration and police, and its consequent distribution between"|FALSE
39064|"particular boards or offices, which having their business appointed by"|FALSE
39064|"law, to that end and for that reason, possess independence of action,"|FALSE
39064|"without at the same time ceasing to stand under higher supervision."|FALSE
39064|"Secondly, too, there arises the participation of _several_ in"|FALSE
39064|"state-business, who together constitute the “general order” (§ 528) in so"|FALSE
39064|"far as they take on themselves the charge of universal ends as the"|FALSE
39064|"essential function of their particular life;—the further condition for"|FALSE
39064|"being able to take individually part in this business being a certain"|FALSE
39064|"training, aptitude, and skill for such ends."|FALSE
39064|"§ 544. The estates-collegium or provincial council is an institution by"|FALSE
39064|"which all such as belong to civil society in general, and are to that"|FALSE
39064|"degree private persons, participate in the governmental power, especially"|FALSE
39064|"in legislation—viz. such legislation as concerns the universal scope of"|FALSE
39064|"those interests which do not, like peace and war, involve the, as it were,"|FALSE
39064|"personal interference and action of the State as one man, and therefore do"|FALSE
39064|"not belong specially to the province of the sovereign power. By virtue of"|FALSE
39064|"this participation subjective liberty and conceit, with their general"|FALSE
39064|"opinion, can show themselves palpably efficacious and enjoy the"|FALSE
39064|"satisfaction of feeling themselves to count for something."|FALSE
39064|"The division of constitutions into democracy, aristocracy and monarchy, is"|FALSE
39064|"still the most definite statement of their difference in relation to"|FALSE
39064|"sovereignty. They must at the same time be regarded as necessary"|FALSE
39064|"structures in the path of development,—in short, in the history of the"|FALSE
39064|"State. Hence it is superficial and absurd to represent them as an object"|FALSE
39064|"of _choice_. The pure forms—necessary to the process of evolution—are, in"|FALSE
39064|"so far as they are finite and in course of change, conjoined both with"|FALSE
39064|"forms of their degeneration,—such as ochlocracy, &c., and with earlier"|FALSE
39064|"transition-forms. These two forms are not to be confused with those"|FALSE
39064|"legitimate structures. Thus, it may be—if we look only to the fact that"|FALSE
39064|"the will of one individual stands at the head of the state—oriental"|FALSE
39064|"despotism is included under the vague name monarchy,—as also feudal"|FALSE
39064|"monarchy, to which indeed even the favourite name of “constitutional"|FALSE
39064|"monarchy” cannot be refused. The true difference of these forms from"|FALSE
39064|"genuine monarchy depends on the true value of those principles of right"|FALSE
39064|"which are in vogue and have their actuality and guarantee in the"|FALSE
39064|"state-power. These principles are those expounded earlier, liberty of"|FALSE
39064|"property, and above all personal liberty, civil society, with its industry"|FALSE
39064|"and its communities, and the regulated efficiency of the particular"|FALSE
39064|"bureaux in subordination to the laws."|FALSE
39064|"The question which is most discussed is in what sense we are to understand"|FALSE
39064|"the participation of private persons in state affairs. For it is as"|FALSE
39064|"private persons that the members of bodies of estates are primarily to be"|FALSE
39064|"taken, be they treated as mere individuals, or as representatives of a"|FALSE
39064|"number of people or of the nation. The aggregate of private persons is"|FALSE
39064|"often spoken of as the _nation_: but as such an aggregate it is _vulgus_,"|FALSE
39064|"not _populus_: and in this direction, it is the one sole aim of the state"|FALSE
39064|"that a nation should _not_ come to existence, to power and action, _as"|FALSE
39064|"such an aggregate_. Such a condition of a nation is a condition of"|FALSE
39064|"lawlessness, demoralisation, brutishness: in it the nation would only be a"|FALSE
39064|"shapeless, wild, blind force, like that of the stormy, elemental sea,"|FALSE
39064|"which however is not self-destructive, as the nation—a spiritual"|FALSE
39064|"element—would be. Yet such a condition may be often heard described as"|FALSE
39064|"that of true freedom. If there is to be any sense in embarking upon the"|FALSE
39064|"question of the participation of private persons in public affairs, it is"|FALSE
39064|"not a brutish mass, but an already organised nation—one in which a"|FALSE
39064|"governmental power exists—which should be presupposed. The desirability of"|FALSE
39064|"such participation however is not to be put in the superiority of"|FALSE
39064|"particular intelligence, which private persons are supposed to have over"|FALSE
39064|"state officials—the contrary may be the case—nor in the superiority of"|FALSE
39064|"their good will for the general best. The members of civil society as such"|FALSE
39064|"are rather people who find their nearest duty in their private interest"|FALSE
39064|"and (as especially in the feudal society) in the interest of their"|FALSE
39064|"privileged corporation. Take the case of _England_ which, because private"|FALSE
39064|"persons have a predominant share in public affairs, has been regarded as"|FALSE
39064|"having the freest of all constitutions. Experience shows that that"|FALSE
39064|"country—as compared with the other civilised states of Europe—is the most"|FALSE
39064|"backward in civil and criminal legislation, in the law and liberty of"|FALSE
39064|"property, in arrangements for art and science, and that objective freedom"|FALSE
39064|"or rational right is rather _sacrificed_ to formal right and particular"|FALSE
39064|"private interest; and that this happens even in the institutions and"|FALSE
39064|"possessions supposed to be dedicated to religion. The desirability of"|FALSE
39064|"private persons taking part in public affairs is partly to be put in their"|FALSE
39064|"concrete, and therefore more urgent, sense of general wants. But the true"|FALSE
39064|"motive is the right of the collective spirit to appear as an _externally"|FALSE
39064|"universal_ will, acting with orderly and express efficacy for the public"|FALSE
39064|"concerns. By this satisfaction of this right it gets its own life"|FALSE
39064|"quickened, and at the same time breathes fresh life in the administrative"|FALSE
39064|"officials; who thus have it brought home to them that not merely have they"|FALSE
39064|"to enforce duties but also to have regard to rights. Private citizens are"|FALSE
39064|"in the state the incomparably greater number, and form the multitude of"|FALSE
39064|"such as are recognised as persons. Hence the will-reason exhibits its"|FALSE
39064|"existence in them as a preponderating majority of freemen, or in its"|FALSE
39064|"“reflectional” universality, which has its actuality vouchsafed it as a"|FALSE
39064|"participation in the sovereignty. But it has already been noted as a"|FALSE
39064|"“moment” of civil society (§§ 527, 534) that the individuals rise from"|FALSE
39064|"external into substantial universality, and form a _particular_ kind,—the"|FALSE
39064|"Estates: and it is not in the inorganic form of mere individuals as such"|FALSE
39064|"(after the _democratic_ fashion of election), but as organic factors, as"|FALSE
39064|"estates, that they enter upon that participation. In the state a power or"|FALSE
39064|"agency must never appear and act as a formless, inorganic shape, i.e."|FALSE
39064|"basing itself on the principle of multeity and mere numbers."|FALSE
39064|"Assemblies of Estates have been wrongly designated as the _legislative"|FALSE
39064|"power_, so far as they form only one branch of that power,—a branch in"|FALSE
39064|"which the special government-officials have an _ex officio_ share, while"|FALSE
39064|"the sovereign power has the privilege of final decision. In a civilised"|FALSE
39064|"state moreover legislation can only be a further modification of existing"|FALSE
39064|"law, and so-called new laws can only deal with minutiae of detail and"|FALSE
39064|"particularities (cf. § 529, note), the main drift of which has been"|FALSE
39064|"already prepared or preliminarily settled by the practice of the"|FALSE
39064|"law-courts. The so-called _financial law_, in so far as it requires the"|FALSE
39064|"assent of the estates, is really a government affair: it is only"|FALSE
39064|"improperly called a law, in the general sense of embracing a wide, indeed"|FALSE
39064|"the whole, range of the external means of government. The finances deal"|FALSE
39064|"with what in their nature are only particular needs, ever newly recurring,"|FALSE
39064|"even if they touch on the sum total of such needs. If the main part of the"|FALSE
39064|"requirement were—as it very likely is—regarded as permanent, the provision"|FALSE
39064|"for it would have more the nature of a law: but to be a law, it would have"|FALSE
39064|"to be made once for all, and not be made yearly, or every few years,"|FALSE
39064|"afresh. The part which varies according to time and circumstances concerns"|FALSE
39064|"in reality the smallest part of the amount, and the provisions with regard"|FALSE
39064|"to it have even less the character of a law: and yet it is and may be only"|FALSE
39064|"this slight variable part which is matter of dispute, and can be subjected"|FALSE
39064|"to a varying yearly estimate. It is this last then which falsely bears the"|FALSE
39064|"high-sounding name of the “_Grant_” of the _Budget_, i.e. of the whole of"|FALSE
39064|"the finances. A law for one year and made each year has even to the plain"|FALSE
39064|"man something palpably absurd: for he distinguishes the essential and"|FALSE
39064|"developed universal, as content of a true law, from the reflectional"|FALSE
39064|"universality which only externally embraces what in its nature is many. To"|FALSE
39064|"give the name of a law to the annual fixing of financial requirements only"|FALSE
39064|"serves—with the presupposed separation of legislative from executive—to"|FALSE
39064|"keep up the illusion of that separation having real existence, and to"|FALSE
39064|"conceal the fact that the legislative power, when it makes a decree about"|FALSE
39064|"finance, is really engaged with strict executive business. But the"|FALSE
39064|"importance attached to the power of from time to time granting “supply,”"|FALSE
39064|"on the ground that the assembly of estates possesses in it a _check_ on"|FALSE
39064|"the government, and thus a guarantee against injustice and violence,—this"|FALSE
39064|"importance is in one way rather plausible than real. The financial"|FALSE
39064|"measures necessary for the state’s subsistence cannot be made conditional"|FALSE
39064|"on any other circumstances, nor can the state’s subsistence be put yearly"|FALSE
39064|"in doubt. It would be a parallel absurdity if the government were e.g. to"|FALSE
39064|"grant and arrange the judicial institutions always for a limited time"|FALSE
39064|"merely; and thus, by the threat of suspending the activity of such an"|FALSE
39064|"institution and the fear of a consequent state of brigandage, reserve for"|FALSE
39064|"itself a means of coercing private individuals. Then again, the pictures"|FALSE
39064|"of a condition of affairs, in which it might be useful and necessary to"|FALSE
39064|"have in hand means of compulsion, are partly based on the false conception"|FALSE
39064|"of a contract between rulers and ruled, and partly presuppose the"|FALSE
39064|"possibility of such a divergence in spirit between these two parties as"|FALSE
39064|"would make constitution and government quite out of the question. If we"|FALSE
39064|"suppose the empty possibility of getting _help_ by such compulsive means"|FALSE
39064|"brought into existence, such help would rather be the derangement and"|FALSE
39064|"dissolution of the state, in which there would no longer be a government,"|FALSE
