39064|"§ 548. As the mind of a special nation is actual and its liberty is under"|FALSE
39064|"natural conditions, it admits on this nature-side the influence of"|FALSE
39064|"geographical and climatic qualities. It is in time; and as regards its"|FALSE
39064|"range and scope, has essentially a _particular_ principle on the lines of"|FALSE
39064|"which it must run through a development of its consciousness and its"|FALSE
39064|"actuality. It has, in short, a history of its own. But as a restricted"|FALSE
39064|"mind its independence is something secondary; it passes into universal"|FALSE
39064|"world-history, the events of which exhibit the dialectic of the several"|FALSE
39064|"national minds,—the judgment of the world."|FALSE
39064|"§ 549. This movement is the path of liberation for the spiritual"|FALSE
39064|"substance, the deed by which the absolute final aim of the world is"|FALSE
39064|"realised in it, and the merely implicit mind achieves consciousness and"|FALSE
39064|"self-consciousness. It is thus the revelation and actuality of its"|FALSE
39064|"essential and completed essence, whereby it becomes to the outward eye a"|FALSE
39064|"universal spirit—a world-mind. As this development is in time and in real"|FALSE
39064|"existence, as it is a history, its several stages and steps are the"|FALSE
39064|"national minds, each of which, as single and endued by nature with a"|FALSE
39064|"specific character, is appointed to occupy only one grade, and accomplish"|FALSE
39064|"one task in the whole deed."|FALSE
39064|"The presupposition that history has an essential and actual end, from the"|FALSE
39064|"principles of which certain characteristic results logically flow, is"|FALSE
39064|"called an _a priori_ view of it, and philosophy is reproached with _a"|FALSE
39064|"priori_ history-writing. On this point, and on history-writing in general,"|FALSE
39064|"this note must go into further detail. That history, and above all"|FALSE
39064|"universal history, is founded on an essential and actual aim, which"|FALSE
39064|"actually is and will be realised in it—the plan of Providence; that, in"|FALSE
39064|"short, there is Reason in history, must be decided on strictly"|FALSE
39064|"philosophical ground, and thus shown to be essentially and in fact"|FALSE
39064|"necessary. To presuppose such aim is blameworthy only when the assumed"|FALSE
39064|"conceptions or thoughts are arbitrarily adopted, and when a determined"|FALSE
39064|"attempt is made to force events and actions into conformity with such"|FALSE
39064|"conceptions. For such _a priori_ methods of treatment at the present day,"|FALSE
39064|"however, those are chiefly to blame who profess to be purely historical,"|FALSE
39064|"and who at the same time take opportunity expressly to raise their voice"|FALSE
39064|"against the habit of philosophising, first in general, and then in"|FALSE
39064|"history. Philosophy is to them a troublesome neighbour: for it is an enemy"|FALSE
39064|"of all arbitrariness and hasty suggestions. Such _a priori_"|FALSE
39064|"history-writing has sometimes burst out in quarters where one would least"|FALSE
39064|"have expected it, especially on the philological side, and in Germany more"|FALSE
39064|"than in France and England, where the art of historical writing has gone"|FALSE
39064|"through a process of purification to a firmer and maturer character."|FALSE
39064|"Fictions, like that of a primitive age and its primitive people, possessed"|FALSE
39064|"from the first of the true knowledge of God and all the sciences,—of"|FALSE
39064|"sacerdotal races,—and, when we come to minutiae, of a Roman epic, supposed"|FALSE
39064|"to be the source of the legends which pass current for the history of"|FALSE
39064|"ancient Rome, &c., have taken the place of the pragmatising which detected"|FALSE
39064|"psychological motives and associations. There is a wide circle of persons"|FALSE
39064|"who seem to consider it incumbent on a _learned_ and _ingenious_ historian"|FALSE
39064|"drawing from the original sources to concoct such baseless fancies, and"|FALSE
39064|"form bold combinations of them from a learned rubbish-heap of"|FALSE
39064|"out-of-the-way and trivial facts, in defiance of the best-accredited"|FALSE
39064|"history."|FALSE
39064|"Setting aside this subjective treatment of history, we find what is"|FALSE
39064|"properly the opposite view forbidding us to import into history an"|FALSE
39064|"_objective purpose_. This is after all synonymous with what _seems_ to be"|FALSE
39064|"the still more legitimate demand that the historian should proceed with"|FALSE
39064|"_impartiality_. This is a requirement often and especially made on the"|FALSE
39064|"_history of philosophy_: where it is insisted there should be no"|FALSE
39064|"prepossession in favour of an idea or opinion, just as a judge should have"|FALSE
39064|"no special sympathy for one of the contending parties. In the case of the"|FALSE
39064|"judge it is at the same time assumed that he would administer his office"|FALSE
39064|"ill and foolishly, if he had not an interest, and an exclusive interest in"|FALSE
39064|"justice, if he had not that for his aim and one sole aim, or if he"|FALSE
39064|"declined to judge at all. This requirement which we may make upon the"|FALSE
39064|"judge may be called _partiality_ for justice; and there is no difficulty"|FALSE
39064|"here in distinguishing it from _subjective_ partiality. But in speaking of"|FALSE
39064|"the impartiality required from the historian, this self-satisfied insipid"|FALSE
39064|"chatter lets the distinction disappear, and rejects both kinds of"|FALSE
39064|"interest. It demands that the historian shall bring with him no definite"|FALSE
39064|"aim and view by which he may sort out, state and criticise events, but"|FALSE
39064|"shall narrate them exactly in the casual mode he finds them, in their"|FALSE
39064|"incoherent and unintelligent particularity. Now it is at least admitted"|FALSE
39064|"that a history must have an object, e.g. Rome and its fortunes, or the"|FALSE
39064|"Decline of the grandeur of the Roman empire. But little reflection is"|FALSE
39064|"needed to discover that this is the presupposed end which lies at the"|FALSE
39064|"basis of the events themselves, as of the critical examination into their"|FALSE
39064|"comparative importance, i.e. their nearer or more remote relation to it. A"|FALSE
39064|"history without such aim and such criticism would be only an imbecile"|FALSE
39064|"mental divagation, not as good as a fairy tale, for even children expect a"|FALSE
39064|"_motif_ in their stories, a purpose at least dimly surmiseable with which"|FALSE
39064|"events and actions are put in relation."|FALSE
39064|"In the existence of a _nation_ the substantial aim is to be a state and"|FALSE
39064|"preserve itself as such. A nation with no state formation, (a _mere"|FALSE
39064|"nation_), has strictly speaking no history,—like the nations which existed"|FALSE
39064|"before the rise of states and others which still exist in a condition of"|FALSE
39064|"savagery. What happens to a nation, and takes place within it, has its"|FALSE
39064|"essential significance in relation to the state: whereas the mere"|FALSE
39064|"particularities of individuals are at the greatest distance from the true"|FALSE
39064|"object of history. It is true that the general spirit of an age leaves its"|FALSE
39064|"imprint in the character of its celebrated individuals, and even their"|FALSE
39064|"particularities are but the very distant and the dim media through which"|FALSE
39064|"the collective light still plays in fainter colours. Ay, even such"|FALSE
39064|"singularities as a petty occurrence, a word, express not a subjective"|FALSE
39064|"particularity, but an age, a nation, a civilisation, in striking"|FALSE
39064|"portraiture and brevity; and to select such trifles shows the hand of a"|FALSE
39064|"historian of genius. But, on the other hand, the main mass of"|FALSE
39064|"singularities is a futile and useless mass, by the painstaking"|FALSE
39064|"accumulation of which the objects of real historical value are overwhelmed"|FALSE
39064|"and obscured. The essential characteristic of the spirit and its age is"|FALSE
39064|"always contained in the great events. It was a correct instinct which"|FALSE
39064|"sought to banish such portraiture of the particular and the gleaning of"|FALSE
39064|"insignificant traits, into the _Novel_ (as in the celebrated romances of"|FALSE
39064|"Walter Scott, &c.). Where the picture presents an unessential aspect of"|FALSE
39064|"life it is certainly in good taste to conjoin it with an unessential"|FALSE
39064|"material, such as the romance takes from private events and subjective"|FALSE
39064|"passions. But to take the individual pettinesses of an age and of the"|FALSE
39064|"persons in it, and, in the interest of so-called truth, weave them into"|FALSE
39064|"the picture of general interests, is not only against taste and judgment,"|FALSE
39064|"but violates the principles of objective truth. The only truth for mind is"|FALSE
39064|"the substantial and underlying essence, and not the trivialities of"|FALSE
39064|"external existence and contingency. It is therefore completely indifferent"|FALSE
39064|"whether such insignificancies are duly vouched for by documents, or, as in"|FALSE
39064|"the romance, invented to suit the character and ascribed to this or that"|FALSE
39064|"name and circumstances."|FALSE
39064|"The point of interest of _Biography_—to say a word on that here—appears to"|FALSE
39064|"run directly counter to any universal scope and aim. But biography too has"|FALSE
39064|"for its background the historical world, with which the individual is"|FALSE
39064|"intimately bound up: even purely personal originality, the freak of"|FALSE
39064|"humour, &c. suggests by allusion that central reality and has its interest"|FALSE
39064|"heightened by the suggestion. The mere play of sentiment, on the contrary,"|FALSE
39064|"has another ground and interest than history."|FALSE
39064|"The requirement of impartiality addressed to the history of philosophy"|FALSE
39064|"(and also, we may add, to the history of religion, first in general, and"|FALSE
39064|"secondly, to church history) generally implies an even more decided bar"|FALSE
39064|"against presupposition of any objective aim. As the State was already"|FALSE
39064|"called the point to which in political history criticism had to refer all"|FALSE
39064|"events, so here the “_Truth_” must be the object to which the several"|FALSE
39064|"deeds and events of the spirit would have to be referred. What is actually"|FALSE
39064|"done is rather to make the contrary presupposition. Histories with such an"|FALSE
39064|"object as religion or philosophy are understood to have only subjective"|FALSE
39064|"aims for their theme, i.e. only opinions and mere ideas, not an essential"|FALSE
39064|"and realised object like the truth. And that with the mere excuse that"|FALSE
39064|"there is no truth. On this assumption the sympathy with truth appears as"|FALSE
39064|"only a partiality of the usual sort, a partiality for opinion and mere"|FALSE
39064|"ideas, which all alike have no stuff in them, and are all treated as"|FALSE
39064|"indifferent. In that way historical truth means but correctness—an"|FALSE
39064|"accurate report of externals, without critical treatment save as regards"|FALSE
39064|"this correctness—admitting, in this case, only qualitative and"|FALSE
39064|"quantitative judgments, no judgments of necessity or notion (cf. notes to"|FALSE
39064|"§§ 172 and 175). But, really, if Rome or the German empire, &c. are an"|FALSE
39064|"actual and genuine object of political history, and the aim to which the"|FALSE
39064|"phenomena are to be related and by which they are to be judged; then in"|FALSE
39064|"universal history the genuine spirit, the consciousness of it and of its"|FALSE
39064|"essence, is even in a higher degree a true and actual object and theme,"|FALSE
39064|"and an aim to which all other phenomena are essentially and actually"|FALSE
39064|"subservient. Only therefore through their relationship to it, i.e. through"|FALSE
39064|"the judgment in which they are subsumed under it, while it inheres in"|FALSE
39064|"them, have they their value and even their existence. It is the spirit"|FALSE
39064|"which not merely broods _over_ history as over the waters, but lives in it"|FALSE
39064|"and is alone its principle of movement: and in the path of that spirit,"|FALSE
39064|"liberty, i.e. a development determined by the notion of spirit, is the"|FALSE
39064|"guiding principle and only its notion its final aim, i.e. truth. For"|FALSE
39064|"Spirit is consciousness. Such a doctrine—or in other words that Reason is"|FALSE
39064|"in history—will be partly at least a plausible faith, partly it is a"|FALSE
39064|"cognition of philosophy."|FALSE
39064|"§ 550. This liberation of mind, in which it proceeds to come to itself and"|FALSE
39064|"to realise its truth, and the business of so doing, is the supreme right,"|FALSE
39064|"the absolute Law. The self-consciousness of a particular nation is a"|FALSE
39064|"vehicle for the contemporary development of the collective spirit in its"|FALSE
39064|"actual existence: it is the objective actuality in which that spirit for"|FALSE
39064|"the time invests its will. Against this absolute will the other particular"|FALSE
