39064|"ministrant to its revelation and the vessels of its honour."|FALSE
39064|"The strictly technical aspects of the Mind’s elevation to God have been"|FALSE
39064|"spoken of in the Introduction to the Logic (cf. especially § 51, note). As"|FALSE
39064|"regards the starting-point of that elevation, Kant has on the whole"|FALSE
39064|"adopted the most correct, when he treats belief in God as proceeding from"|FALSE
39064|"the practical Reason. For that starting-point contains the material or"|FALSE
39064|"content which constitutes the content of the notion of God. But the true"|FALSE
39064|"concrete material is neither Being (as in the cosmological) nor mere"|FALSE
39064|"action by design (as in the physico-theological proof) but the Mind, the"|FALSE
39064|"absolute characteristic and function of which is effective reason, i.e."|FALSE
39064|"the self-determining and self-realising notion itself,—Liberty. That the"|FALSE
39064|"elevation of subjective mind to God which these considerations give is by"|FALSE
39064|"Kant again deposed to a _postulate_—a mere “ought”—is the peculiar"|FALSE
39064|"perversity, formerly noticed, of calmly and simply reinstating as true and"|FALSE
39064|"valid that very antithesis of finitude, the supersession of which into"|FALSE
39064|"truth is the essence of that elevation."|FALSE
39064|"As regards the “mediation” which, as it has been already shown (§ 192, cf."|FALSE
39064|"§ 204 note), that elevation to God really involves, the point specially"|FALSE
39064|"calling for note is the “moment” of negation through which the essential"|FALSE
39064|"content of the starting-point is purged of its finitude so as to come"|FALSE
39064|"forth free. This factor, abstract in the formal treatment of logic, now"|FALSE
39064|"gets its most concrete interpretation. The finite, from which the start is"|FALSE
39064|"now made, is the real ethical self-consciousness. The negation through"|FALSE
39064|"which that consciousness raises its spirit to its truth, is the"|FALSE
39064|"purification, _actually_ accomplished in the ethical world, whereby its"|FALSE
39064|"conscience is purged of subjective opinion and its will freed from the"|FALSE
39064|"selfishness of desire. Genuine religion and genuine religiosity only issue"|FALSE
39064|"from the moral life: religion is that life rising to think, i.e. becoming"|FALSE
39064|"aware of the free universality of its concrete essence. Only from the"|FALSE
39064|"moral life and by the moral life is the Idea of God seen to be free"|FALSE
39064|"spirit: outside the ethical spirit therefore it is vain to seek for true"|FALSE
39064|"religion and religiosity."|FALSE
39064|"But—as is the case with all speculative process—this development of one"|FALSE
39064|"thing out of another means that what appears as sequel and derivative is"|FALSE
39064|"rather the absolute _prius_ of what it appears to be mediated by, and what"|FALSE
39064|"is here in mind known as its truth."|FALSE
39064|"Here then is the place to go more deeply into the reciprocal relations"|FALSE
39064|"between the state and religion, and in doing so to elucidate the"|FALSE
39064|"terminology which is familiar and current on the topic. It is evident and"|FALSE
39064|"apparent from what has preceded that moral life is the state retracted"|FALSE
39064|"into its inner heart and substance, while the state is the organisation"|FALSE
39064|"and actualisation of moral life; and that religion is the very substance"|FALSE
39064|"of the moral life itself and of the state. At this rate, the state rests"|FALSE
39064|"on the ethical sentiment, and that on the religious. If religion then is"|FALSE
39064|"the consciousness of “absolute”_ truth_, then whatever is to rank as right"|FALSE
39064|"and justice, as law and duty, i.e. as _true_ in the world of free will,"|FALSE
39064|"can be so esteemed only as it is participant in that truth, as it is"|FALSE
39064|"subsumed under it and is its sequel. But if the truly moral life is to be"|FALSE
39064|"a sequel of religion, then perforce religion must have the _genuine_"|FALSE
39064|"content; i.e. the idea of God it knows must be the true and real. The"|FALSE
39064|"ethical life is the divine spirit as indwelling in self-consciousness, as"|FALSE
39064|"it is actually present in a nation and its individual members. This"|FALSE
39064|"self-consciousness retiring upon itself out of its empirical actuality and"|FALSE
39064|"bringing its truth to consciousness, has in its _faith_ and in its"|FALSE
39064|"_conscience_ only what it has consciously secured in its spiritual"|FALSE
39064|"actuality. The two are inseparable: there cannot be two kinds of"|FALSE
39064|"conscience, one religious and another ethical, differing from the former"|FALSE
39064|"in body and value of truth. But in point of form, i.e. for thought and"|FALSE
39064|"knowledge—(and religion and ethical life belong to intelligence and are a"|FALSE
39064|"thinking and knowing)—the body of religious truth, as the pure"|FALSE
39064|"self-subsisting and therefore supreme truth, exercises a sanction over the"|FALSE
39064|"moral life which lies in empirical actuality. Thus for self-consciousness"|FALSE
39064|"religion is the “basis” of moral life and of the state. It has been the"|FALSE
39064|"monstrous blunder of our times to try to look upon these inseparables as"|FALSE
39064|"separable from one another, and even as mutually indifferent. The view"|FALSE
39064|"taken of the relationship of religion and the state has been that, whereas"|FALSE
39064|"the state had an independent existence of its own, springing from some"|FALSE
39064|"force and power, religion was a later addition, something desirable"|FALSE
39064|"perhaps for strengthening the political bulwarks, but purely subjective in"|FALSE
39064|"individuals:—or it may be, religion is treated as something without effect"|FALSE
39064|"on the moral life of the state, i.e. its reasonable law and constitution"|FALSE
39064|"which are based on a ground of their own."|FALSE
39064|"As the inseparability of the two sides has been indicated, it may be worth"|FALSE
39064|"while to note the separation as it appears on the side of religion. It is"|FALSE
39064|"primarily a point of form: the attitude which self-consciousness takes to"|FALSE
39064|"the body of truth. So long as this body of truth is the very substance or"|FALSE
39064|"indwelling spirit of self-consciousness in its actuality, then"|FALSE
39064|"self-consciousness in this content has the certainty of itself and is"|FALSE
39064|"free. But if this present self-consciousness is lacking, then there may be"|FALSE
39064|"created, in point of form, a condition of spiritual slavery, even though"|FALSE
39064|"the _implicit_ content of religion is absolute spirit. This great"|FALSE
39064|"difference (to cite a specific case) comes out within the Christian"|FALSE
39064|"religion itself, even though here it is not the nature-element in which"|FALSE
39064|"the idea of God is embodied, and though nothing of the sort even enters as"|FALSE
39064|"a factor into its central dogma and sole theme of a God who is known in"|FALSE
39064|"spirit and in truth. And yet in Catholicism this spirit of all truth is in"|FALSE
39064|"actuality set in rigid opposition to the self-conscious spirit. And, first"|FALSE
39064|"of all, God is in the “host” presented to religious adoration as an"|FALSE
39064|"_external thing_. (In the Lutheran Church, on the contrary, the host as"|FALSE
39064|"such is not at first consecrated, but in the moment of enjoyment, i.e. in"|FALSE
39064|"the annihilation of its externality, and in the act of faith, i.e. in the"|FALSE
39064|"free self-certain spirit: only then is it consecrated and exalted to be"|FALSE
39064|"present God.) From that first and supreme status of externalisation flows"|FALSE
39064|"every other phase of externality,—of bondage, non-spirituality, and"|FALSE
39064|"superstition. It leads to a laity, receiving its knowledge of divine"|FALSE
39064|"truth, as well as the direction of its will and conscience from without"|FALSE
39064|"and from another order—which order again does not get possession of that"|FALSE
39064|"knowledge in a spiritual way only, but to that end essentially requires an"|FALSE
39064|"external consecration. It leads to the non-spiritual style of"|FALSE
39064|"praying—partly as mere moving of the lips, partly in the way that the"|FALSE
39064|"subject foregoes his right of directly addressing God, and prays others to"|FALSE
39064|"pray—addressing his devotion to miracle-working images, even to bones, and"|FALSE
39064|"expecting miracles from them. It leads, generally, to justification by"|FALSE
39064|"external works, a merit which is supposed to be gained by acts, and even"|FALSE
39064|"to be capable of being transferred to others. All this binds the spirit"|FALSE
39064|"under an externalism by which the very meaning of spirit is perverted and"|FALSE
39064|"misconceived at its source, and law and justice, morality and conscience,"|FALSE
39064|"responsibility and duty are corrupted at their root."|FALSE
39064|"Along with this principle of spiritual bondage, and these applications of"|FALSE
39064|"it in the religious life, there can only go in the legislative and"|FALSE
39064|"constitutional system a legal and moral bondage, and a state of"|FALSE
39064|"lawlessness and immorality in political life. Catholicism has been loudly"|FALSE
39064|"praised and is still often praised—logically enough—as the one religion"|FALSE
39064|"which secures the stability of governments. But in reality this applies"|FALSE
39064|"only to governments which are bound up with institutions founded on the"|FALSE
39064|"bondage of the spirit (of that spirit which should have legal and moral"|FALSE
39064|"liberty), i.e. with institutions that embody injustice and with a morally"|FALSE
39064|"corrupt and barbaric state of society. But these governments are not aware"|FALSE
39064|"that in fanaticism they have a terrible power, which does not rise in"|FALSE
39064|"hostility against them, only so long as and only on condition that they"|FALSE
39064|"remain sunk in the thraldom of injustice and immorality. But in mind there"|FALSE
39064|"is a very different power available against that externalism and"|FALSE
