39064|"The perception had dawned upon Plato with great clearness of the gulf"|FALSE
39064|"which in his day had commenced to divide the established religion and the"|FALSE
39064|"political constitution, on one hand, from those deeper requirements which,"|FALSE
39064|"on the other hand, were made upon religion and politics by liberty which"|FALSE
39064|"had learnt to recognise its inner life. Plato gets hold of the thought"|FALSE
39064|"that a genuine constitution and a sound political life have their deeper"|FALSE
39064|"foundation on the Idea,—on the essentially and actually universal and"|FALSE
39064|"genuine principles of eternal righteousness. Now to see and ascertain what"|FALSE
39064|"these are is certainly the function and the business of _philosophy_. It"|FALSE
39064|"is from this point of view that Plato breaks out into the celebrated or"|FALSE
39064|"notorious passage where he makes Socrates emphatically state that"|FALSE
39064|"philosophy and political power must coincide, that the Idea must be"|FALSE
39064|"regent, if the distress of nations is to see its end. What Plato thus"|FALSE
39064|"definitely set before his mind was that the Idea—which implicitly indeed"|FALSE
39064|"is the free self-determining thought—could not get into consciousness save"|FALSE
39064|"only in the form of a thought; that the substance of the thought could"|FALSE
39064|"only be true when set forth as a universal, and as such brought to"|FALSE
39064|"consciousness under its most abstract form."|FALSE
39064|"To compare the Platonic standpoint in all its definiteness with the point"|FALSE
39064|"of view from which the relationship of state and religion is here"|FALSE
39064|"regarded, the notional differences on which everything turns must be"|FALSE
39064|"recalled to mind. The first of these is that in natural things their"|FALSE
39064|"substance or genus is different from their existence in which that"|FALSE
39064|"substance is as subject: further that this subjective existence of the"|FALSE
39064|"genus is distinct from that which it gets, when specially set in relief as"|FALSE
39064|"genus, or, to put it simply, as the universal in a mental concept or idea."|FALSE
39064|"This additional “individuality”—the soil on which the universal and"|FALSE
39064|"underlying principle _freely_ and expressly exists,—is the intellectual"|FALSE
39064|"and thinking _self_. In the case of _natural_ things their truth and"|FALSE
39064|"reality does not get the form of universality and essentiality through"|FALSE
39064|"themselves, and their “individuality” is not itself the form: the form is"|FALSE
39064|"only found in subjective thinking, which in philosophy gives that"|FALSE
39064|"universal truth and reality an existence of its own. In man’s case it is"|FALSE
39064|"otherwise: his truth and reality is the free mind itself, and it comes to"|FALSE
39064|"existence in his self-consciousness. This absolute nucleus of man—mind"|FALSE
39064|"intrinsically concrete—is just this—to have the form (to have thinking)"|FALSE
39064|"itself for a content. To the height of the thinking consciousness of this"|FALSE
39064|"principle Aristotle ascended in his notion of the entelechy of thought,"|FALSE
39064|"(which is νοῆσις τῆς νοήσεως), thus surmounting the Platonic Idea (the"|FALSE
39064|"genus, or essential being). But thought always—and that on account of this"|FALSE
39064|"very principle—contains the immediate self-subsistence of subjectivity no"|FALSE
39064|"less than it contains universality; the genuine Idea of the intrinsically"|FALSE
39064|"concrete mind is just as essentially under the one of its terms"|FALSE
39064|"(subjective consciousness) as under the other (universality): and in the"|FALSE
39064|"one as in the other it is the same substantial content. Under the"|FALSE
39064|"subjective form, however, fall feeling, intuition, pictorial"|FALSE
39064|"representation: and it is in fact necessary that in point of time the"|FALSE
39064|"consciousness of the absolute Idea should be first reached and apprehended"|FALSE
39064|"in this form: in other words, it must exist in its immediate reality as"|FALSE
39064|"religion, earlier than it does as philosophy. Philosophy is a later"|FALSE
39064|"development from this basis (just as Greek philosophy itself is later than"|FALSE
39064|"Greek religion), and in fact reaches its completion by catching and"|FALSE
39064|"comprehending in all its definite essentiality that principle of spirit"|FALSE
39064|"which first manifests itself in religion. But Greek philosophy could set"|FALSE
39064|"itself up only in opposition to Greek religion: the unity of thought and"|FALSE
39064|"the substantiality of the Idea could take up none but a hostile attitude"|FALSE
39064|"to an imaginative polytheism, and to the gladsome and frivolous humours of"|FALSE
39064|"its poetic creations. The _form_ in its infinite truth, the _subjectivity_"|FALSE
39064|"of mind, broke forth at first only as a subjective free _thinking_, which"|FALSE
39064|"was not yet identical with the _substantiality_ itself,—and thus this"|FALSE
39064|"underlying principle was not yet apprehended as _absolute mind_. Thus"|FALSE
39064|"religion might appear as first purified only through philosophy,—through"|FALSE
39064|"pure self-existent thought: but the form pervading this underlying"|FALSE
39064|"principle—the form which philosophy attacked—was that creative"|FALSE
39064|"imagination."|FALSE
39064|"Political power, which is developed similarly, but earlier than"|FALSE
39064|"philosophy, from religion, exhibits the onesidedness, which in the actual"|FALSE
39064|"world may infect its _implicitly_ true Idea, as demoralisation. Plato, in"|FALSE
39064|"common with all his thinking contemporaries, perceived this demoralisation"|FALSE
39064|"of democracy and the defectiveness even of its principle; he set in relief"|FALSE
39064|"accordingly the underlying principle of the state, but could not work into"|FALSE
