39064|"Here might seem to be the place to treat in a definite exposition of the"|FALSE
39064|"reciprocal relations of philosophy and religion. The whole question turns"|FALSE
39064|"entirely on the difference of the forms of speculative thought from the"|FALSE
39064|"forms of mental representation and “reflecting” intellect. But it is the"|FALSE
39064|"whole cycle of philosophy, and of logic in particular, which has not"|FALSE
39064|"merely taught and made known this difference, but also criticised it, or"|FALSE
39064|"rather has let its nature develop and judge itself by these very"|FALSE
39064|"categories. It is only by an insight into the value of these forms that"|FALSE
39064|"the true and needful conviction can be gained, that the content of"|FALSE
39064|"religion and philosophy is the same,—leaving out, of course, the further"|FALSE
39064|"details of external nature and finite mind which fall outside the range of"|FALSE
39064|"religion. But religion is the truth _for all men_: faith rests on the"|FALSE
39064|"witness of the spirit, which as witnessing is the spirit in man. This"|FALSE
39064|"witness—the underlying essence in all humanity—takes, when driven to"|FALSE
39064|"expound itself, its first definite form under those acquired habits of"|FALSE
39064|"thought which his secular consciousness and intellect otherwise employs."|FALSE
39064|"In this way the truth becomes liable to the terms and conditions of"|FALSE
39064|"finitude in general. This does not prevent the spirit, even in employing"|FALSE
39064|"sensuous ideas and finite categories of thought, from retaining its"|FALSE
39064|"content (which as religion is essentially speculative,) with a tenacity"|FALSE
39064|"which does violence to them, and acts _inconsistently_ towards them. By"|FALSE
39064|"this inconsistency it corrects their defects. Nothing easier therefore for"|FALSE
