39064|"inexhaustible essence, than which there is nothing higher, think me who am"|FALSE
39064|"unperceived to have become perceptible.”"|FALSE
39064|"This “All,” which Krishna calls himself, is not, any more than the Eleatic"|FALSE
39064|"One, and the Spinozan Substance, the Every-thing. This every-thing,"|FALSE
39064|"rather, the infinitely-manifold sensuous manifold of the finite is in all"|FALSE
39064|"these pictures, but defined as the “accidental,” without essential being"|FALSE
39064|"of its very own, but having its truth in the substance, the One which, as"|FALSE
39064|"different from that accidental, is alone the divine and God. Hindooism"|FALSE
39064|"however has the higher conception of Brahma, the pure unity of thought in"|FALSE
39064|"itself, where the empirical everything of the world, as also those"|FALSE
39064|"proximate substantialities, called Gods, vanish. On that account"|FALSE
39064|"Colebrooke and many others have described the Hindoo religion as at bottom"|FALSE
39064|"a Monotheism. That this description is not incorrect is clear from these"|FALSE
39064|"short citations. But so little concrete is this divine unity—spiritual as"|FALSE
39064|"its idea of God is—so powerless its grip, so to speak—that Hindooism, with"|FALSE
39064|"a monstrous inconsistency, is also the maddest of polytheisms. But the"|FALSE
39064|"idolatry of the wretched Hindoo, when he adores the ape, or other"|FALSE
39064|"creature, is still a long way from that wretched fancy of a Pantheism, to"|FALSE
39064|"which everything is God, and God everything. Hindoo monotheism moreover is"|FALSE
39064|"itself an example how little comes of mere monotheism, if the Idea of God"|FALSE
39064|"is not deeply determinate in itself. For that unity, if it be"|FALSE
39064|"intrinsically abstract and therefore empty, tends of itself to let"|FALSE
39064|"whatever is concrete, outside it—be it as a lot of Gods or as secular,"|FALSE
39064|"empirical individuals—keep its independence. That pantheism indeed—on the"|FALSE
39064|"shallow conception of it—might with a show of logic as well be called a"|FALSE
39064|"monotheism: for if God, as it says, is identical with the world, then as"|FALSE
39064|"there is only one world there would be in that pantheism only one God."|FALSE
39064|"Perhaps the empty numerical unity must be predicated of the world: but"|FALSE
39064|"such abstract predication of it has no further special interest; on the"|FALSE
39064|"contrary, a mere numerical unity just means that its _content_ is an"|FALSE
39064|"infinite multeity and variety of finitudes. But it is that delusion with"|FALSE
39064|"the empty unity, which alone makes possible and induces the wrong idea of"|FALSE
39064|"pantheism. It is only the picture—floating in the indefinite blue—of the"|FALSE
39064|"world as _one thing_, _the all_, that could ever be considered capable of"|FALSE
39064|"combining with God: only on that assumption could philosophy be supposed"|FALSE
39064|"to teach that God is the world: for if the world were taken as it is, as"|FALSE
39064|"everything, as the endless lot of empirical existence, then it would"|FALSE
39064|"hardly have been even held possible to suppose a pantheism which asserted"|FALSE
39064|"of such stuff that it is God."|FALSE
39064|"But to go back again to the question of fact. If we want to see the"|FALSE
39064|"consciousness of the One—not as with the Hindoos split between the"|FALSE
39064|"featureless unity of abstract thought, on one hand, and on the other, the"|FALSE
39064|"long-winded weary story of its particular detail, but—in its finest purity"|FALSE
39064|"and sublimity, we must consult the Mohammedans. If e.g. in the excellent"|FALSE
39064|"Jelaleddin-Rumi in particular, we find the unity of the soul with the One"|FALSE
39064|"set forth, and that unity described as love, this spiritual unity is an"|FALSE
39064|"exaltation above the finite and vulgar, a transfiguration of the natural"|FALSE
39064|"and the spiritual, in which the externalism and transitoriness of"|FALSE
39064|"immediate nature, and of empirical secular spirit, is discarded and"|FALSE
39064|"absorbed(174)."|FALSE
39064|"I refrain from accumulating further examples of the religious and poetic"|FALSE
39064|"conceptions which it is customary to call pantheistic. Of the philosophies"|FALSE
39064|"to which that name is given, the Eleatic, or Spinozist, it has been"|FALSE
39064|"remarked earlier (§ 50, note) that so far are they from identifying God"|FALSE
39064|"with the world and making him finite, that in these systems this"|FALSE
39064|"“everything” has no truth, and that we should rather call them"|FALSE
39064|"monotheistic, or, in relation to the popular idea of the world, acosmical."|FALSE
39064|"They are most accurately called systems which apprehend the Absolute only"|FALSE
39064|"as substance. Of the oriental, especially the Mohammedan, modes of"|FALSE
39064|"envisaging God, we may rather say that they represent the Absolute as the"|FALSE
39064|"utterly universal genus which dwells in the species or existences, but"|FALSE
39064|"dwells so potently that these existences have no actual reality. The fault"|FALSE
39064|"of all these modes of thought and systems is that they stop short of"|FALSE
39064|"defining substance as subject and as mind."|FALSE
39064|"These systems and modes of pictorial conception originate from the one"|FALSE
39064|"need common to all philosophies and all religions of getting an idea of"|FALSE
39064|"God, and, secondly, of the relationship of God and the world. (In"|FALSE
39064|"philosophy it is specially made out that the determination of God’s nature"|FALSE
39064|"determines his relations with the world.) The “reflective” understanding"|FALSE
39064|"begins by rejecting all systems and modes of conception, which, whether"|FALSE
39064|"they spring from heart, imagination or speculation, express the"|FALSE
39064|"interconnexion of God and the world: and in order to have God pure in"|FALSE
39064|"faith or consciousness, he is as essence parted from appearance, as"|FALSE
39064|"infinite from the finite. But, after this partition, the conviction arises"|FALSE
39064|"also that the appearance has a relation to the essence, the finite to the"|FALSE
39064|"infinite, and so on: and thus arises the question of reflection as to the"|FALSE
39064|"nature of this relation. It is in the reflective form that the whole"|FALSE
39064|"difficulty of the affair lies, and that causes this relation to be called"|FALSE
39064|"incomprehensible by the agnostic. The close of philosophy is not the"|FALSE
39064|"place, even in a general exoteric discussion, to waste a word on what a"|FALSE
39064|"“notion” means. But as the view taken of this relation is closely"|FALSE
39064|"connected with the view taken of philosophy generally and with all"|FALSE
39064|"imputations against it, we may still add the remark that though philosophy"|FALSE
39064|"certainly has to do with unity in general, it is not however with abstract"|FALSE
39064|"unity, mere identity, and the empty absolute, but with concrete unity (the"|FALSE
39064|"notion), and that in its whole course it has to do with nothing else;—that"|FALSE
39064|"each step in its advance is a peculiar term or phase of this concrete"|FALSE
39064|"unity, and that the deepest and last expression of unity is the unity of"|FALSE
39064|"absolute mind itself. Would-be judges and critics of philosophy might be"|FALSE
39064|"recommended to familiarise themselves with these phases of unity and to"|FALSE
39064|"take the trouble to get acquainted with them, at least to know so much"|FALSE
39064|"that of these terms there are a great many, and that amongst them there is"|FALSE
39064|"great variety. But they show so little acquaintance with them—and still"|FALSE
39064|"less take trouble about it—that, when they hear of unity—and relation"|FALSE
39064|"_ipso facto_ implies unity—they rather stick fast at quite abstract"|FALSE
39064|"indeterminate unity, and lose sight of the chief point of interest—the"|FALSE
39064|"special mode in which the unity is qualified. Hence all they can say about"|FALSE
39064|"philosophy is that dry identity is its principle and result, and that it"|FALSE
39064|"is the system of identity. Sticking fast to the undigested thought of"|FALSE
39064|"identity, they have laid hands on, not the concrete unity, the notion and"|FALSE
39064|"content of philosophy, but rather its reverse. In the philosophical field"|FALSE
39064|"they proceed, as in the physical field the physicist; who also is well"|FALSE
39064|"aware that he has before him a variety of sensuous properties and"|FALSE
39064|"matters—or usually matters alone, (for the properties get transformed into"|FALSE
39064|"matters also for the physicist)—and that these matters (elements) _also_"|FALSE
39064|"stand in _relation_ to one another. But the question is, Of what kind is"|FALSE
39064|"this relation? Every peculiarity and the whole difference of natural"|FALSE
39064|"things, inorganic and living, depend solely on the different modes of this"|FALSE
39064|"unity. But instead of ascertaining these different modes, the ordinary"|FALSE
39064|"physicist (chemist included) takes up only one, the most external and the"|FALSE
39064|"worst, viz. _composition_, applies only it in the whole range of natural"|FALSE
39064|"structures, which he thus renders for ever inexplicable."|FALSE
39064|"The aforesaid shallow pantheism is an equally obvious inference from this"|FALSE
39064|"shallow identity. All that those who employ this invention of their own to"|FALSE
39064|"accuse philosophy gather from the study of God’s _relation_ to the world"|FALSE
39064|"is that the one, but only the one factor of this category of relation—and"|FALSE
39064|"that the factor of indeterminateness—is identity. Thereupon they stick"|FALSE
39064|"fast in this half-perception, and assert—falsely as a fact—that philosophy"|FALSE
39064|"teaches the identity of God and the world. And as in their judgment either"|FALSE
39064|"of the two,—the world as much as God—has the same solid substantiality as"|FALSE
39064|"the other, they infer that in the philosophic Idea God is _composed_ of"|FALSE
39064|"God and the world. Such then is the idea they form of pantheism, and which"|FALSE
39064|"they ascribe to philosophy. Unaccustomed in their own thinking and"|FALSE
39064|"apprehending of thoughts to go beyond such categories, they import them"|FALSE
39064|"into philosophy, where they are utterly unknown; they thus infect it with"|FALSE
39064|"the disease against which they subsequently raise an outcry. If any"|FALSE
39064|"difficulty emerge in comprehending God’s relation to the world, they at"|FALSE
39064|"once and very easily escape it by admitting that this relation contains"|FALSE
39064|"for them an inexplicable contradiction; and that hence, they must stop at"|FALSE
39064|"the vague conception of such relation, perhaps under the more familiar"|FALSE
39064|"names of, e.g. omnipresence, providence, &c. Faith in their use of the"|FALSE
39064|"term means no more than a refusal to define the conception, or to enter on"|FALSE
39064|"a closer discussion of the problem. That men and classes of untrained"|FALSE
39064|"intellect are satisfied with such indefiniteness, is what one expects; but"|FALSE
39064|"when a trained intellect and an interest for reflective study is"|FALSE
39064|"satisfied, in matters admitted to be of superior, if not even of supreme"|FALSE
39064|"interest, with indefinite ideas, it is hard to decide whether the thinker"|FALSE
39064|"is really in earnest with the subject. But if those who cling to this"|FALSE
39064|"crude “rationalism” were in earnest, e.g. with God’s omnipresence, so far"|FALSE
39064|"as to realise their faith thereon in a definite mental idea, in what"|FALSE
39064|"difficulties would they be involved by their belief in the true reality of"|FALSE
39064|"the things of sense! They would hardly like, as Epicurus does, to let God"|FALSE
39064|"dwell in the interspaces of things, i.e. in the pores of the"|FALSE
39064|"physicists,—said pores being the negative, something supposed to exist"|FALSE
39064|"_beside_ the material reality. This very “Beside” would give their"|FALSE
39064|"pantheism its spatiality,—their everything, conceived as the mutual"|FALSE
39064|"exclusion of parts in space. But in ascribing to God, in his relation to"|FALSE
39064|"the world, an action on and in the space thus filled on the world and in"|FALSE
39064|"it, they would endlessly split up the divine actuality into infinite"|FALSE
39064|"materiality. They would really thus have the misconception they call"|FALSE
39064|"pantheism or all-one-doctrine, only as the necessary sequel of their"|FALSE
39064|"misconceptions of God and the world. But to put that sort of thing, this"|FALSE
39064|"stale gossip of oneness or identity, on the shoulders of philosophy, shows"|FALSE
39064|"such recklessness about justice and truth that it can only be explained"|FALSE
39064|"through the difficulty of getting into the head thoughts and notions, i.e."|FALSE
39064|"not abstract unity, but the many-shaped modes specified. If statements as"|FALSE
39064|"to facts are put forward, and the facts in question are thoughts and"|FALSE
39064|"notions, it is indispensable to get hold of their meaning. But even the"|FALSE
39064|"fulfilment of this requirement has been rendered superfluous, now that it"|FALSE
39064|"has long been a foregone conclusion that philosophy is pantheism, a system"|FALSE
39064|"of identity, an All-one doctrine, and that the person therefore who might"|FALSE
39064|"be unaware of this fact is treated either as merely unaware of a matter of"|FALSE
39064|"common notoriety, or as prevaricating for a purpose. On account of this"|FALSE
39064|"chorus of assertions, then, I have believed myself obliged to speak at"|FALSE
39064|"more length and exoterically on the outward and inward untruth of this"|FALSE
39064|"alleged fact: for exoteric discussion is the only method available in"|FALSE
39064|"dealing with the external apprehension of notions as mere facts,—by which"|FALSE
39064|"notions are perverted into their opposite. The esoteric study of God and"|FALSE
39064|"identity, as of cognitions and notions, is philosophy itself."|FALSE
39064|"§ 574. This notion of philosophy is the self-thinking Idea, the truth"|FALSE
39064|"aware of itself (§ 236),—the logical system, but with the signification"|FALSE
39064|"that it is universality approved and certified in concrete content as in"|FALSE
39064|"its actuality. In this way the science has gone back to its beginning: its"|FALSE
39064|"result is the logical system but as a spiritual principle: out of the"|FALSE
39064|"presupposing judgment, in which the notion was only implicit and the"|FALSE
39064|"beginning an immediate,—and thus out of the _appearance_ which it had"|FALSE
39064|"there—it has risen into its pure principle and thus also into its proper"|FALSE
39064|"medium."|FALSE
39064|"§ 575. It is this appearing which originally gives the motive of the"|FALSE
39064|"further development. The first appearance is formed by the syllogism,"|FALSE
39064|"which is based on the Logical system as starting-point, with Nature for"|FALSE
39064|"the middle term which couples the Mind with it. The Logical principle"|FALSE
39064|"turns to Nature and Nature to Mind. Nature, standing between the Mind and"|FALSE
39064|"its essence, sunders itself, not indeed to extremes of finite abstraction,"|FALSE
39064|"nor itself to something away from them and independent,—which, as other"|FALSE
39064|"than they, only serves as a link between them: for the syllogism is _in"|FALSE
39064|"the Idea_ and Nature is essentially defined as a transition-point and"|FALSE
39064|"negative factor, and as implicitly the Idea. Still the mediation of the"|FALSE
39064|"notion has the external form of _transition_, and the science of Nature"|FALSE
39064|"presents itself as the course of necessity, so that it is only in the one"|FALSE
39064|"extreme that the liberty of the notion is explicit as a self-amalgamation."|FALSE
39064|"§ 576. In the second syllogism this appearance is so far superseded, that"|FALSE
39064|"that syllogism is the standpoint of the Mind itself, which—as the"|FALSE
39064|"mediating agent in the process—presupposes Nature and couples it with the"|FALSE
39064|"Logical principle. It is the syllogism where Mind reflects on itself in"|FALSE
39064|"the Idea: philosophy appears as a subjective cognition, of which liberty"|FALSE
39064|"is the aim, and which is itself the way to produce it."|FALSE
39064|"§ 577. The third syllogism is the Idea of philosophy, which has"|FALSE
39064|"self-knowing reason, the absolutely-universal, for its middle term: a"|FALSE
39064|"middle, which divides itself into Mind and Nature, making the former its"|FALSE
39064|"presupposition, as process of the Idea’s subjective activity, and the"|FALSE
39064|"latter its universal extreme, as process of the objectively and implicitly"|FALSE
39064|"existing Idea. The self-judging of the Idea into its two appearances (§§"|FALSE
39064|"575, 576) characterises both as its (the self-knowing reason’s)"|FALSE
39064|"manifestations: and in it there is a unification of the two aspects:—it is"|FALSE
39064|"the nature of the fact, the notion, which causes the movement and"|FALSE
39064|"development, yet this same movement is equally the action of cognition."|FALSE
39064|"The eternal Idea, in full fruition of its essence, eternally sets itself"|FALSE
39064|"to work, engenders and enjoys itself as absolute Mind."|FALSE
