39064|"      III."|FALSE
39064|"      I saw but One through all heaven’s starry spaces gleaming:"|FALSE
39064|"      I saw but One in all sea billows wildly streaming."|FALSE
39064|"      I looked into the heart, a waste of worlds, a sea,—"|FALSE
39064|"      I saw a thousand dreams,—yet One amid all dreaming."|FALSE
39064|"      And earth, air, water, fire, when thy decree is given,"|FALSE
39064|"      Are molten into One: against thee none hath striven."|FALSE
39064|"      There is no living heart but beats unfailingly"|FALSE
39064|"      In the one song of praise to thee, from earth and heaven."|FALSE
39064|"      V."|FALSE
39064|"      As one ray of thy light appears the noonday sun,"|FALSE
39064|"      But yet thy light and mine eternally are one."|FALSE
39064|"      As dust beneath thy feet the heaven that rolls on high:"|FALSE
39064|"      Yet only one, and one for ever, thou and I."|FALSE
39064|"      The dust may turn to heaven, and heaven to dust decay;"|FALSE
39064|"      Yet art thou one with me, and shalt be one for aye."|FALSE
39064|"      How may the words of life that fill heaven’s utmost part"|FALSE
39064|"      Rest in the narrow casket of one poor human heart?"|FALSE
39064|"      How can the sun’s own rays, a fairer gleam to fling,"|FALSE
39064|"      Hide in a lowly husk, the jewel’s covering?"|FALSE
39064|"      How may the rose-grove all its glorious bloom unfold,"|FALSE
39064|"      Drinking in mire and slime, and feeding on the mould?"|FALSE
39064|"      How can the darksome shell that sips the salt sea stream"|FALSE
39064|"      Fashion a shining pearl, the sunlight’s joyous beam?"|FALSE
39064|"      Oh, heart! should warm winds fan thee, should’st thou floods"|FALSE
39064|"      endure,"|FALSE
39064|"      One element are wind and flood; but be thou pure."|FALSE
39064|"      IX."|FALSE
39064|"      I’ll tell thee how from out the dust God moulded man,—"|FALSE
39064|"      Because the breath of Love He breathed into his clay:"|FALSE
39064|"      I’ll tell thee why the spheres their whirling paths began,—"|FALSE
39064|"      They mirror to God’s throne Love’s glory day by day:"|FALSE
39064|"      I’ll tell thee why the morning winds blow o’er the grove,—"|FALSE
39064|"      It is to bid Love’s roses bloom abundantly:"|FALSE
39064|"      I’ll tell thee why the night broods deep the earth above,—"|FALSE
39064|"      Love’s bridal tent to deck with sacred canopy:"|FALSE
39064|"      All riddles of the earth dost thou desire to prove?—"|FALSE
39064|"      To every earthly riddle is Love alone the key."|FALSE
39064|"      XV."|FALSE
39064|"      Life shrinks from Death in woe and fear,"|FALSE
39064|"      Though Death ends well Life’s bitter need:"|FALSE
39064|"      So shrinks the heart when Love draws near,"|FALSE
39064|"      As though ’twere Death in very deed:"|FALSE
39064|"      For wheresoever Love finds room,"|FALSE
39064|"      There Self, the sullen tyrant, dies."|FALSE
39064|"      So let him perish in the gloom,—"|FALSE
39064|"      Thou to the dawn of freedom rise."|FALSE
39064|"      In this poetry, which soars over all that is external and sensuous,"|FALSE
39064|"      who would recognise the prosaic ideas current about so-called"|FALSE
39064|"      pantheism—ideas which let the divine sink to the external and the"|FALSE
39064|"      sensuous? The copious extracts which Tholuck, in his work _Anthology"|FALSE
39064|"      from the Eastern Mystics_, gives us from the poems of Jelaleddin and"|FALSE
39064|"      others, are made from the very point of view now under discussion."|FALSE
39064|"      In his Introduction, Herr Tholuck proves how profoundly his soul has"|FALSE
39064|"      caught the note of mysticism; and there, too, he points out the"|FALSE
39064|"      characteristic traits of its oriental phase, in distinction from"|FALSE
39064|"      that of the West and Christendom. With all their divergence,"|FALSE
39064|"      however, they have in common the mystical character. The conjunction"|FALSE
39064|"      of Mysticism with so-called Pantheism, as he says (p. 53), implies"|FALSE
39064|"      that inward quickening of soul and spirit which inevitably tends to"|FALSE
39064|"      annihilate that external _Everything_, which Pantheism is usually"|FALSE
39064|"      held to adore. But beyond that, Herr Tholuck leaves matters standing"|FALSE
39064|"      at the usual indistinct conception of Pantheism; a profounder"|FALSE
39064|"      discussion of it would have had, for the author’s emotional"|FALSE
39064|"      Christianity, no direct interest; but we see that personally he is"|FALSE
39064|"      carried away by remarkable enthusiasm for a mysticism which, in the"|FALSE
39064|"      ordinary phrase, entirely deserves the epithet Pantheistic. Where,"|FALSE
39064|"      however, he tries philosophising (p. 12), he does not get beyond the"|FALSE
39064|"      standpoint of the “rationalist” metaphysic with its uncritical"|FALSE
39064|"      categories."|FALSE
